<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TysonCharge 1stLd-Writethru a0752 12-15 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tyson Charge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0752,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Woman Accuses Tyson Of Harassment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Tyson was ..., to ADD boxer's comments; note
contents of grafs 3-4, `Davis said ..., may be offensive to some
readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged Thursday that
heavyweight champion Mike Tyson sexually molested her in a Manhattan
disco last week, the second woman to make such a charge.
   The woman, Lori Davis, 29, of Bay Shore on Long Island said she
planned to sue Tyson for mental anguish and trauma.
   Davis said she was dancing with a male partner at Bentley's Disco
Lounge around 2 a.m. Sunday when ``Someone grabbed my behind under
my dress.
   ``I turned around and screamed, `try that again and I'll slap the
---- out of you,''' she said.
   ``Then it dawned on me that I was screaming at the heavyweight
champion of the world,'' she said.
   Tyson, in Los Angeles to announce his upcoming fight with Frank
Bruno, said, ``I don't even know this person, I don't know what
happened.''
   Davis said Tyson was standing on the dance floor with two male
companions when the incident occurred. ``He put his hands up in the
air and said ``Whoa, whoa, we have a live one here,''' Davis said.
   Tyson and his friends then moved away to another area of the
disco. Asked if her male partner confronted Tyson on the dance
floor, she replied: ``No, the man had common sense.''
   She said she was willing to put aside the incident but when she
read two days ago that another woman had charged Tyson with sexually
molesting her at Bentley's on the same night she decided to come
forward.
   Her attorney, Stuart Berg, said the lawsuit will seek $1 million
in damages for ``trauma, shock and mental anguish.''
   Berg said Davis is scheduled to be interviewed by detectives in
Manhattan to determine if any criminal complaints should be filed.
   ``I am really angry and embarrassed at the whole thing,'' said
Davis.
</TEXT>
