<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0641 12-15 1018</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Defends PLO Move; Says US Steadfastly Supports Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: DELETES 6th graf pvs bgng, `State Department,' and INSERTS 1
graf after 7th graf pvs bgng, `White House' to UPDATE with State
officials saying talks with the PLO probably will open in Tunis on
Friday afternoon</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday defended opening a
dialogue with the PLO, calling it ``just another step'' in the
Middle East peace process and saying Israel shouldn't worry about
America's commitment to its security.
   But Reagan also said he would not hesitate to ``break off
communications'' if Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation
Organization reneged on its acceptance of Israel's sovereignty or
its renunciation of terrorism as an instrument to achieve policy
objectives.
   During separate Oval Office picture-taking sessions with Turkish
Prime Minister Turgut Ozal and Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco de
Mita, the president said he decided to reverse his longstanding
opposition to contacts with the PLO on the basis of statements that
Arafat made in Geneva on Wednesday.
   When asked if he thought that Israel was justified in being upset
with his administration's move, Reagan replied: ``Well, I don't
think so, in the sense that we have made it very plain that we have
not retreated one inch from our position of guaranteeing the safety
of Israel.''
   Acting on the instructions of Secretary of State George P.
Shultz, the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert H. Pelletreau Jr.,
called the director general of the political section at the PLO's
Tunis headquarters to try to make arrangements for the talks, U.S.
officials said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters that ``at
this point, there has been no substantive response in terms of time,
place or location.''
   State Department officials later said that talks with the PLO
probably would begin in Tunis on Friday afternoon.
   On Capitol Hill, leading members of Congress gave the new opening
a wary welcome, and they joined Reagan in seeking to reassure Israel
that U.S. officials will be alert to any PLO tricks.
   ``This is good news and the right path to follow,'' said Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. ``I think we would best be very careful that the PLO
continue to show real seriousness and be wary of any decepion.''
   Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, the newly elected Senate majority
leader, welcomed the U.S. move and called it a ``significant step
toward advancing the peace process.''
   Reagan said the administration agreed to open a substantive
dialogue with the PLO after it became satisfied that Arafat had
complied with the U.S. conditions for such direct contacts.
   Asked to explain the policy reversal, the president said: ``Well,
because the words have been spoken, and the words were the words
that we have been stating were necessary.'' But he said, ``Of
course, ... the words must be matched by performance, and if they're
not, why, we're back where we started.''
   Questioned about what he would do if the PLO failed to live up to
its commitments, Reagan said, ``Well, we'd certainly break off
communications.'' He stressed that the ultimate solution in the
Middle East ``does not depend on outsiders _ or us.''
   ``Peace must be brought about by the involved nations meeting
with each other and settling their differences,'' he said.
   Asked why the United States does not recognize a Palestinian
state, Reagan said, ``... Because there is no such thing as of now.
There isn't a Palestinian state. And if you recognize someone ... as
that, it would be us declaring who was in charge there.''
   Reagan said commencing exploratory talks with the PLO was ``just
another step in what we've been trying for eight years _ to bring
about peace in the Middle East.''
   President-elect Bush told reporters he supported Reagan's
decision.
   ``I haven't spelled out any hopes about it,'' he added. ``Arafat
met the conditions of the United States and we will go forward with
a dialogue, not negotiations, but a dialogue. ... Let's see how
things evolve.''
   As for the discussions, Bush said, ``There's no game plan;
there's no five-point program.''
   Asked if he would prefer that the talks wait until his
administration starts next month, Bush replied, ``I am vice
president of the United States. I become president on Jan. 20. On
Jan. 21, I'll tell you what I want to do.''
   The U.S. announcement late Wednesday left Israel in diplomatic
isolation and came just a few hours after Bush had taken a tough
line against the PLO, declaring it failed to meet the U.S.
conditions.
   But Reagan and Shultz said that Arafat, in statements made in
Geneva about the same time that Bush was speaking, had met the U.S.
conditions for a ``substantive dialogue'' _ a form of diplomatic
acceptance long sought by the Palestinian group.
   Only a day earlier, the State Department had said Arafat failed
to meet the U.S. conditions. And less than three weeks ago, Shultz
had accused the PLO of terrorism, said Arafat was ``an accessory to
such terrorism'' and denied the PLO leader an entry visa to address
the U.N. General Assembly in New York.
   The United States long has insisted that the PLO accept U.N.
resolutions, adopted in 1967 and 1973, affirming the right of all
states in the Middle East to live in peace. Israel is not
specifically mentioned. The United States also has demanded that
Arafat's organization renounce terrorism and accept Israel's right
to exist.
   White House spokesman Fitzwater said U.S. officials would move
``cautiously into the dialogue'' with PLO representatives and that
the talks would ``establish a foundation'' for the organization ``to
prove that they have changed their ways.''
   ``It's too early to speculate on how these things might take
place,'' he said. ``This is a first step ... and how the follow-on
steps will evolve, we really don't want to draw parameters at this
point.''
   ``We did have strong feelings about the PLO and we still have
strong feelings,'' Fitzwater said. But he said the administration
decided to permit contacts because there has been ``evidence of
change.''
</TEXT>
