<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0826 12-15 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0826,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Seymour; A separate moved for AMs as a0736 on Symington.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Symington</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuart Symington, the nation's first Air
Force secretary and a U.S. senator from Missouri for 24 years, died
Wednesday of heart failure. He was 87.
   Symington served in World War I as an Army second lieutenant. He
held six various posts within President Harry Truman's
administration between 1945 to 1952, including the nation's first
Air Force secretary from 1947-1950.
   Symington served in the U.S. Senate from Missouri from 1953 to
1976, deciding at that time not to seek re-election. He was a
``favorite son'' candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1956 and 1960. Symington retired from the Senate in
1976.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Dorothy Jordan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Jordan, an actress who starred
opposite Clark Gable, Joel McCrea and Ramon Novarro in motion
pictures of the 1930s, died Dec. 7 of heart failure at age 82.
   Miss Jordan landed small parts in such Broadway musicals as
``Garrick Gaieties'' and ``Twinkle Twinkle.'' She was the understudy
for Fred Astaire's sister, Adele, in ``Funny Face.'' Miss Jordan
began her movie career when she was cast in the 1930 film ``In Gay
Madrid'' with Novarro.
   Her other credits included ``Min and Bill,'' ``The Taming of the
Shrew,'' ``Young Sinners,'' and ``Hell Divers'' with Clark Gable. In
1932 Miss Jordan, appeared opposite Joel McCrea in ``The Lost
Squadron'' and in ``Bondage'' a year later. She emerged briefly in
the 1950s to appear in character roles in ``The Sun Shines Bright,''
``The Searchers'' and ``The Wings of Eagles.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Shellhase</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OCEAN RIDGE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Shellhase, 93, a artist who
captured the diversity of American life through sketches and
drawings, died Monday.
   Shellhase's works have been shown in galleries such as the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Illustrators Club of New York, the
Norton Gallery and the New Chapellier Gallery of New York.
   His illustrations and cartoons appeared in the Saturday Evening
Post, The New Yorker, The New York Times, Collier's and Esquire.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Perry Lieber</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perry Lieber, a well-known publicity agent who
was a confidant of the late billionaire Howard Hughes, died Monday
at the age of 83.
   Lieber joined the publicity department at RKO Studios in 1930,
working there for 25 years and becoming the studio's publicity
director. He worked with many of RKO's top stars, including John
Wayne, Robert Mitchum, Cary Grant, Jane Russell, Ginger Rogers,
Ingrid Bergman and Debbie Reynolds.
   Lieber began his association with Hughes in 1948, when Hughes
purchased RKO. He handled all public relations for Hughes' Summa
Corp. until his death.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Anne Seymour</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Seymour, a actress who was heard almost
nightly during radio's Golden Age of the 1930s and 1940s, died Dec.
8 of respiratory complications. She was 79.
   Miss Seymour made her Broadway debut in 1928 as an understudy in
``Mr. Moneypenny.'' Her stage credits include ``Sunrise at
Campobello,'' ``Hay Fever,'' ``Saturday's Children,'' ``The Intimate
Strangers,'' ``The Sorcerer,'' ``Troilus and Cressida'' and ``Time
Out for Ginger.''
   Miss Seymours' radio credits include ``Portia Faces Life,'' ``The
Ford Theatre,'' ``Grand Hotel,'' ``Against the Storm,'' ``The
Magnificent Montague'' ``Armstrong Theater'' and others.
   Her first film was ``All the King's Men'' in 1949. Other movie
credits include ``All the Fine Young Cannibals,'' ``Misty,'' ``How
to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying'' and her last,
``Shoeless Joe,'' which has not been released.
   On television Miss Seymour appeared in ``Studio One,'' ``Robert
Montgomery Presents,'' ``Kraft Television Theater,'' ``The Jackie
Gleason Show,'' ``Naked City'' and ``Perry Mason,'' and recently,
``Cagney and Lacey.''
</TEXT>
