<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HousingProjectDeath     12-15 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Project Death,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Sues City For $60 Million In Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city was hit with a $60 million lawsuit
Wednesday alleging negligence on the part of Fire Department
paramedics who did not treat a 9-year-old boy who eventually died
from an asthma attack.
   Fire department spokesmen claim the ambulance was pelted with
eggs and rocks and paramedics were forced to retreat when they
arrived at a housing project Monday.
   ``All the evidence we have says there was nothing being thrown at
the paramedics,'' attorney Michael Bledsoe said. ``They just flatly
refused to go up'' to the apartment.
   Bledsoe filed a lawsuit on behalf of Sharon Jarnagin, whose son,
Carl, died. The lawsuit asks for $10 million in actual damages and
$50 million in punitive damages.
   A city attorney, Michael Lyons, said he was aware of the lawsuit
but had no comment.
   The paramedics, summoned by an emergency call at 4:16 p.m.
Monday, were not aware of the seriousness of the asthma attack when
they first arrived at the housing project, the Fire Department says.
   They left the scene and returned 24 minutes later when police
arrived, according to the Fire Department.
   Police officers said they found the boy in a bedroom in the
family's fifth-floor apartment. He was taken to a hospital, where he
was pronounced dead.
   Fire Department employees Tuesday washed the ambulance used by
the paramedics, removing any trace of egg that may have been on it,
Bledsoe said.
   ``When we heard about it we got a protective order barring anyone
from doing anything to the ambulance until we could inspect it,'' he
said
   The order was issued Wednesday by Cook County Judge Lester
Foreman.
   Fire Department spokesman Tom Sheppard said tapes of
communications between the paramedics and dispatchers show proof
that the ambulance was hit by flying objects.
   ``At all times paramedics and emergency medical technicians
should avoid placing themselves in danger,'' Sheppard said, reading
a city policy.
   The boy's mother and neighbors insist there was no danger to the
paramedics.
</TEXT>
