<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Derailment 1stLd-Writethru a0817 12-15 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Derailment, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0817,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Derails, Forces Evacuation of 100 Residents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `They can't...', to UPDATE
with crews considering transfer of propane, which could take 36
hours, and to move up and update detail on highway, railroad
closing. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `State police...'. DELETES last 3
grafs, now redundant.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two derailed railroad cars leaking highly
explosive liquid propane Wednesday forced the evacuation of about
100 residents and closed an interstate highway and rail routes in
northern Arizona.
   A total of 26 cars derailed early Wednesday about 10 miles east
of Flagstaff after 84 Santa Fe Railroad Co. cars somehow became
uncoupled during a stop, said a company official.
   Residents near the derailment were told at about 11 a.m. to plan
to spend at least 24 hours away from their homes while authorities
tried to defuse the cars leaking liquid propane.
   ``This has the potential to become a very dangerous situation,''
said Coconino County Sheriff Joe Richards.
   He said hazardous-materials teams from the Santa Fe Railroad Co.
and the state Department of Public Safety hoped to siphon off the
propane through a makeshift rigging of pipes and valves and ignite
it in a controlled burn.
   ``They can't offload it, because that would be too dangerous,''
Richards said. ``It's too dangerous to move heavy equipment in there
because of the potential for an explosion.''
   But later in the day, Santa Fe spokesman Mike Martin said that
hazardous materials experts were considering an alternate strategy,
an intricate process of pumping the propane out of the leaking
propane cars with special equipment.
   The process would take up to 36 hours, he said. If it is used,
the propane would be taken by truck and would be reloaded on
different tank cars later, Martin said. The experts hoped to decide
on a stragegy by early Thursday, he said.
   The residents evacuated earlier Wednesday would not be allowed to
return to their homes until the propane was completely removed.
   Authorities sealed off both the railroad right-of-way and
Interstate 40 over the 58-mile stretch between Flagstaff and
Winslow. By late evening Wednesday, the road and railroad remained
closed.
   State police helicopters also closed off the airspace over the
wreckage, chasing away aircraft carrying photographers.
   An Amtrak spokesman said the derailment held up two trains.
   Two other cars carrying propane, one with a hazardous-cargo
label, and 21 others derailed, but they were not leaking. The car
with the hazardous-cargo label was believed to be carrying an
industrial solvent, and was not considered explosive, officials said.
   Santa Fe spokesman Mike Martin said the train was parked at the
Ralston Purina pet-food plant in East Flagstaff to drop off one car
when the cars became uncoupled and began rolling east down a slight
grade.
   The runaway reached an estimated 40 mph before the cars derailed
on a curve. No one was injured, he said.
   Investigators began a probe to determine why the train sections
became separated, but the cause was not immediately determined,
Martin said. The westbound train originated in Kansas City, Mo.
</TEXT>
