<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-PLOPolicy Bjt   12-15 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-PLO Policy, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Decision Raises Problems for Israel, Questions About Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sudden U.S. decision to deal with the
Palestine Liberation Organization raises tough political problems
for Israel and suggests disarray within the Reagan administration in
its final weeks.
   Even while Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other senior
officials were making preparations at the White House for
Wednesday's historic announcement, President-elect George Bush was
criticizing the PLO for failing to meet U.S. conditions for a
dialogue.
   Speaking at the Executive Office Building just across the street,
Bush vowed to continue the Reagan administration's tough stand
against Yasser Arafat's organization. He demanded ``a clear and
unambiguous statement'' explicitly recognizing Israel, renouncing
terrorism and accepting two major U.N. Security Council resolutions
on the right of all states to live within secure boundaries.
   ``Before we have a dialogue with the PLO the signals have to be
clear, unmistakable, unambiguous,'' Bush said, biting off each word
with decisive crispness.
   Simultaneously, however, Arafat was giving a news conference in
Geneva that Shultz seized on as evidence that the PLO chairman had
come around to accepting the U.S. conditions.
   The result was announcements by President Reagan and by Shultz
that there would be a ``substantive dialogue'' with the PLO in Tunis
_ leaving Bush looking like the odd man out.
   Shultz, meanwhile, did not explain later at a State Department
news conference how what Arafat said on Wednesday had differed from
what the PLO leader had said a day earlier. The day-earlier comments
had been declared unacceptable.
   Having denied Arafat a visa less than three weeks earlier, Shultz
suddenly was approving direct dealings with a man he had denounced
as an ``accessory'' in acts of terrorism against Israelis and
Americans.
   Asked what was different about Arafat's most recent statement,
Shultz said cryptically: ``It was clear. It was not encumbered.''
   The decision was in a long State Department tradition of policy
shifts that always are defended as not policy shifts at all.
   It clearly backs Israel into a corner, now standing alone in
shunning the PLO. Shultz said he would not presume to advise another
country what it ought to do.
   ``It's totally for Israel to make its own decisions about what it
wants to do, and there's nothing to be inferred judgmentally about
what they should do,'' he said.
   The choice Israel faces is to watch the United States, its
closest friend, make arrangements for Mideast negotiations with the
PLO and not participate, or to agree to attend a peace conference
with the participation of the Palestine Liberation Organization now
a virtual certainty.
   The PLO could come under pressure, too _ from the United States
to make good on Arafat's declaration renouncing terrorism in all
forms.
   Bush, undoubtedly, will be asked by reporters in the next few
days why he seemed so out of step with what was brewing within the
White House. In a way, though, he may benefit from the decision
taken by the outgoing Reagan administration.
   Any political storm caused by embracing the PLO will not fall on
him. It's a decision that may have been inevitable, and one he now
will not have to make.
   But he may have to make one just as tough _ whether to support a
Palestinian state.
   Shultz said he was not endorsing statehood for the Palestinians
by approving the dialogue. And yet, the PLO's demand for a state
carved out of Israeli-held territory will be bolstered by its entry
into America's diplomatic community.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid, who heads the AP's State
Department staff, have covered U.S. diplomacy on the Middle East for
15 years.
</TEXT>
