<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-15 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Wheat Group Disputes Crop Projection By International Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Wheat Council is forecasting
that world wheat production could rise to a record level in the
1989-90 season and start a modest rebuilding of depleted grain
stockpiles.
   But an official of the U.S. National Association of Wheat Growers
says the council's assertion is premature and that i's too early to
make such projections.
   The council said Wednesday that wheat production could reach a
record 550 million metric tons in the 1989-90 season. That would be
5 million tons more than is expected to be consumed and would allow
world stocks to rebuild, said the council.
   A decline in stocks after the estimated fall of 37 million tons
this season would leave an ``uncomfortably narrow margin of security
between world supply and demand,'' the council said.
   If the council is correct about 1989-90 wheat production
exceeding use once again and starting another buildup in surpluses,
it could mean downward pressure on wheat prices.
   The Agriculture Department has not made any such projections yet.
   ``Our tendency over time is to have more faith in the USDA
projections,'' said Carl Schwensen, the association's executive vice
president here. ``The wheat council projections have a constituency
of developing countries that they inform through their various
forecasts.''
   Schwensen added in a telephone interview: ``Whether it exceeds
(consumption) or not, I think it's heroic to make any predictions
about that at this point.''
   Stockpiles built up during the wheat glut of the mid-1980s are
being depleted this season because of the sharp drop in 1988-89
wheat production caused by droughts in the United States and Canada.
   World wheat production for 1988-89 now is forecast by the council
at 500 million tons, 13 million tons below the previous season's
figure and 37 million down on the 1986-87 record.
   Tighter supplies this season have led to higher world prices
which are encouraging growers to increase plantings for 1989-90, the
council said.
   The USDA has forecast global wheat production this season at
502.5 million tons, about in line with the council's estimate for
1988-89. But USDA has not yet projected world wheat output for
1989-90.
   But department officials have been saying that the recent higher
prices and draw-down of wheat stocks are expected to boost plantings
for next season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department report says that even
if depleted soil moisture is replenished, the effects of the 1988
drought will continue to be ``very much in evidence'' next year
because of the disruptions is has caused.
   Net cash income, the difference between cash expenses and cash
gross receipts, is expected to be down somewhat from this year's
near-record $57 billion to between $48 billion and $52 billion.
   But the department's Economic Research Service said that would
still put 1989 net cash income at the fourth-highest level on record.
   Economists say net cash income was high in 1988 despite the
drought because so many farmers sold off commodities harvested in
earlier years, and because of large federal payments.
   Total crop and livestock receipts in 1989 are expected to rise
slightly from this year's record level, the report said.
   As a result of the drought and the draining of stored
inventories, farmers may boost crop plantings by as much as 30
million acres, but that will increase production costs. Government
payments are expected to decline 20 percent to 25 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-awaited question about who George Bush
wants as his secretary of agriculture has been answered, but
attention now turns to the No. 2 job in the Agriculture Department.
   Clayton Yeutter, currently the U.S. trade representative, was
announced Wednesday at Bush's choice to head USDA.
   The deputy secretary's job currently is held by Peter Myers, who
was on everybody's list of potential candidates to be Bush's
secretary of agriculture.
   It is unclear whether Myers, a Missouri farmer, will remain as
deputy. One name that surfaced hours after Yeutter was announced is
that of Jack Parnell, California state agriculture commissioner, who
reportedly is being pushed by strong California interests for Myers'
job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
