<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DOT-Eastern     12-15 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DOT-Eastern,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rules Out Further Probe Of Eastern's Financial Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department says it has no
plans to investigate further the financial fitness of Eastern
Airlines, denying a request from the airline's unions who claim the
company is being stripped of its assets.
   The department said Wednesday that Eastern ``has demonstrated
that it has the financial strength to operate safely and without due
risk to consumers'' and no formal fitness investigation is needed.
   The DOT also chastised the unions representing Eastern pilots and
machinists for bringing the petition. It accused the unions of
engaging in ``a transparent attempt to put pressure'' on management
by raising false safety concerns.
   ``Based on our earlier preliminary investigation of Eastern and
our review of publicly available current information, we believe
that Eastern remains fit to operate,'' said the department.
   There was no immediate comment from the unions.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said in Miami that the DOT
decision was ``recognition that the pilots' claims are absolute
nonsense'' and ``reaffirms what was decided conclusively months
ago'' in another federal investigation of Eastern and its parent
company, Texas Air Corp.
   The DOT earlier this year conducted an in-depth look at the
fitness of Texas Air Corp., including an examination of various
financial transactions involving Eastern that had been put into
question by the unions. Last June the department said it found Texas
Air Corp., to be fit to operate, although it raised concerns about
the ongoing labor disputes at Eastern.
   On Wednesday, the department in a sharply worded order denying
the unions' petition said the ``only cause for concern with respect
to safety issues has been created by the irresponsible conduct'' of
the pilot and machinist unions in withdrawing from a joint
labor-management safety committee that the two sides had established
last July.
   After Eastern announced in October that it planned to sell its
Northeast shuttle operation to billionaire Donald Trump for $365
million, Eastern's unions withdrew from the safety committees, the
department said.
   On Dec. 7, the Air Line Pilots Association, which represents
Eastern pilots, filed its petition requesting that the department
reopen its investigation of Eastern's fitness because of the
proposed sale of the shuttle, the only profitable part of the
airline.
   The pilots union later was joined by the Machinists union in
making the request.
   The petition argued that the proposed sale of the Eastern Shuttle
to Trump amounts to ``downsizing'' Eastern and ``undermining the
airline's financial condition ... to the point that it may not
survive.''
</TEXT>
