<DOCNO> AP881215-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0214EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Theologian'sSuit     12-15 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Theologian's Suit,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial To Offer Rare Inside Look At Roman Catholic Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a Roman Catholic priest's claim
that Catholic University violated his academic freedom will provide
an unusual look at the church's inner workings.
   The suit was brought by the Rev. Charles E. Curran after the
university revoked his right to teach theology on grounds that his
writings were at odds with the faith.
   The suit pits Curran's claims of academic freedom against the
church's contention it has the power to discipline clergy who stray
from the orthodox teachings of the faith.
   Cardinal James A. Hickey, archbishop of Washington and chancellor
of the university, was the first witness as the trial got under way
Wednesday in Superior Court.
   Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, archbishop of Chicago who chaired the
university's board of trustees when action was first taken against
Curran, is also set to testify.
   Hickey defended the university's decision to revoke Curran's
``canonical mission'' to teach Roman Catholic theology after Vatican
authorities determined his writings were at odds with the faith.
   Curran, 54, refused an offer to teach ethics outside the
university's religious department.
   The university contends that it was merely enforcing the highest
authority of the Vatican, which had revoked Curran's right to teach
Roman Catholic theology.
   As an ordained priest, the university contends, Curran has an
obligation to obey the revocation of his mission to teach Catholic
theology.
   Curran contends he was never conferred such authority and his
contract to teach was no different than any other university
professor with tenure.
   Hickey defended the decision to discipline Curran, saying: ``the
case of Father Curran had become a widely known matter. It has
caused, in my opinion, a great deal of harm to the church.''
   The church has the power to declare that a theologian no longer
speaks for the faith ``when it believes a theologian has seriously
departed from the Catholic teaching,'' Hickey said.
   An investigation of Curran's writings, which, among other things,
disputed the church's stance on birth control and homosexuality,
determined he was ``unfaithful to the role as professor of
theology,'' Hickey said.
   Because of the case's notoriety, it was important that he be
removed from the theology, particularly because of the university's
``unique relationship both with the Holy See and the Catholic Church
in this country,'' Hickey said.
   Founded in 1885 by Pope Leo XIII, Catholic University functions
as one of few ``pontifical universities'' in the country that is
governed directly by the church.
   The action was taken because ``it seemed inconceivable to the
board of trustees of the university that we could simply join in
defiance on the part of Father Curran,'' Hickey testified.
   Curran's attorney, Paul Saunders, said the decision to remove
Curran from the ecclesiastical faculty violated academic freedoms
specifically conferred on the faculty following a strike over the
issue in 1967.
   Moreover, Saunders said Curran's dissenting views, summarized in
his work ``Faithful Dissent,'' were well known to the church long
before his dismissal earlier this year.
   ``The actions that have been taken against him are not because of
some brand-new heretical position,'' Saunders said.
   ``If the notion of academic freedom in the specific context of
the present case means anything, it means the university guaranteed
a freedom in the face of public dissent from certain church
teachings,'' Saunders said in pre-trial arguments.
   But Kevin T. Baine, who represents the university, said the court
had no right to question the church's application of canon law,
which governed the relationship between Curran and the university.
   ``Father Curran thinks he hasn't an obligation to his church to
abide by this declaration,'' Bain said.
   Curran was trying to change the university into something that he
``wants it to be,'' Baine argued.
   Judge Frederick H. Weisberg agreed that the court has no power to
second-guess application of church law, but ruled that the issue in
the case is whether these canons formed the basis of Curran's
contract.
   Hickey said that Curran was implicitly conferred a ``canonical
mission'' when he was hired.
   Following his suspension from Catholic University in 1987, Curran
was a visiting professor at Cornell. He currently has a one-year
appointment at the University of Southern California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScholarshipPrograms     12-15 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scholarship Programs,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students In Pioneering Scholarship Program Beat National Graduation
Rate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix slugline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pioneering private effort to help
underprivileged students get college scholarships has achieved a
graduation rate sharply above the national average, a study
concluded.
   The 21-year-old, privately financed Cleveland Scholarship
Programs released a study of its first two decades Wednesday showing
80 percent of those who got grants from the program and enrolled in
four-year colleges graduated.
   Nationally, about 50 percent of students who start college
receive their degrees, the program said.
   CSP has assisted more than 57,000 students, most from Cleveland
public high schools, since its founding. Last year 3,700 students
received specialized help applying for college admission and
scholarships, and 540 underprivileged students received grants
averaging $375.
   Under the program, counseling is available to all students but
only students from underprivileged economic backgrounds can qualify
for its direct grants.
   ``They really helped me a lot,'' said Dwight W. Newsom, 34, who
graduated from Bowling Green State University in 1976 and is now a
sales executive with a concrete supply company.
   Newsom, the first member of his family to attend college, said
CSP provided him with crucial help meeting an array of unfamiliar
college admission and scholarship requirements and deadlines.
   ``As far as filling out paperwork, it was totally new for me,''
Newsom said.
   Christina R. Milano, the program's executive director, said the
result of the survey showed that ``a private partnership can have a
major impact on assisting economically disadvantaged students. ...
They can go on to college and be very successful.''
   CSP has 21 part-time counselers who visit high schools and meet
with students to help them apply to college and seek financial
assistance from various sources. Follow-up counseling continues
through the campus years.
   The alumni study was conducted by Eugene S. Uyeki of Case Western
Reserve University among a random sample of 633 students out of the
8,205 who received direct CSP grants from 1967 to 1983.
   Eighty-five percent of those surveyed had average family incomes
of less than $25,000 and more than half were the first family member
to attend college.
   CSP calls itself the nation's oldest non-profit, privately
supported college financial aid counseling service. It has been used
as a model for similar programs in New York, Miami and other cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
