<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-15 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five-year-old Jamie Clouse believes in Santa
Claus. Kriss Kringle, after all, saved his life.
   The boy's mother, Robin Clouse, had stopped at a traffic light
Tuesday when Jamie began choking on the food he was eating.
   ``I was Christmas shopping and I was in the middle lane of
traffic,'' said Ms. Clouse, 29. ``My little boy was choking and I
didn't know what to do.''
   Ms. Clouse jumped from the car and pulled Jamie out of the
passenger side.
   ``He couldn't breathe and I was ready to turn him upside down,''
she said.
   Suddenly a man dressed in a Santa suit got of the van stopped in
the next lane and took the child from her arms.
   ``He performed the Heimlich maneuver,'' Ms. Clouse said.
   The food caught in Jamie's throat dislodged and he was able to
breath again. But traffic was backed up, and Santa Claus ambled back
in his van and drove away.
   ``I didn't get a chance to thank him and I don't even know who he
was,'' Ms. Clouse said.
   Jamie does. It was Santa Claus, who was in the van ``on his way
to the North Pole to get his reindeer for Christmas Eve,'' Jamie
said. ``He saved my life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Son Of Heaven exhibit, a display of priceless
artifacts of the emperors of China, was inspected by a woman who
knew them.
   Fun Ai Chao Lum, a 104-year-old Seattle resident born in China
during the Qing Dynasty, took in the exhibition Wednesday at the
Seattle Center, along with other seniors citizens from the Sunshine
Garden, a day-care center for elderly Chinese.
   The exhibit includes items more than 2,600 years old. Mrs. Lum's
62-year-old son, James, said she was especially interested in the
clothing and possessions of the Qing Dynasty, who ruled China from
1644 to 1911.
   Escorted by Liu Shishu, the chief curator from the Chinese team
accompanying the exhibition, Mrs. Lum appeared engrossed by much of
the artwork and regalia of the imperial Chinese court, listening
intently as Liu's Mandarin was translated into her native Cantonese.
   ``She remembers the last three emperors very well,'' her son
said. ``Anything before that's a little fuzzy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yes, Virginia, there really is a Santa
Claus, a judge decided after hearing from a jolly, old man who
bellowed the familiar ``Ho, Ho, Ho!''
   In a grave tone, Municipal Judge George T. Choppelas said he was
drawing partly on legal precedent set in the movie, ``Miracle on
34th Street,'' in which a New York court found for the defendant _
Santa Claus.
   ``As long as there is love and generosity and gift-giving, this
court is going to find that there really, really is a Santa Claus,''
Choppelas said Wednesday in the city's Court of Historical Review
and Appeals, a just-for-fun tradition with a real judge and lawyers.
   Choppelas made his ruling after a rollicking, 90-minute ``trial''
to consider the question.
   After rounds of argument, the event came to a standstill with the
appearance of a large man in a red suit and white beard who laughed
a hearty ``Ho, ho, ho!'' as he entered the courtroom, toting a sack
with toys and a golf club.
   Anti-Claus lawyer Frank Winston attacked him but got nowhere.
   An irate Claus reminded Winston that ``I got a letter from you
when you were 6 years old.'' Testimony from 5-year-old Dave Wharton
helped the Santa cause, despite browbeating by Winston, who escorted
the child off the stand.
   ``Shame on you,'' admonished the judge, before he made his ruling.
</TEXT>
