<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MakingTheDecision     12-15 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Making The Decision,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Arafat Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Decision Caps Diplomatic Ping-Pong Over PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to open direct
talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization capped a month of
intense debate over recent PLO overtures, a period in which the
United States stood virtually alone in the court of world opinion.
   The historic decision announced Wednesday came 18 days after
Secretary of State George P. Shultz refused to allow PLO chairman
Yasser Arafat to enter the United States to address the U.N. General
Assembly. Shultz said Arafat was kept out because his organization
``engaged in terrorism against Americans and others.''
   Shultz made clear Wednesday that he was not forgiving the PLO for
its past but said Arafat's statements earlier in the day recognizing
the existence of Israel and renouncing terrorism had met standards
set in 1975 for U.S. dialogue with the PLO.
   Many nations attacked Shultz's Nov. 26 decision not to allow
Arafat to come to New York. Shultz made the decision just 11 days
after the Palestine National Council, the PLO's governing body, had
accepted U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338 as the basis for peace talks
and world leaders were eager for Arafat to elaborate.
   The criticism of Shultz came from all quarters and included
assertions the United States was violating the agreement under which
New York serves as the organization's headquarters. Even Pope John
Paul II, without specifically referring to the decision, said
``every obstacle'' to the peace process should be removed.
   U.N. delegates passed a resolution denouncing the decision, and
only the United States and Israel voted against it. Britain
abstained. President Reagan and President-elect Bush stood by Shultz.
   The U.N. then took the unprecedented step of moving its debate to
Geneva, where on Tuesday Arafat made his long-awaited speech and
declared, ``Come, let us make peace.'' He recognized Israel's right
to exist, condemned terrorism and said peace negotiations should be
based on Resolutions 242 and 338 _ the three U.S. conditions for
opening a dialogue with the PLO.
   Shultz had received advance word Arafat might meet the standards
and had, according to sources, informed Israel that he was prepared
to announce that the United States was ready to talk to the PLO.
   But, after a close examination of the speech, the State
Department said Arafat's language was ambiguous and ``did not meet
our conditions.''
   Arafat then called a Wednesday news conference in Geneva and,
carefully choosing his words as advisers whispered to him, read a
statement that called for a Palestinian state to co-exist alongside
Israel, said resolutions 242 and 338 should serve as the framework
for peace talks and that ``we totally and absolutely renounce all
forms of terrorism, including individual terrorism, group and state
terrorism.''
   At virtually the same time Arafat spoke, Bush was applauding the
PLO leader's Tuesday speech but repeating the standard Reagan
administration line that it had not gone far enough.
   ``I want it clear, I want it unambiguous, I want is so nobody can
argue with what's been said,'' said the president-elect, apparently
unaware of the clearer statements just made by Arafat.
   But at the White House and the State Department, where again
advance word had been received that Arafat was ready to meet the
U.S. conditions, the day was spent determining whether he had.
   At 9:30 a.m. Reagan was briefed by Lt. Gen. Colin Powell, his
national security adviser, and told Arafat planned a news conference
at which he might use the ``right language.''
   Four hours later Reagan met with Shultz, Powell and White House
chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein and reaffirmed that he was ready
to authorize dialogue provided Arafat met the conditions, according
to White House aides.
   At 4 p.m. Shultz and Powell spoke again: Shultz had a copy of
Arafat's statement and indicated Arafat had met the conditions.
   Less than a half-hour passed when Powell briefed Bush and gave
him a copy of Arafat's statement.
   At 5:12 p.m., according to the White House, Powell and Duberstein
called Reagan and told him they believed Arafat had met the
conditions. Reagan immediately authorized the dialogue. The
administration notified Israel and others of the decision.
   Even before Shultz made the formal announcement, Israel issued a
statement saying it regretted the move.
   Shultz made it official just after 6:30 p.m.
   ``I didn't change my mind,'' he said in response to the
inevitable question. ``They made their statements clear.''
</TEXT>
