<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-Arafat-Reax     12-15 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Arafat-Reax,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many U.S. Jews Cautiously Support PLO Move; Arab-Americans Endorse
It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. Jewish groups warily supported the Reagan
administration's historic decision to sit down with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, while Arab-Americans said the policy
reversal rekindled hope for Middle East peace.
   Several American Jewish leaders said they trusted President
Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz in their decision to
open a ``substantive dialogue'' with the PLO, but called on PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat to back his words of peace with action.
   ``We understand that the United States, having set standards for
speaking with the PLO and the PLO having met those minimum
standards, that it is appropriate for us to live up to its
commitment,'' said Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith in New York.
   ``It is a first step. Now we must watch to see if the PLO will
match words with deeds.''
   James Zogby, executive director of the Arab-American Institute in
Washington, called the government's decision to end its longtime
rejection of the PLO as a party to Middle East peace efforts an
``important step forward.''
   ``The dialogue should throw into sharp relief the failure of
Israel to say yes to the very issues that the PLO has now acceded
to,'' Zogby said. ``Our hope is that the dialogue is productive and
that peace is now possible.''
   In Washington, legislators from both parties cautiously endorsed
the move.
   ``It may be a blind alley, but an alley worth treading with eyes
open,'' said Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind. ``This dialogue in no way
mitigates our steadfast support of Israel. But I hope Israel will at
least be willing to informally acknowledge this process as a worthy
attempt.''
   ``In the interest of peace and security for Israel and all
parties in the region, the U.S. has no sensible choice but to begin
a dialogue,'' said U.S. Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the
House foreign operations appropriations subcommittee.
   But, he added, ``the proof will still lie in deeds and not
words.''
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, who nearly a decade ago was forced by
then-President Carter to resign as the U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations for meeting with a PLO representative, applauded the
decision, saying, ``People were not ready for this before now.''
   Reagan said Wednesday he authorized the State Department to enter
into ``a substantive dialogue'' with the Palestinian group after
Arafat said he was renouncing ``all forms of terrorism.''
   Shultz, who only two weeks ago barred Arafat from entering the
United States and called him an ``accessory'' to terrorism, said the
PLO issued a statement in which it met all three U.S. conditions for
a dialogue. The conditions were acceptance of U.N. Security Council
resolutions affirming the right of all states to live in peace,
recognition of Israel and renunciation of terrorism.
   While the Israeli government swiftly criticized the move, many
U.S. Jewish groups were reluctant to do so, reflecting the
dissension that has marred relations between Israel and many
American Jews over Israel's hardline policies on the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Morris B. Abram, chairman of the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations in New York, said in a
statement: ``We neither approve nor disapprove. We accept it. We
trust the United States.''
   ``The first action the U.S. should take in its conversations with
the PLO should be to demand that the PLO repeal the Palestine
National Covenant, which calls for the destruction of the state of
Israel,'' he said.
   ``Unless and until the PLO translates its words into the deed of
repealing that covenant, there can be no progress toward peace in
the Middle East.''
   However, the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, dedicated to
the study of the Holocaust and promoting Israel in world affairs,
said it was disappointed with the decision.
   ``While both President Reagan and Secretary of State George
Shultz have proven themselves to be the staunchest friends of the
state of Israel, the road they have chosen to embark is fraught with
danger,'' said the statement read by a spokesman, Rabbi Abraham
Cooper.
   The response from Arab-American organizations, while generally
favorable, was in some cases tinged with bitterness. M.T. Mehdi,
president of the American Arab Relations Committee in New York, said
his organization was ``not impressed.''
   ``The State Department should talk to Israel and urge it not to
shoot at the Palestinian youth nor to use American airplanes to
attack Palestinian camps in Lebanon,'' he said.
</TEXT>
