<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--911Delivery     12-15 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--911 Delivery,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Gives Birth Alone With Help of 911 Dispatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOND DU LAC, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candy Jones was alone when she gave
birth to a healthy baby girl, whose deliver got a ``long-distance''
boost by a 911 police communciations officer.
   Jones, 26, called the emergency number early Tuesday and was on
the line with Officer Laurie Matthews for about 10 minutes before
giving birth to her full-term daughter. Paramedics arrived moments
later.
   ``I'm having my baby _ I'm at home,'' Jones told Matthews.
   Jones said she was alone, but that her parents were on their way
to her apartment, according to a tape of the call.
   An ambulance was dispatched, and Matthews told Jones to stay on
the telephone line.
   She then calmed the pregnant woman as Jones screamed with each
contraction.
   The delivery went just fine, said a paramedic who took the mother
and daughter to St. Agnes Hospital.
</TEXT>
