<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0508EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaldenPond     12-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walden Pond,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Orders Full Environmental Review for Walden Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government is best that governs least, according to
Henry David Thoreau, but a state order for a full environmental
review of a proposed project near his beloved Walden Pond may keep
development of the area at bay.
   ``We are Walden Pond's caretakers,'' said John DeVillars, the
state's newly named secretary of the Environmental Affairs Agency,
which called for the lengthy review on Wednesday.
   ``Our responsibility is to ensure that we take every reasonable
measure to avoid or minimize damage to this historic area. Nothing
short of a full review will fulfill that responsibility,'' DeVillars
said.
   At issue is a proposed Concord Office Park by the developer
Boston Properties, which wants to build a 148,000-square-foot office
building and a 518-car parking area.
   The land is near where Thoreau worked on his masterpiece,
``Walden,'' while living there in solitude beginning in 1845 for two
years in a hut on land owned by Ralph Waldo Emerson. In the book,
Thoreau writes about the importance being close to nature.
   The land later was donated to Middlesex County and eventually to
the state, which maintains the heavily used recreation area around
the pond.
   Some preservation groups have urged the state to buy the land and
add it to the Walden State Reservation surrounding the pristine,
historic site in Concord. But despite passage of a record $500
million bond for land purchases, state officials say they cannot
afford to buy it.
   Edward Linde, president of Boston Properties, said the state's
``11th-hour'' decision had no basis in law or logic.
   ``The record proves that Boston Properties has complied fully
with every applicable state and local environmental and zoning law
and regulation,'' Linde said. ``We will review the state's request
carefully.''
   The site proposed for the development was cleared 25 years ago
and is now zoned for commercial development by Concord, whose
officials are eager to add the development to the town's tax base.
   In August, Boston Properties voluntarily agreed to an initial
evaluation of the project under the Massachusetts Environmental
Policy Act (MEPA). After the company filed a report, the state
decided to order a full MEPA review _ an often lengthy and expensive
process _ based on the developer's information, staff analysis and
public comment.
   The key issue cited by the state in ordering the review was
concern over traffic surrounding the area.
   Walden Pond is a 62-acre body of water in a 333-acre state-owned
reservation on the edge of Concord, an affluent town of 12,500 about
20 miles northwest of Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
