<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Consul-Spying     12-15 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consul-Spying,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Consul General Accused of Providing Cover for Spies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Yugoslav consul general here, indicted for
allegedly laundering $1.5 million, gave diplomatic cover to two men
involved in smuggling documents and computer information to
Yugoslavia, officials said.
   An affidavit by Louise Hodess, a U.S. Customs Service agent,
alleges that Bahrudin Bijedic, Chicago consul general, provided
cover for the men, both of whom are American citizens, the Chicago
Tribune reported today.
   According to the affidavit, one of the men, Yugoslav-born
Vjekoslov Spanjol, of Plano, Texas, was ``the second in command of
Yugoslavian Intelligence in the United States.''
   The other man was identified as Hubert F. Cole of Carrollton,
Texas.
   Bijedic, Spanjol, Cole and two other men were indicted Dec. 1 by
a federal grand jury in Philadelphia on charges they engaged in the
money-laundering scheme.
   Spanjol and Cole were able to get documents and computer
information from Department of Defense contractors in the
Dallas-Fort Worth area and smuggle the data to Belgrade via
diplomatic pouch, the newspaper said.
   Ms. Hodess' affidavit said all of the defense contractors
involved had contracts with an office-cleaning service operated by
Spanjol out of Richardson, Texas. It alleged that Spanjol's
employees obtained discarded documents and other information from
the contractors' trash.
   Federal law prohibits the delivery of information relating to the
national defense to any foreign government.
   The affidavit was filed as part of an ongoing investigation of
Bijedic and the others, the newspaper said.
   Earlier this month, Bijedic, Cole, Spanjol and two other men were
charged with funneling $1.5 million to bank accounts controlled by
an undercover U.S. Customs agent. LBS Bank of New York Inc., the
U.S. branch of a Yugoslavian bank, also was indicted.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney William Cook, at the request of the U.S.
attorney's office in Philadelphia, asked Wednesday that a seal on
the affidavit be lifted. U.S. Magistrate Elaine Bucklo granted the
motion, allowing the case file to be open to the public.
   Cook declined to comment on the contents of the affidavit.
   The affidavit disclosed that Cole held several meetings with an
undercover U.S. Customs agent, which were secretly tape-recorded,
and stated that he and Spanjol already were involved with laundering
money in Yugoslavia for a drug dealer in San Antonio.
   Before being conferred diplomatic cover by Bijedic, Cole said he
and Spanjol concealed the currency in their luggage, the affidavit
states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-Factions     12-15 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Factions,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat's Political Triumph Could Trigger Radical Backlash</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. decision to talk to the PLO is a
major political triumph for Yasser Arafat that could breathe new
life into the comatose Middle East peace process _ or touch off a
violent backlash by Palestinian radicals.
   There is also the possibility that factions outside the PLO such
as the one led by terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal may simply unleash
a new wave of terror to wreck the PLO chairman's diplomatic
initiative.
   If the breakthrough fails to produce solid political gains,
particularly U.S. pressure on Israel to negotiate, it could trigger
attacks by radicals within the PLO who fear Arafat has made too many
concessions in the Palestinians' 40-year-old struggle for a homeland.
   The Marxist Popular Front for Liberation of Palestine, which
reconciled with Arafat last year after a four-year split, has
already accused him of ``capitulation'' by renouncing terrorism and
recognizing Israel's right to exist.
   Col. Saeed Mousa, who leads the Syrian-based breakaway
Fatah-Uprising faction, on Wednesday branded Arafat ``a traitor ...
for his surrenderist concessions to the United States and the
Israeli enemy.''
   Mousa, known by his nom de guerre of Abu Mousa, split from the
PLO in 1983 with other dissident factions in a Syrian-backed mutiny
launched to protest Arafat's moves toward moderation.
   After fierce fighting, Arafat and his loyalists, already forced
out of Beirut and south Lebanon by Israel's 1982 invasion, were
driven out of their last Lebanese stronghold.
   Capt. Ahmed Jibril, commander of the extremist Syrian-backed
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command,
declared angrily in Damascus Wednesday night: ``Arafat has
recognized and offered four-fifths of the Palestinian land to
Israel.''
   The PLO leadership has accepted that Israel is there to stay and
seeks a Palestinian homeland only in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, abandoning the dream of regaining all of pre-1948 Palestine.
   ``By renouncing violence and terrorism, Arafat is condemning
anyone who uses the gun against the Israeli occupier,'' Jibril said.
``Arafat has offered Israel what he doesn't have. The land of
Palestine is not the property of any organization or any
individual.''
   West German authorities six weeks ago arrested 13 suspected
PFLP-GC members who they said were planning terrorist attacks. They
also seized explosives.
   Arafat and his top lieutenants would be targets along with
Israelis and American if the radicals go on the warpath again.
   For 15 years, since he first showed signs of moderation, Arafat
has had to battle not only the Israelis, but Palestinian extremists
and hard-line Arab states led by Syria, whose President Hafez Assad
has long sought to wrestle control of the Palestinian cause from
Arafat.
   Gunmen led by the renegade Abu Nidal, wanted by a dozen
countries, have assassinated a score of key Arafat aides over the
years in a campaign to silence the moderates.
   Others have been killed by Israel's secret service, Mossad. The
Israelis' latest victim was Arafat's right-hand man, Khalil
al-Wazir, who was slain in Tunis on April 16.
   The Reagan administration agreed Wednesday to open direct talks
with Arafat after he told a special U.N. General Assembly session in
Geneva that the PLO renounces ``all forms of terrorism'' and said it
explicitly recognizes Israel's right to exist.
   That was an abrupt turnaround by Washington, which only the day
before had said Arafat had not gone far enough to meet U.S.
conditions for a dialogue.
   Last month, Arafat steered the Palestine National Council, the
PLO's parliament-in-exile and highest decision-making body, to
implicitly recognize Israel's right to exist by accepting U.N.
Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338. It also declared an
independent Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza, where
Palestinians have been in revolt for a year.
   Radical PLO factions disagreed with Arafat's moderate strategy,
which was primarily aimed at persuading the Americans to deal
directly with the PLO and put pressure on Israel to negotiate.
   George Habash's Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
the prime mover behind the wave of airliner hijackings of the 1960s
and 1970s, and the Marxist Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine nonethless reluctantly went along with the PNC declaration
``in the interest of unity.''
   But Habash warned Arafat last month: ``We're backing your efforts
because this is what the majority wants. But we don't believe
moderation will pay.
   ``We can't wait forever. If you fail, you have to come back to
this council to say so and we can then decide the future course.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Ed Blanche is The Associated Press' Middle East
news editor based in Nicosia and has covered PLO affairs and
international terrorism since 1967.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
