<DOCNO> AP881215-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerTests     12-15 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Tests,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rodent Tests Poor Way to Evaluate Chemicals for Cancer Risk, Study
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lengthy testing in rats and mice to predict
whether a chemical poses a cancer hazard in humans usually fails to
provide enough information to justify its cost, researchers asserted
today.
   Most chemicals should be classified instead on the basis of
short-term lab tests, says a cost-benefit analysis in the British
journal Nature.
   Concerns over rodent testing have been raised before, centering
on the uncertainty over how relevant they are for predicting how a
chemical will affect people.
   The researchers said 30 percent of chemicals tested for
cancer-causing potential in one program behaved differently in rats
than in mice. Rodent tests are probably no more predictive for
humans and could be much less, since people are more biologically
different from rodents than rats are from mice, researchers said.
   Before deciding on whether to use a long-term rodent test,
regulators should consider results of short-term testing and the
costs to society of misclassifying a chemical, researchers said. For
most chemicals, proceeding to the rodent tests would not be worth
the cost, they said.
   Social costs of misclassifying a chemical include additional
cancers if a dangerous chemical is wrongly labeled safe. If a safe
chemical is erroneously labeled cancer-causing, society loses access
to a potentially valuable compound or pays for needless precautions.
   The researchers are from Carnegie-Mellon University in
Pittsburgh, Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland and the
University of Washington in Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0057 </DOCNO>
