<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwayKillings     12-15 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Killings,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused In Second Rape; Held on $20,000 Bond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed truck driver is accused
of raping two women in separate assaults along the same densely
wooded stretch of highway where the bodies of six women have been
discovered since July, officials said.
   Neil Anderson, 35, of New Bedford, pleaded innocent Wednesday to
charges he abducted and raped a woman at knifepoint in August 1987.
He was held at the Bristol County jail on $20,000 bond.
   Afterward, a second woman who identified Anderson in a composite
photograph accused him of raping her in July, said Bristol County
District Attorney Ronald A. Pina.
   ``The two rape cases have come out as a legitimate result of this
investigation'' into the highway serial killings, said Pina,
although he declined to confirm news reports that Anderson is a
suspect in the slayings.
   ``There's a good list of suspects we have. They're all being
checked out,'' Pina said at a news conference Wednesday. ``I think
we are definitely closing in. The circle is becoming smaller and
smaller.''
   The partially clad skeletons of six women have been found since
July in a six- to eight-mile radius along Interstate 195 and Route
140 in Dartmouth and Freetown.
   Thomas Gibney, a spokesman for Pina, declined to say whether
Anderson, a divorced father of two who lives with his mother and
grandmother, had been among those questioned in the slayings.
   Pina has said he believes the six killings were likely the
victims of the same killer or killers and that the victims all had
ties to New Bedford's Weld Square neighborhood, known for
prostitution and drugs.
   Douglas Ubelaker, a forensic pathologist with the Smithsonian
Institution called in to examine the victims' remains, said all six
women apparently died in a similar manner, but he declined to detail
his findings.
   Anderson, who has also worked as a welder and lives about 10
blocks from the Weld Square area, was arrested at home Tuesday. He
was charged with aggravated rape, kidnapping, and assault and
battery with a dangerous weapon.
   James M. Quinn, the public defender representing Anderson, said
his client ``has been charged with only one crime. I think that to
try to link that to any other events is very unfair.''
   Gibney said an arraignment on the second rape charge would not be
held unless Anderson posted bail. ``At that time we would slap the
other warrant on him, but barring that he's just going to sit there
(in jail) until he goes before the grand jury on the other
charges,'' he said.
   Judge John A. Markey scheduled a pretrial hearing on Dec. 21 in
New Bedford District Court. Anderson also will appear at that time
on charges of assault and battery with a deadly weapon in an
unrelated fight, Quinn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
