<HEAD>Young Troublemaker Receives Harsh Sentence For Stolen Lottery
Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Pezzuti was dreaming of riches
when he tried to redeem 47 stolen state lottery tickets last June.
He found out the tickets were worth 15 years in prison.
   In tears, the 18-year-old high school dropout with 32 juvenile
convictions was led from court after Palm Beach County Circuit Judge
Thomas Sholts balked at pleas for leniency and imposed the harshest
sentence possible.
   ``He's graduated to the major leagues,'' Sholts said.
   Pezzuti, scheduled for a February trial on other charges of
dealing in stolen goods, was convicted last month of trying to
receive a free ticket for each of the tickets stolen from a Juno
Beach beauty salon.
   Pezzuti's father, Jim Pezzuti, said his son planned to appeal the
sentence.
   ``It's sort of obvious the state attorneys are out to get him,''
he said. ``He's not really a hardened criminal.''
   Assistant State Attorney Jacqui Charbonneau recommended the
sentence based on Pezzuti's prior juvenile record.
   The elder Pezzuti said his son has been in jail since his
conviction, and ``that probably did more to straighten him up than
anything he did in the juvenile system.''
   Pezzuti went through the juvenile system without being punished
much for his crimes, mostly burglaries and automobile thefts, say
family members.
   ``He thought, `I'm never going to get in trouble. They're just
playing with me,''' said his sister, Debbie.
</TEXT>
