<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CampaignIndictment     12-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Indictment,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Accused of Election Law Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four businessman face up to 17 years in prison
if convicted on charges they tried to illegally aid Sen. Alan
Cranston's campaign by funneling money to an opponent of his chief
rival.
   The five-count federal indictment handed up Wednesday contends
that $120,000 was used for an advertising campaign in support of
American Independent Party candidate Ed Vallen, who ran against
Cranston, D-Calif., and Republican Rep. Ed Zschau in 1986.
   ``We were not involved in any way, even indirectly,'' Cranston
spokesman Murray Flanders said in a telephone interview from
Washington.
   According to acting U.S. Attorney Gary Feess, the defendants
solicited some 55 contributors to write checks to Green Stripe
Media, which produced a TV ad for Vallen.
   Feess told a news conference that the people who wrote checks
were reimbursed for amounts running from $1,000 to $4,000. He
declined to say whether the check writers knew they were violating
election laws.
   ``The individuals were told different things by different
people,'' Feess said.
   Feess stressed that Cranston knew nothing about the plan and had
no role in approving it. There was also no evidence that anyone on
Cranston's staff was involved.
   ``We have absolutely no evidence that Senator Cranston knew or
approved of this action,'' he said, adding there is no indication
that it had any influence on the outcome of the election. Cranston
narrowly defeated Zschau.
   Feess indicated that Michael R. Goland, 41, of Beverly Hills was
the moving force in the alleged scheme.
   Goland was charged with conspiring with Sandore Habalow, 45, of
Los Angeles and Lyle R. Weisman, 31, of Beverly Hills. Michael B.
Altman, 42, of Los Angeles was charged with aiding and abetting the
alleged contributions by acting as a conduit through which funds
were passed to the media company.
   If convicted, Goland could get up to 17 years in prison and fines
totaling $1 million. Weisman and Habalow each face up to 16 years
and $875,000 in fines if convicted; Altman could get a year and be
fined $125,000.
   According to the Federal Election Commission, Goland poured more
than $1 million into a campaign against former Sen. Charles Percy,
R-Ill., in 1984. Percy, who lost to Democrat Paul Simon, said Goland
wanted him defeated because the businessman didn't think he was
ardent enough in his support of Israel.
   ``Goland has one issue he is rabid on,'' Percy said after his
1984 defeat. ``He thinks I am not enough pro-Israel.''
   During the 1986 campaign, Zschau's credentials on support for
Israel were questioned. Like Percy, Zschau counted himself a
supporter of Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
