<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0657EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Symington-Obit     12-15 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Symington-Obit,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Split Denied Missourian Chance at White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuart Symington might have become the nation's
36th president as successor to the slain John F. Kennedy, said a
longtime confidant of the late Missouri senator.
   Symington died Wednesday at his home in New Canaan, Conn. He was
87.
   Symington, who was the nation's first Secretary of the Air Force
and later built a reputation as a principled politician, died of
heart disease, said James Symington, one of his two sons.
   Longtime confidant Clark A. Clifford recalled the 1969 Democratic
convention, and events that could have made Symington vice president.
   ``I was carrying messages back and forth,'' Clifford said from
Washington. ``The day before the (nominating) decision was to be
made, Senator Kennedy said, `I'm now offering the No. 2 position to
Senator Symington. Take it to him, and get back to me.'''
   Clifford recalled that elements of the party pressing for a
Southerner on the ticket eventually persuaded Kennedy to select
Lyndon B. Johnson for the vice presidency.
   ``I took that (message) back to Senator Symington,'' Clifford
said. ``He seemed very relaxed about it. He didn't seem to be
hungering for it (the nomination) anyway.''
   Symington was praised by both Democrats and Republicans.
   ``He exuded integrity,'' said U.S. District Judge William L.
Hungate, who served as a House Democrat from Missouri from 1964 to
1977. ``There was no question of any improprieties. No shadows ever
fell on Stuart Symington.''
   ``He was one of those tall trees whose falling will leave a great
vacant spot'' said former State Treasurer, James Spainhower, a
Democrat.
   Symington made his mark not only as a senator from 1952 to 1976
but as the secretary of the Air Force and, before that, as a
trouble-shooting industrialist summoned to St. Louis from Baltimore
in 1937 to bring strike-plagued Emerson Electric Co. back to
financial prosperity.
   As Air Force secretary, Symington ``set down broad principles and
courses of action, and the decisions he made in those early days had
substantial impact on the manner in which the Air Force later
developed,'' said Clifford, a former Defense secretary.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., ran against Symington in 1970 and
lost, then won the seat after Symington decided not to seek
re-election in 1976.
   Despite the fact they were from different parties, Symington
resigned from office before the term ended so Danforth would have
the most seniority of the new senators elected that year.
   ``To consider that he did this for someone who had run against
him, for someone of the other party, says a lot about this man,
about the bigness of the man and about his concern for our state,''
Danforth said.
   Although he was best known as a champion of military air in his
more than 30 years of public service, Symington's popularity at home
was largely based on his battles for local projects.
   Symington was born in Amherst, Mass., in 1901. He graduated from
Yale University in 1923 and entered business.
   In 1978, Symington married Ann ``Nancy'' Hemingway Watson and
moved to New Caanan, a wealthy Connecticut community just north of
New York City. Symington's first wife, Evelyn Wadsworth Symington,
died in 1972.
   In addition to his son, James, Symington is survived by a second
son, Stuart Symington Jr., six grandchildren and six
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
