<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficerSlain     12-15 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officer Slain,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Services Set for Slain Police Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plainclothes policeman who became the fifth
Dallas officer killed this year may have been shot during an
undercover cocaine transaction ``for the fun of it,'' an
investigator says.
   Lawrence R. Cadena, who left his police desk job three years ago
to work undercover on drug raids, was killed during a shootout that
also left a suspected drug dealer dead and two others wounded,
authorities said.
   Sgt. James Chandler described the department's mood as somber in
what has become the deadliest year ever for the police force. ``Four
was unbelievable,'' he said. ``Five was just _ I don't know. You
don't know what to say.''
   Police said Wednesday that Cadena's killer apparently didn't know
the 17-year veteran was an officer when he delivered bogus drugs to
Cadena. Cadena's assailant threw the fake drugs inside the car in
which the officer was sitting, then shot him at close range with a
semiautomatic rifle Tuesday.
   ``The drug was bunk,'' said narcotics division Capt. Eddie Walt
said. ``Essentially, they killed him for the fun of it.''
   Cadena, 43, was shot in the chest, abdomen and both arms. He was
pronounced dead at Baylor University Medical Center in Dallas about
30 minutes later.
   The drug suspect, Hector Rodriguez Jocimino, 36, of Dallas was
shot in the chest and back by a backup police officer, authorities
said. He died later at Parkland Memorial Hospital, said an emergency
room supervisor.
   Javier Suarez Medina, 20, was in serious condition at Parkland
with wounds to the chest and abdomen, while Fernando Fernandez, 17,
was in serious condition with wounds to both legs, hospital
officials said.
   Police said both Medina and Fernandez have been charged with
capital murder. Fernandez also was charged with unlawful delivery of
a controlled substance.
   Police Chief Mack Vines, who called Cadena a ``model officer,''
said that all of the officers apparently followed the correct
procedure during the undercover operation and that the presence of
additional backup officers probably would not have prevented the
shooting.
   Dallas police have been under fire from some city council members
and community minority leaders, who have accused police of being too
trigger-happy.
   A memorial service was planned for Cadena today at St. Patrick's
Catholic Church in Dallas.
</TEXT>
