<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cheerleader-Suit     12-15 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cheerleader-Suit,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paralyzed Cheerleader Settles Suit For $2.1 million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school cheerleader left paralyzed from
the waist down when she fell on a concrete floor while attempting a
difficult stunt will receive $2.1 million from the school district,
a teacher and former principal.
   The settlement involving Angie McAll, 18, was announced
Wednesday. Miss McAll was injured in 1987.
   ``She was a super athlete before she was hurt,'' said her
attorney, Robert Cunningham. ``She would be glad to give the money
back to get back in the condition she was in.''
   The settlement requires the county Board of School Commissioners'
insurance company to pay $100,000, the maximum the school system can
pay in a personal injury case.
   Insurance companies for the teacher supervising the cheerleaders,
Cynthia Stanley, and the former principal at Murphy High School,
Paul Sousa, settled at $1 million apiece.
   Miss McAll was injured when two girls tossed her into the air and
she attempted to land on another cheerleader's shoulders after
performing a back flip, Cunningham said. It was the first time she
had attempted the stunt.
   Miss McAll suffered a broken back and injured her spinal cord.
   The lawsuit alleged that the board allowed cheerleaders to
perform difficult gymnastic maneuvers without protective mats or
spotters to guard against falls. It also claimed cheerleaders did
not receive adequate training or supervision.
   Cunningham said the school system's cheerleader rules did not
mention safety.
   ``They had things about gum chewing, lengths of the cheerleaders'
skirts and gyrating motions,'' he added.
   Robert C. Campbell III, the board's attorney, said Miss McAll
``assumed the risk and and knew the dangers and plus she signed
waiver of liability'' in case of injury.
</TEXT>
