<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-USAmbassador 1stLd-Writethru a0497 12-15 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-US Ambassador, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Picked To Talk With PLO Was Once Palestinian Hostage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for grafs 7-8 pvs, ``Pelletreau's office ...''
to UPDATE with phone call to PLO; PICKS up 9th graf pvs, ``Between
foreign ...''
^With PM-Arafat, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert H. Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to
Tunisia assigned to open talks with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, is one of the most experienced and knowledgable
American diplomats on Arab affairs.
   Colleagues say he enjoys telling about the time he was held
hostage by Palestinian terrorists for several hours in 1970 as a
junior political officer in Amman, Jordan _ and walking away from
his captors.
   ``He loves to recount this story,'' a U.S. diplomat stationed in
Europe told The Associated Press, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``He was standing there as the press conference was going
on and he just walked away. He bears them no ill-will. It was a
great adventure.''
   Pelletreau, 53, of Patchogue, N.Y., is fluent in Arabic and
French, has served in U.S. embassies in Algeria, Morocco,
Mauritania, Lebanon, Jordan and Syria, and is a former ambassador to
Bahrain.
   He was named Wednesday by Secretary of State George P. Shultz as
the ``only authorized channel'' for what Shultz said would be a
``substantive dialogue'' with PLO representatives.
   The PLO political headquarters is in Tunis, the capital of the
North African Arab nation of Tunisia.
   Pelletreau's office referred calls today to the embassy press
office. Information Officer Adnan Siddiqi said the ambassador made a
brief telephone call to PLO headquarters to make the first contact.
He said he did not know when the first direct meeting would take
place.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat met East German officials in Berlin
today, and it was not known when he planned to return to Tunis.
   Between foreign postings, Pelletreau served in Washington as
director of Arabian peninsula affairs in the State Department and as
deputy assistant secretary of state for Middle East and South Asian
affairs.
   From 1985 until his assignment to Tunis in March 1987, Pelletreau
shifted over to the Pentagon to serve as deputy assistant secretary
of defense for Middle East and South Asian affairs.
   The anecdotal highlight of his career came in September 1970,
when guerrillas of George Habash's Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine _ a radical faction of the PLO _ diverted three
airliners to Amman and took the passengers and crews hostage.
   As Pelletreau has told the story to colleagues, he was kidnapped
on the streets of Amman by Popular Front guerrillas and taken with
other hostages to a large news conference at a downtown hotel.
   Noting his captors's attention was diverted, Pelletreau edged in
among the journalists, then slipped out and walked away, the
American diplomat said.
   When his absence was noticed, the guerrillas sent teams out
looking for him _ including one that passed him on the street _ but
he made it to safety in the U.S. Embassy.
   ``Those were in the innocent days,'' the diplomat recalled.
``It's almost hard to remember the days when you just didn't kill
diplomats.''
</TEXT>
