<DOCNO> AP881215-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     12-15 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Call to Postpone Elections, Tamils Threaten Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professional, civic and religious
leaders today urged the government to postpone presidential
elections because of ethnic violence that has claimed at least 88
lives this week.
   Separatist Tamil rebels called for a boycott of Monday's
balloting, blaming two main candidates for assassinations and
fighting that wracked this Indian Ocean island for five years.
   Also, soldiers said they captured an underground hide-out of
Sinhalese extremists waging a campaign of terror and intimidation to
overthrow the government. Four rebels were killed and 23
surrendered, said a military spokesman who insisted on anonymity.
   Hours earlier, he said, the Sinhalese radicals raided a southern
village and killed eight people. They left notes warning, ``This is
the fate of government spies.''
   The United Organization for Peace and Democracy, an umbrella
group for 30 professional, social and religious societies, said
President Junius R. Jayewardene should call off the elections
because of escalating violence by the the Sinhalese extremist group
the People's Liberation Front.
   A five-member opposition group called the Democratic People's
Alliance met with Jayewardene, leader of the United National Party,
on Wednesday. ``We asked him to put off the election as already we
feel it will not only not be fair and free but held under tension,''
said a spokesman.
   Jayewardene has not commented, but called a special Cabinet
meeting for Saturday.
   The front said the government cannot conduct a fair election and
urged the 9.3 million voters to boycott polling.
   Opposition politicians, the powerful Buddhist clergy and labor
organizations repeatedly have urged Jayewardene to help defuse the
crisis by forming a caretaker government of all political parties
and suspending emergency regulations imposed May 1983.
   Jayewardene, a Sinhalese, is prohibited by law from seeking a
third six-year term.
   The 82-year-old leader has said he will dissolve Parliament and
step aside Tuesday. Opposition leaders say that will be too late.
   Sinhalese extremists say a government peace accord offering
limited autonomy makes too many concessions to minority Tamils who
are fighting for a separate homeland in the north and east. Nearly
10,000 people have died since the war started in 1983.
   Mainly Hindu Tamils, who are 18 percent of the island's 16
million people, contend they are denied jobs, education and
development by the majority Buddhist Sinhalese.
   The biggest Tamil group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
today called for an election boycott. They charged the two main
candidates _ Ramasinghe Premadasa of the United National Party and
Sirimavo Bandaranaike of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party _ were
``instrumental in creating the ethnic conflict and have been
responsible for the genocide of Tamils.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
