<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Settlement,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castration Victim Sent Check by Insurance Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was castrated by two
intruders while awaiting trial on rape charges has reached a
$100,000 settlement in a lawsuit against a former sheriff who
displayed the man's testicles in a jar.
   Wayne Dumond, 39, convicted of rape and kidnapping in 1985 and
serving a sentence of life plus 20 years, plans to use part of the
money to pay legal fees in his appeal, said his attorney, John
Wesley Hall Jr.
   Dumond won a federal lawsuit in August against St. Francis County
and former Sheriff Coolidge Conlee, who was accused of displaying
Dumond's testicles in a jar of formaldehyde on his desk.
   Dumond, who was castrated at home by two masked intruders using
fishing line, claimed he was humiliated by Conlee's display and said
it forced him and his family to go into hiding. The intruders were
never caught.
   A federal jury awarded umond $150,000 in damages, but Hall
accepted a check Monday from Imperial Casualty Insurance Co. of
Omaha, Neb.
   ``We settled because the amount we got was so close to what we
were entitled to,'' he said. ``We gave them a little discount to get
the money now instead of waiting another year while they filed more
appeals.''
   Conlee was sentenced on Dec. 7 to 20 years in federal prison for
racketeering, gambling and extortion.
</TEXT>
