<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LawmakerSlaying     12-15 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lawmaker Slaying,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teenager Gets Life For Murdering Of Lawmaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA C. HUSLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was spared the electric chair and
sentenced to life in prison for murdering a state legislator with
blows from a hammer.
   Bernard Williams, 18, wiped away tears as he was taken in
shackles from the courthouse Wednesday after sentencing in the
robbery and slaying May 17 of Rep. William Telek, a 64-year-old
Republican from western Pennsylvania.
   Williams was convicted earlier Wednesday.
   The jury deadlocked on the death penalty, giving Judge John C.
Dowling no choice but to sentence Williams to life in prison without
chance of parole.
   Prosecutors said Williams beat Telek in the head, dumped his body
in a suburban street and stole about $100 and Telek's car after the
legislator left a late-night poker game. Williams was arrested later
that day, driving Telek's car.
   A hammer that witnesses said matched Telek's wounds was found in
Williams' bedroom.
   Williams testified that he he took the car from an acquaintance
and found the hammer in the car.
   The murder, believed to be the state's first involving a sitting
legislator, prompted a review of security at the Capitol. Telek was
last seen alive in the building's underground garage following the
card game.
   ``I'm innocent,'' Williams said. ``Why should I be happy to get
life for something I didn't do? If I'd have did it, I'd have pleaded
guilty to it.''
   Telek's widow, Leona Lee, said in a statement: ``In this case,
let's just say justice has prevailed.'
</TEXT>
