<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0515 12-15 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Favorable World Reaction To U.S.-PLO Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with reax from Britain, other nations,
new quotes, ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. decision to open a dialogue with
the PLO was hailed today in the Arab world and beyond as a step that
would advance peace in the Middle East. Some Palestinian refugees
wept for joy at the news.
   The Soviet Union, Britain, Italy and Japan were among nations
joining Arab states in expressing pleasure at the U.S. move,
announced Wednesday by Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Israel expressed shock and sorrow over the decision, saying it
would not serve the cause of peace.
   ``This is a great step by a great nation,'' said Mohammed
Milhelm, the former mayor of Halhoul in the occupied West Bank who
was expelled by Israel.
   ``One of the major roadblocks has now been removed to convening
an international conference and the peaceful co-existence between
all peoples and all religions and all states,'' he said.
   In Cairo, a senior Foreign Ministry official said Egypt welcomed
the U.S. move and considered it ``an important step and a positive
development on the road to a comprehensive peace in the region.
   ``Egypt played a big role in the developments and contacts that
led to this step,'' added the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Egypt's leading newspaper, the state-owned Al Ahram, hailed the
U.S. decision with an eight-column headline: ``Historic Development
Serving Peace Efforts in the Middle East.''
   The daily reported from Washington that the Shultz decision came
only hours after President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt phoned him ``to
urge him to take a positive attitude toward the constructive
decisions of the PLO.''
   In Geneva, Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky said
today the U.S. decision was ``a reasonable action going in the right
direction.''
   Britain welcomed the move in a statement by Foreign Office
Minister William Waldegrave, who said in Cairo: ``I welcome the fact
that the Americans share our analysis that the PLO has moved to
positions that represent real progress.''
   Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco de Mita, visiting Washington, said
``one cannot but express a positive attitude'' toward the
development, and Greek government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said
it ``creates very hopeful prospects'' for progress in the Middle
East. Japan and Australia also issued statements praising the U.S.
move.
   In Oslo, Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg of Norway was
quoted by the national NTB news agency as saying ``Israel's rigid
attitude toward the Palestine Liberation Organization is not serving
Israeli interests.''
   ``I will not be surprised if the Americans are fed up with
Israel's rigid attitude in the Middle East issue,'' he said. ``The
American willingness to start such a dialogue is an important step
in the direction of a peace conference and a solution of the Middle
East conflict.''
   George Habash, leader of the hardline PLO faction Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine, said, ``Although the U.S.
administration says that initiating the dialogue does not entail
recognition of Palestinian rights to ... an independent state, we
still welcome the latest development.''
   He said the U.S. move was taken ``so Washington could end the
diplomatic isolation that followed its refusal to grant (PLO)
Chairman Yasser Arafat a visa to go to New York (last month to
address the United Nations).''
   Habash's statement referred to ``Israel'' instead of ``the
Zionist entity,'' a phrase the Popular Front and other factions have
traditionally used to describe the Jewish state.
   Kamel Abu Jaber, head of Jordan's World Affairs Council, said the
U.S. decision had improved its image in the Arab world.
   ``It has just pulled the United States from the mud it has
planted itself in for the last 40 years ... and appears it is
heading in the right direction, for the benefit of the Palestinains
and the benefit of the Israelis,'' he declared.
   ``It has created a new reality with which the Israelis will live
and have to live,'' he noted.
   Beirut's leftist An-Nidaa daily was headlined: ``American Retreat
Under Blows of Stone-throwing Heroes.'' It referred to the yearlong
Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The official Saudi Arabian news agency announced the Shultz
decision with the headline, ``Finally, American-Palestinian
dialogue.''
   In the Hussein Palestinian refugee camp in Amman, accountant Said
Khalidy, 26, said, ``I never expected the United States would look
at us or care to find a solution to the Palestinian issue.
   ``At last the Reagan administration has done something worthwhile
... and it should be thanked for it.''
</TEXT>
