<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tibet-DutchWoman     12-15 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet-Dutch Woman,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Accuses Dutch Woman Of Breaking Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said today that a Dutch woman broke the law
by being at the scene of a Tibetan demonstration during which
Chinese police shot her in the arm.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said Christa Meindersma of
Amsterdam violated a law that forbids foreigners to mingle with
Tibetans during riots. She was among at least 13 people injured
during the protest Saturday in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, in which
Chinese officials said a Tibetan Buddhist monk was killed.
   Western witnesses said they saw two bodies, including that of a
small child, and that Tibetans told them seven people were killed.
   Li said Ms. Meindersma also violated customs regulations by
bringing into Lhasa a book by the Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled former
leader. The book, ``My Land And My People,'' is banned in China
because it advocates Tibet's independence from China.
   Ms. Meindersma told The Associated Press in a telephone interview
from Lhasa that she was reading the book to learn Tibetan. She said
police confiscated the book and her passport.
   Earlier this week authorities barred Ms. Meindersma from leaving
Lhasa, but gave her permission to leave Wednesday at the request of
the Dutch government.
   Ms. Meindersma, Schwartz and other Western witnesses said
Saturday's protest began when about 30 Tibetans walked silently into
Lhasa's central market square behind a monk carrying the banned flag
of pre-Communist Tibet.
   The witnesses said police opened fire on the crowd without
warning. China's official media maintains the police gave a warning
first and then fired in the air.
   Ms. Meindersma told the AP she stood not among the demonstrators
but with a large crowd of curious onlookers. She said police
continued firing at her and others even as they ran from the scene
in panic.
   Li refused to say if any formal charges had been brought against
Ms. Meindersma. But Willem de Bruin, adminstrative and consular
attache at the Dutch Embassy, said today that authorities told him
no charges would be filed.
   Li did not acknowledge that Ms. Meindersma was shot by police,
and only spoke of her being ``slightly injured.'' She said a bullet
entered her left arm and exited through her shoulder.
   Tibetan activists seeking the return of the Dalai Lama and an end
to 38 years of Chinese Communist rule have demonstrated repeatedly
over the past 14 months. Saturday's confrontation was the third
protest to end in bloodshed.
   According to Western travelers, at least 38 people were killed in
violent clashes with police on Oct. 1, 1987 and March 5.
   The Dalai Lama headed Tibet's civil administration before
Communist Chinese troops entered in 1950. He fled to India in 1959
during an abortive anti-Chinese uprising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
