<DOCNO> AP881215-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Symington 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 12-15 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Symington, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0514,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Split Denied Missourian Chance at White House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS throughout to ADD that Symington accepted the offer
and ADD background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Stuart Symington, a champion
and watchdog of the nation's military who died at age 87, was
offered _ then denied _ the No. 2 spot on the 1960 presidential
ticket with John F. Kennedy, a friend says.
   The former Missouri senator, who died Wednesday at his home in
New Canaan, Conn., was the nation's first Air Force secretary and
built a reputation as a principled politician. He died of heart
disease, said son James Symington.
   He was at first a champion of military air power and big military
outlays, but opposed the Vietnam War, became increasingly critical
of defense spending and ``excessive secrecy'' and was an opponent of
the F-14 fighter.
   Washington lawyer and former Defense Secretary Clark A. Clifford
recalled the 1960 Democratic convention and events that could have
made Symington vice president.
   ``The day before the decision was to be made, Senator Kennedy
said, `I'm now offering the No. 2 position to Senator Symington.
Take it to him and get back to me,''' he said.
   Clifford said Symington accepted but Kennedy backed out under
strong pressure to select a Southerner and went with Lyndon B.
Johnson of Texas.
   ``I took that back to Senator Symington,'' Clifford said. ``He
seemed very relaxed about it. He didn't seem to be hungering for it
(the nomination) anyway.''
   Symington served as a senator from 1953 until his retirement in
1977 and held various posts in the Truman administration, including
Air Force secretary in 1947-50 and assistant secretary of war for
air in 1946-47.
   He was a favorite-son candidate for the Democatic presidential
nomination in 1956 and 1960.
   Before that, he was a trouble-shooting industrialist summoned to
St. Louis to bring strike-plagued Emerson Electric Co. back to
financial prosperity in 1937.
   ``He exuded integrity,'' said U.S. District Judge William L.
Hungate, who served as a House Democrat from Missouri from 1964 to
1977. ``There was no question of any improprieties. No shadows ever
fell on Stuart Symington.''
   ``He was one of those tall trees whose falling will leave a great
vacant spot'' said former state Treasurer James Spainhower, a
Democrat.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., won Symington's seat after he
decided not to seek re-election in 1976. Symington resigned before
his term ended so Danforth would have the most seniority of the new
senators elected that year.
   ``To consider that he did this for someone who had run against
him, for someone of the other party, says a lot about this man,
about the bigness of the man and about his concern for our state,''
Danforth said.
   Symington was born in Amherst, Mass., in 1901. He graduated from
Yale University in 1923 and entered business.
   In 1978, Symington married Ann ``Nancy'' Hemingway Watson and
moved to New Caanan, a wealthy Connecticut community just north of
New York City. Symington's first wife, Evelyn Wadsworth Symington,
died in 1972.
   In addition to his wife and son, Symington is survived by another
son, Stuart Symington Jr., six grandchildren and six
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Bombs     12-15 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Bombs,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Blasts Injure 13 On Guerrilla Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least six bombs exploded today and late
Wednesday in Santiago and other cities, and police said 13 people
were injured. A leftist guerrilla group claimed responsibility.
   In the worst incident, a powerful bomb went off late Wednesday
night one block from the presidential palace, injuring five people.
   Military President Augusto Pinochet was not at the palace when
the explosion occurred.
   The Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic Front, a leftist urban guerrilla
group, said it planted the bombs to mark the fifth anniversary of
its founding Wednesday. A spokesman for the group telephoned several
news agencies, including The Associated Press.
   In Quilpue, a city 95 miles northwest of Santiago, a firebomb
planted at a public transportation depot totally destroyed a vehicle
Wednesday evening. Police said 8 people suffered minor burns.
   Several Santiago neighborhoods suffered blackouts which police
blamed on bombs.
   It was the second straight night of similar bomb attacks. At
least 10 bombs exploded Tuesday in Santiago and other cities,
causing property damage but no injuries.
   In another Wednesday night attack, a bomb partially destroyed a
small stretch of railroad track just south of Santiago, halting
traffic for several hours, according to police.
   Guerrillas also raided two small radio stations in Santiago and
the northern city of La Serena and briefly broadcast anti-government
slogans, police said.
</TEXT>
