<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Missiles     12-15 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Missiles,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Batch of Missiles Removed from West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEU ULM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army today removed nine
more U.S.-built Pershing 2 nuclear missiles from a base, the third
batch to be withdrawn from West Germany under the superpower treaty
signed a year ago.
   The missiles, under the control of the U.S. Army's 56th Field
Artillery Brigade, were loaded onto army trucks that departed Wiley
Barracks in Neu Ulm, 180 miles southeast of Frankfurt, in two
convoys.
   U.S. Army spokesman Major Jerry Hart said one convoy, carrying
first- and second-stage rocket motors and radar and guidance
systems, was being shipped to the United States where the motors
will be destroyed.
   The missile components to be flown to the United States were
packed in large metal containers, he said.
   ``A second convoy consisting of missile erector launchers left
about 9 a.m. and are on the way to the U.S. Army's Missile
Maintenance Center in Hausen, where they will be scheduled for
destruction,'' Hart said. Hausen is a Frankfurt suburb about 180
miles north of Neu Ulm.
   It was the third removal of Pershing II missiles under the
Intermediate Nuclear Forces Treaty signed by Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan in Washington last
December.
   The first batch of nine Pershing IIs were removed Sept. 1, from
Heilbronn, 120 miles southeast of Frankfurt. Nine more of the
missiles were withdrawn from Mutlangen, 24 miles east of Stuttgart,
on Nov. 15.
   Of those deployed, 108 Pershing 2 and 96 cruise missiles were
stationed at four bases in West Germany. All are to be removed by
May 31, 1991 under the superpower accord.
</TEXT>
