<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Church-Haiti     12-15 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church-Haiti,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roman Catholic Order Expels Activist Priest in Haiti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic order said today it had expelled an
activist priest in Haiti it accused of instigating violence and
exalting class warfare. The priest was the apparent target of a
September attack that killed 13 people.
   The Rev. Jean Bertrand Aristide had been at odds with superiors
of his Salesian order in Rome for some time. He had been ordered to
leave his homeland and go to Canada by Oct. 17.
   But Aristide, 35, defied the order and a spokesman for the
Salesian order, the Rev. Giuseppe Costa, said he is still on the
island.
   A communique by the Salesian Society of St. John Bosco said
Aristide has rebuffed repeated attempts to correct his behavior,
which they described as ``in contrast with his Salesian and priestly
vocation.''
   ``The type of political commitment he has assumed is in serious
contrast with the clear will of the founder (of the order). In
addition, the incitement to hate and violence, the exaltation of
class struggle, go directly against that fidelity to the (teaching)
of the church that forms a living part of the Salesian spirit.''
   It called him a ``destabilizing'' element for Haitian Roman
Catholics.
   Aristide has led calls for an uprooting of the vestiges of the
former regime of Jean-Claude Duvalier, who was overthrown in 1986.
   In September, Aristide was the apparent object of a bloody attack
on his church in the Haitian capital of Port-au-Prince during a
Sunday Mass by thugs linked to the ousted regime.
   Thirteen people were killed and more than 70 were wounded.
Aristide escaped.
   The massacre provoked another military coup, in which
rank-and-file soldiers ousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and replaced him
with Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril.
   The statement said the action by the order was ``painful'' but
that there was no way Aristide could remain a Salesian without
changing his ways.
   ``The Salesians continue to pray for Jean B. Aristide, still
nourishing the hope of a sincere fraternal embrace as soon as he
wants it,'' the statement said.
   The order's spokesman said the decree, which was ratified by the
Vatican last week, did not change Aristide's status as a priest.
</TEXT>
