<HEAD>Judge Argues Defense Attorneys On Wrong Track In James Brown Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony; Picks up
6th graf, `The singer ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Brown failed to heed an officer's
flashing blue lights and siren, the lawman testified today at the
soul singer's assault trial.
   Sheriff's Deputy Donald Danner said he pulled alongside Brown's
truck several times Sept. 24 and the singer swerved as if trying to
run him off the road.
   Brown, known as the Godfather of Soul, also allegedly attempted
to run over two North Augusta Public Safety officers. He is charged
with assault with intent to kill and failure to stop for police.
   Brown ``had a total disregard for his surroundings,'' Danner said
in his report of that day's events.
   Brown, 55, testified Wednesday that he didn't pull over during
the chase through Augusta, Ga., and North Augusta, S.C., because,
``I was scared to death.''
   ``I went to Vietnam and I wasn't that frightened,'' he said.
   Brown said he initially wasn't aware of the first two officers
who attempted to pull him over. Brown seemed somewhat confused about
the sequence of events.
   The singer, wearing a gray suit and blue satin shirt, testified
that he didn't remember driving more than 80 mph. When he did stop,
he said, the officers scared him by shooting at his truck and
banging on the windows.
   Meanwhile, Judge Hubert Long rejected defense arguments that
authorities acted recklessly during the pursuit.
   ``Even if the officers made a mistake and endangered the public,
I don't see what that has to do with ... a man who failed to stop
for a blue light,'' the judge said.
   Brown could receive up to 30 years in prison if convicted.
</TEXT>
