<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Chairman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Candidate Undermined by Own Governor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with later Blanchard comment, inserting new grafs 4-5</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan state Democratic chairman Richard
Wiener's campaign to become national party chairman suffered a blow
at the hands of his own governor just as the battle for the top
party job widened.
   Wiener has been regarded as one of the leading contenders to
succeed retiring Democratic national chairman Paul Kirk. But
Michigan Gov. James Blanchard's remark Wednesday that he lacks the
stature required for the post was widely viewed as damaging his
prospects.
   ``I like Rick. He did a great job here in Michigan and is a dear
friend,'' Blanchard told The Detroit News. ``But there is obviously
a strong feeling that the chairman ought to be a presidential type
of candidate, a party spokesman who can be on television responding
to George Bush, a person of existing national stature.''
   Blanchard, in an interview with the Associated Press later, said
he did not intend his remarks as criticism of Wiener and regarded
him as a good choice ``if we're looking for a nuts-and-bolts guy.''
   Blanchard said he was not yet endorsing any of the candidates
because as chairman of the Democratic Governors Association he wants
to consult with the other governors.
   The race for the Democratic chairmanship widened as two more
candidates, former Reps. James R. Jones of Oklahoma and Michael
Barnes of Maryland, formally announced.
   A third candidate, former top Jesse Jackson aide Ronald H. Brown,
rounded up the endorsement of former presidential candidate Bruce
Babbitt in his attempt to establish broader credentials in the party.
   Wiener sought to put the best face on Blanchard's comment, saying
it was candid and positive.
   ``What I have done throughout my professional career is put
together campaigns and later a state party that has elected a lot of
people,'' Wiener said.
   Jones, a longtime party insider, said he hoped to avoid a
divisive free-for-all that some are predicting would pit the Jackson
wing of the party against Southerners, conservatives and moderates.
   ``I think there is a myth that this is a blood-bath type of
election,'' Jones said.
   The nearly 400 voting members of the Democratic National
Committee will select a new chairman to replace Kirk when they meet
in Washington on Feb. 9 and 10.
   Babbitt endorsed Brown in a letter to committee members. He said
Brown would not be ``a stalking horse for Jesse Jackson'' but an
effective party builder.
   Jones, former chairman of the House Budget Committee, is a
moderate-to-conservative Democrat who said he would draw on a base
of support among Democrats in the South and West.
   ``My Southern and Western roots place me at the center of our
party's beliefs and ideals,'' he said in a statement.
   Also a factor, however, is a move by Alabama party chairman John
Baker and others to have a current member of Congress, such as Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, serve as chairman. But that would require a
change of the party's charter to permit a part-time chairman, a
difficult maneuver needing a two-thirds vote of the committee.
   Jones said he believed he had more than 100 votes among the
committee members so far but acknowledged some were not firm
commitments. The race is expected to be expensive, and Jones said he
is prepared to spend as much as Brown _ perhaps $150,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
