<HEAD>No Hero's Welcome For Rescue Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of dogs sent to Soviet
Armenia to help rescue earthquake victims are angry because the
animals will be placed in quarantine for four months when they
return, news reports said Thursday.
   ``I have a dog at home. If the two dogs are apart for four
months, they won't be able to work as a team when they get back
together again,'' Nils Karlsson, who sent one dog to Armenia, told
the national news agency TT.
   ``Completely scandalous,'' Agneta Eriksson was quoted as saying
from Leninakan, U.S.S.R., where her dog Raffi was searching for
victims.
   The 16 animals, all volunteered for service by their owners, are
credited with finding 14 people so far in the rubble of the
devastated Soviet cities.
   Sweden's animal quarantine laws are among the strictest in
Europe, and they are credited with making the country rabies-free.
Stig Sjostedt, a director of the Rescue Office, said the quarantine
would be enforced, but planned to talk to each dog owner and explain
the necessity for the move.
</TEXT>
