<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--India-VotingAge     12-15 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--India-Voting Age,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Lawmakers Vote To Lower Voting Age to 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lower house of Parliament on Thursday
approved a constitutional amendment to lower the voting age from 21
to 18.
   The measure, which must be approved by the upper house and
President Ramaswamy Venkataraman, would make as many as 50 million
largely educated, young people eligible to cast ballots in next
year's general elections.
   All 544 members of the Lok Sabha, or lower house, approved the
bill, which has the support of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, members
of his governing Congress Party and opposition politicians.
   ``We have full faith in the youth of the country. They have shown
their wisdom and maturity. They are now ready to take part in the
electoral process,'' Gandhi told legislators, who applauded.
   The amendment is part of a package of electoral reforms
introduced last month in Parliament. It says that ``lowering of the
voting age would provide to the unrepresented youth of the country
an opportunity to give vent to their feelings and help them become a
part of the political process.''
</TEXT>
