<HEAD>Two Youths Steal Vatican Payroll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two youths on motorbikes blocked a Vatican
car near St. Peter's Square on Thursday, smashed the back window and
made off with a payroll of nearly $300,000 in cash and checks,
police reported.
   The car had just picked up the money at the Vatican bank inside
the walls of the tiny city-state and was delivering it to the
Congregation for the Eastern Church to pay salaries, police said.
   The robbery occurred near the entrance to the congregation's
headquarters on Via della Conciliazione, 100 yards from St. Peter's
Square.
   Police said the money was in an attache case on the rear seat of
the Fiat Ritmo. The youths escaped on their motorbikes, speeding
through the narrow streets near the Vatican.
   The driver of the car, Cristiano Codado, 40, was not harmed.
   The Eastern Church congregation supervises rites, discipline and
officials of Eastern rite churches around the world.
