<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0545,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Arrives For Court Appearance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with bond set, comments from attorneys;
PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Bakker, 48 ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Jim Bakker today said
``electronic ministry'' itself is on trial after the TV evangelist's
first court appearance since his indictment on charges of defrauding
PTL contributors.
   U.S. Magistrate Paul Taylor set unsecured bond of $50,000 for
Bakker and three former aides, and scheduled a court appearance for
Bakker and Richard Dortch on Jan. 17, when they will enter pleas to
fraud and conspiracy charges.
   The defrocked PTL leader and one-time aides are accused of
diverting more than $5 million in contributions to the evangelical
empire in order to live in luxury. Bakker's wife, Tammy, did not
accompany him today; she was not indicted.
   ``I am not guilty of these charges and I'm looking forward to due
process taking place. If I get a fair trial, we can win this case,''
Bakker said after court.
   ``Bakker is not the only one on trial,'' his attorney George T.
Davis said. ``His wife is on trial and the whole ministry _ the
electronic ministry _ is on trial. ''
   Bakker, Dortch and David and James Taggart were indicted Dec. 5
after a 16-month federal grand jury investigation of PTL's finances
before Bakker left the evangelical empire in a sex and money scandal.
   Dortch is Bakker's former top deputy. David Taggart is Bakker's
former personal aide and James Taggart PTL's one-time interior
decorator.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jerry Miller told Taylor today that no
additional charges were expected against Bakker and Dortch.
   The Taggarts pleaded innocent today to charges of tax evasion.
They are accused of using more than $1.1 million in PTL money for
personal expenditures. Taylor tentatively scheduled their trial for
the last week of January.
   Jim Toms, another Bakker attorney, said he does not expect his
client to enter a plea until next month. Toms said previously that
Bakker would plead innocent.
   Bakker, 48, resigned in 1987 amid revelations he had a sexual
encounter with former church secretary Jessica Hahn and paid her
hush money. Three months later, amid reports of financial
wrongdoing, PTL filed for bankruptcy protection.
   On Tuesday, Canadian real estate magnate Stephen Mernick bought
PTL's assets, including its Christian theme park, hotel and
broadcast studios in Fort Mill, S.C., for $65 million in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court.
   The fate of the PTL's religious operations, which were spun off
by the court into the non-profit Heritage Ministries, remained
unclear. Heritage Ministries uses facilities at the theme park.
</TEXT>
