<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Oldest Man,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy's `Oldest Man' Dies At 109</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUPAZZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giovanni Ferzini, described as the oldest
man in Italy, died of bronchitis, his family said Thursday. He was
109.
   He died Wednesday in a village south of Parma, the family said.
   Ferzini, who was born July 23, 1879, left his village only once,
and that was when he was an infantryman in World War I.
   After the war he returned to the Lupazzano, married and fathered
13 sons. Seven of his sons surrvived him.
   Ferzini was a farmer and an avid hunter who continued to walk the
fields and shoot at game until age 93. He used to say that he missed
the old times, when the air was clean and there was plenty of game.
   A recent survey of Italian municipalities called him the oldest
Italian.
   Lupazzano is a tiny village of 200 inhabitants in a hilly area
renowned for the production and the seasoning of ham.
</TEXT>
