<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Korea-Soviet,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Moscow Will Allow KAL Planes To Fly Over Soviet Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will soon allow
Korea's national airline to send commercial jets through Soviet
airspace and make refueling stops in Moscow, a newspaper reported
Thursday.
   The newspaper, Hankook Ilbo, said Cho Chung-kun, president of
Korean Air, will visit Moscow later this month to work out details
of the agreement.
   KAL neither confirmed nor denied the report.
   The Soviet Union, which has no diplomatic relations with South
Korea, temporarily allowed KAL planes to fly over its territory to
transport European and African athletes to the 1988 Summer Olympics
in Seoul this fall.
   Officials of the two countries have been negotiating ever since
to extend the decision, but the Soviet Union _ which is closely
allied with Seoul's archrival, North Korea _ has been reluctant to
do so, the paper said.
   The proposed agreement would save KAL flights two to four hours
on routes to Paris and Frankfurt, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
