<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-InvestmentFundLoss     12-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Investment Fund Loss,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>W.Va. Loses $200 Million From Investment Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state treasurer has asked the
federal government to investigate an unexplained $200 million loss
in West Virginia's investment fund for local governments.
   The loss has sparked a run on the fund by the local governments,
which have withdrawn more than $100 million in the past three days.
   Three annual reports show that investments in the consolidated
investment fund's ``pool 100'' totaled $773.3 million in 1986. That
figure dropped to $574.1 million a year later, a decrease of $199.2
million.
   No one can say whether the loss represents reduced interest _
money the state thought it would earn but didn't _ or an actual loss
in funds invested.
   The fund was earning a high rate of interest _ up to 13 percent
or more _ during the period when the loss occurred, according to two
annual reports for the state Board of Investments and one from the
state treasurer's office.
   State, county and municipal governments put their money into the
pool, which the state then invests for them.
   Treasurer A. James Manchin on Tuesday urged a federal
investigation into why the fund, which his office manages, suffered
the loss.
   U.S. Attorney Michael Carey said he has passed on to the FBI
Manchin's request that officials determine whether an investigation
is warranted. The FBI has not said whether it will investigate.
   Manchin said he does not believe any criminal wrongdoing is
involved, just ``bad investments.''
   Other probes, including one by the accounting firm of Touche Ross
& Co., are under way.
   Over the past three days, local governments have withdrawn $108.9
million _ including $41.3 million Wednesday _ in reaction to reports
of the loss.
   Several key people involved in the $200 million loss refuse to
discuss it.
   Associate Treasurer Arnold T. Margolin, who was in charge of
investments, has said he alerted Manchin to the problem and is
awaiting the results of the Touche Ross probe.
   Manchin oversees all state investments but accused Margolin of
not handling the investments properly. He said staff members of the
investments office warned Margolin in 1987 that there was a problem,
but he said Margolin _ who has resigned to become an administrative
aide to Gov.-elect Gaston Caperton _ ignored them.
   Manchin has refused to accept Margolin's resignation until the
loss is cleared up.
   Former Assistant Treasurer Kathy Lester, who actually made the
investments for Margolin, disappeared after quitting the treasurer's
office in late 1987.
   Gov. Arch Moore, chairman of the Board of Investments, has
declined to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
