<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-GreatTrek     12-15 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Great Trek,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afrikaners To Celebrate 150th Anniversary of Pioneer Trek</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just before dawn Friday, a few
dozen bearded men in leather clothes will take cover behind ox-drawn
wagons and fight an imaginary battle against a long-ago defeated
Zulu army.
   The pageant by members of right-wing Afrikaner cultural and
political groups will celebrate the Battle of Blood River and the
150th anniversary of the Great Trek that brought the Dutch-descended
pioneers out of the British-ruled Cape Colony into the African
wilderness.
   It won't matter that the make-believe battle won't be seen by
very many people or that it is being staged 20 miles from the
government's main celebration at the Pioneer Monument overlooking
Pretoria.
   Most of the events and celebrations are symbolic, and in South
Africa there are many ways of interpreting them.
   Depending on the interpretation, the 1838 departure of the
pioneer families was undertaken to avoid Britain's abolition of
slavery, to set up a free republic in an unpopulated land, to bring
Christianity and civilization to African tribes, or to steal the
land of blacks and force them into subjugation.
   Stories about life on the trek, battles, and religious faith have
taken on mythical proportions in the folklore of Afrikaners, the
descendants of the pioneers who now dominate the government.
   The 100th anniversary commemoration in 1938 united Afrikaners,
gave impetus to their cultural and political organizations and
propelled them to power in the Nationalist Party parliamentary
victory 10 years later.
   The right-wingers regard the gradual and limited reforms of
apartheid now being made by today's Nationalist government as a
betrayal of white rights. They hope this year's celebration will be
a catalyst leading to the ouster of the Nationalists and victory for
the Conservative Party and its allies.
   A speech by President P.W. Botha to crowds of picnickers at the
Pioneer Monument will be broadcast live on national television.
   The celebrations are the culmination of a four-month re-enactment
of the Great Trek by wagons and oxen that converged on Pretoria this
week.
   Twenty miles away in Donkerhoek, the opposition Conservative
Party, its supporters and right-wing groups such as the Nazi-style
Afrikaner Reform Movement will be carrying on a more traditional
celebration.
   The right-wingers will dress in 19th-century clothes, listen to
poetry and history readings and hold square-dances and sing-a-longs.
   The Day of the Vow, Dec. 16, is considered a sacred national
holiday.
   It commemorates the 1838 battle at Blood River in Zululand when
one of the pioneer groups vowed to keep the day forever holy if they
won the battle against the Zulu King Dingaan the next morning. They
did.
   Most of South Africa's black majority of 26 million, who have no
vote in national affairs, do not celebrate the holiday, although
they don't work on the day because the country virtually closes down.
   A few blacks have participated in the government-sponsored
re-enactment as oxen drivers. But the right-wingers have no blacks
in their festivities.
   A coalition of anti-apartheid groups said it would celebrate the
day from the view of the losing side in the battle. Blacks,
celebrating what they call Heroes Day, will meet in the tribal
homeland of KaNgwane to pay homage to the chiefs who fought the
whites in the 18th and 19th centuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
