<DOCNO> AP881215-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     12-15 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Militia Stirs Fears In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIANG, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Levetico Diwa, a 51-year-old
grandfather, crawled through the brush with his rifle, training to
fight communists because he believes they routinely kill old and
unproductive people.
   Diwa is one of 150,000 volunteers the military hopes to recruit
into a new militia it describes as essential to defeat communist
rebels. Critics fear a new paramilitary will increase human rights
abuses against civilians.
   Military plans call for the Citizens' Armed Forces Geographical
Unit to consolidate under one banner hundreds of paramilitary and
anti-communist vigilante groups to protect villages against the
communist New People's Army. This will help extend government
control and curb rights abuses, officials say.
   In a report today, the London-based group Amnesty International
said legal safeguards are being ignored and that it has documented
evidence of torture and illegal detentions by police, soldiers and
paramilitary forces.
   Human rights groups in the Philippines and political commentators
also question the wisdom of arming thousands more civilians.
   ``The trend toward militarization makes people think the only way
to contend with our problems is through a military solution,'' said
one prominent human rights activist, Mariss Diokno. ``We did not
expect that the vigilante groups would be dismantled and be replaced
by another group.''
   But officers training Diwa and more than 80 other volunteers on
the Bataan Peninsula, 30 miles west of Manila, claim the new unit is
different.
   Diwa and the other recruits are lectured on the human rights that
are guaranteed by the constitution. Regular and non-commissioned
officers will command the new units to ensure they follow
regulations, officials said.
   Like Diwa, most of the volunteers at the makeshift camp in Liang
were peasant farmers aged 18 to 55. Diwa said in an interview that
he joined because he believes that under communism, ``if you are old
and unproductive, then they will kill you.'' He said this notion has
been reinforced by military officers' lectures on the ``evils of
communism.''
   At the camp, trainees undergo a five-week crash course including
weapons training, basic infantry tactics, self-defense and first aid.
   After graduating, paramilitary troops move to villages where they
live with the people, defend them and gather information on rebels
for the army. They get 90 cents a day plus clothing, medical care,
housing and firearms.
   The army ``does not have sufficient manpower to ensure the
security of every village,'' Col. Ramsey Ocampo, constabulary
commander for Bataan, said in a recent interview. Regular troops
will clear areas of rebels and the paramilitary will follow to
maintain government control, he said.
   The government says rebels virtually control 7,800 of the
country's 40,832 villages. ``It just depends on who gets there
first,'' said a communist political officer who spoke on condition
of anonymity. He said the paramilitary would be most effective in
areas that have not been infiltrated.
   Fears about the new unit stem from the Civilian Home Defense
Force, a paramilitary force that was established by former President
Ferdinand Marcos and that became notorious for rights abuses.
   President Corazon Aquino, who replaced Marcos after a
military-civilian uprising, promised to disband that force during
her 1986 election campaign and now says it will be phased out as the
new paramilitary unit is deployed.
   But military officers admit privately that they often turn to
paramilitary veterans to find enough recruits for the new unit.
   Abelardo Torno, a trainee in Pampanga province, said he has
belonged to anti-communist militias since the 1960s, including 17
years in the Home Defense Force. ``All they did was change the
name,'' said an officer who stood nearby.
</TEXT>
