<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Arafat 7thLd-Writethru a0563 12-15 1172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Arafat, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0563,1180</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>US Starts Talking To PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he would not
hesitate to ``break off communications'' with the Palestine
Liberation Organization if it reneged on its declarations to
renounce terrorism and accept Israel's right to exist.
   Reagan defended his decision to permit a dialogue between U.S.
officials and Yasser Arafat's PLO, reversing a 12-year U.S.
government policy, telling reporters that ``words have been spoken''
that spelled out the PLO's acceptance of U.S. conditions for direct
talks.
   The president also said that he didn't think Israel had any
reason to be upset by the U.S. decision because ``we have made it
very plain that we have not retreated one inch from our position of
guaranteeing the safety'' of the Jewish state.
   The president talked to reporters twice, during picture-taking
sessions in the Oval Office with Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal
and later with Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco de Mita. He spoke
after U.S. officials quickly followed through on the reversal of the
longstanding policy against talks with the PLO, seeking an early
meeting.
   A senior State Department official said he hoped that would lead
to direct Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   President-elect George Bush said today he supported the
president's decision. He added:
   ``I haven't spelled out any hopes about it. Arafat met the
conditions of the United States and we will go forward with a
dialogue, not negotiations, but a dialogue. ... Let's see how things
evolve.''
   As for the discussions, he said, ``There's no game plan; there's
no five-point program.''
   Asked if he would prefer that the talks wait until his
administration starts next month, Bush replied, ``I am vice
president of the United States. I become president on Jan. 20. On
Jan. 21, I'll tell you what I want to do.''
   Reagan said the administration made its move after it became
satisfied that PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, in a news conference in
Geneva Wednesday, had complied with the American conditions for a
dialogue with his organization.
   Asked today to explain the policy reversal, Reagan replied,
``Well, because the words have been spoken, and the words were the
words that we have been stating were necessary.''
   But he quickly added that ``of course, ... the words must be
matched by performance, and if they're not, why, we're back where we
started.'' Asked a short time later what he would do if the PLO
failed to live up to its statements, the president replied, ``Well,
we'd certainly break off communications.''
   Asked if such direct U.S.-PLO contacts could achieve anything in
view of opposition by the Israeli government, he said ``the ultimate
solution does not depend on outsiders or us. Peace must be brought
about by the involved nations meeting with each other and settling
their differences.''
   Asked why the United States does not recognize a Palestinian
state, Reagan said, ``Well, because there is no such thing as of
now. There isn't a Palestinian state. And if you recognize someone
... as that, it would be us declaring who was in charge there.''
   Reagan said the move was ``just another step in what we've been
trying for eight years _ to bring about peace in the Middle East.''
   The U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert H. Pelletreau Jr., who was
assigned to open the historic ``substantive dialogue'' with the PLO,
called the director general of the political section at the PLO's
Tunis headquarters to try to make arrangements for the talks, a U.S.
official said.
   While no date was set, ``we're sure the PLO will try hard to have
them take place as soon as possible, '' said the official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   ``But right now, the time, the place and the level have not been
set,'' he said.
   Another U.S. official said the session could be held as early as
tomorrow, and certainly within the next few days.
   He said Tunis was the logical site and he doubted that a senior
PLO official would participate at this stage.
   So far as the topics, the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said ``we have our agenda of things to talk to the PLO
about. First among them is the issue of terrorism. And how you get
to peace negotiations.''
   On Capitol Hill:
   _Sen. George Mitchell, the newly elected Senate majority leader,
welcomed the U.S. move as a ``significant step toward advancing the
peace process.''
   The Maine senator said that Arafat's acceptance of Israel's right
to exist and renouncement of terrorism were ``important statements''
but that ``in light of the PLO's record ... must be viewed with
caution.''
   _The current majority leader, Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., praised the
decision to open a dialogue with the PLO, calling the organization's
new position ``an opportunity that must be pushed forward despite
the risks.''
   ``Our commitment to Israel is firm and unswerving,'' he said in a
written statement. ``But it must be tempered by the realization that
there are times when we must take those first tenuous steps toward
peace.''
   _House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla.,
sought to reassure Israel, saying that continued aid to Israel, the
top recipient of U.S. assistance, is necessary both to calm Israeli
fears and ``as a clear signal to the PLO and other parties that the
United States is committed firmly to the independence of Israel
within secure borders.''
   The announcement Wednesday night left Israel in diplomatic
isolation and came just a few hours after Bush had taken a tough
line against the PLO, declaring that it had not met U.S. conditions
for direct dealings.
   But Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz said that
Arafat, in statements made in Geneva about the same time that Bush
was speaking, had met the U.S. conditions for a ``substantive
dialogue'' _ a form of diplomatic acceptance long sought by the
Palestinian group.
   Only a day earlier, the State Department had said Arafat failed
to meet the U.S. conditions. And less than three weeks ago, Shultz
had accused the PLO of terrorism and said Arafat was ``an accessory
to such terrorism.''
   Shultz, asked Wednesday if he had changed his mind on that
subject, said the PLO had issued a statement Wednesday that ``was
clear; it was not encumbered.''
   He said Arafat's group had accepted U.N. Security Council
resolutions 242 and 338, recognized Israel's right to exist in peace
and security, and renounced terrorism.
   ``As a result,'' Shultz said, ``the United States is prepared for
a substantive dialogue with PLO representatives.''
   Bush just a few hours earlier had demanded that the PLO satisfy
U.S. demands.
   ``I want a clear statement on renunciation of terror,'' Bush
said. ``I want a very clear, unambiguous statement on the right of
Israel to exist as a state, and I want a clear endorsement of
Security Council resolution 242.''
   The U.N. resolutions, adopted in 1967 and 1973, affirm the right
of all states in the Middle East to live in peace. Israel is not
specifically mentioned.
</TEXT>
