<1ST_LINE>u w PM-BushRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 12-15 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says of PLO Talks: ``Let's See How Things Evolve''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 6 grafs with Bush on PLO dialogue, picking up
in 2nd graf pvs, Bush said; deletes 11th graf pvs, Said Palestine</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush said today he
supports President Reagan's decision to begin talks with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, but he cautioned, ``Let's see how
things evolve ... there's no game plan.''
   Bush said Wednesday that PLO leader Yasser Arafat had made ``some
movement'' in a speech Tuesday but not enough to warrant direct
dealings with the PLO by the United States. Later, however, after
administration officials went over new Arafat comments on Israel and
the Middle East, Reagan said the United States would enter into ``a
substantive dialogue'' with the PLO.
   ``The conditions that the American government set out have been
consistent, steadfast and now Mr. Arafat says that those conditions
are met,'' Bush said today. ``So we will observe, we will watch and
our ambassador in Tunisia will begin a dialogue. There's no game
plan, there's no five-point program.''
   Asked if he preferred that the talks wait until he takes office
next month, Bush replied, ``I am vice president of the United
States. I become president on Jan. 20. On Jan. 21 I'll tell you what
I want to do.''
   ``I support the president's decision. Let's see how things
evolve. My position remains the same. I want to see direct talks
between, for example, between King Hussein of Jordan and the
Israelis,'' Bush said.
   One day earlier, Bush took another step in forming his new
administration, naming his choice for agriculture secretary. He also
said John Tower could be an outstanding secretary of defense and he
doubted that an FBI check had turned up anything to disqualify the
former Texas senator.
   Bush said he has not yet decided who will run the Pentagon,
although sources said Tower remained the leading candidate.
   With eight more appointments to go, Bush hopes to complete naming
his Cabinet before Christmas.
   Bush tapped Clayton Yeutter on Wednesday as the sixth member of
his Cabinet. Yeutter, the U.S. trade representative for President
Reagan, will be secretary of agriculture.
   After three years in government, Yeutter had wanted to return to
private business. Standing alongside Bush at a news conference,
Yeutter said there were ``only a few people in the world who could
convince me to carry forward in another stint in government, but
you're one of those few.''
   Bush also said he would name a black to his Cabinet. He has been
urged by some black supporters to name Louis W. Sullivan, a black
who is president of Morehouse School of Medicine, as secretary of
Health and Human Services.
   In addition, The Washington Post reported in today's editions
that another black, Julius W. Becton Jr., a retired three-star Army
general who heads the Federal Emergency Management Agency, is the
top contender to head the Veterans Administration, and that a
Hispanic member of the Federal Communications Commission, Patricia
Diaz Dennis, is a candidate to head the Labor Department.
   Also, an aide to Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., who lost his
re-election bid last month, confirmed that the senator has met with
Bush about possibly taking over the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   Covering a wide range of topics at the news conference, Bush also:
   _Hinted his administration will seek a delay in February's
resumption of arms control talks with the Soviet Union. ``There is
no way that we are going to have by Feb. 15 or 16 a detailed
point-by-point program on arms talks,'' Bush said.
   _Said Vice President-elect Dan Quayle's role would be ``very much
like the Reagan-Bush relationship.'' He said Quayle would be a ``key
player'' in national security affairs if he wants to be and that
there may be specific assignments in other areas.
   _Said he would not seek substantial cuts in existing farm
programs but didn't say what he meant by substantial. ``I do not
believe we will balance the budget eventually on the backs of
farmers,'' he said.
   Yeutter, 58, a onetime Nebraska farmer, was the fifth veteran of
the Reagan administration to join Bush's incoming Cabinet.
   Asked how Yeutter's selection squared with his promise to bring a
new team of people to Washington, Bush said, ``Well, his face is
familiar, but the job is very different than being trade
representative.''
   He promised anew to bring in some unfamiliar faces.
   However, Tower is a familiar figure, a onetime senator from Texas
who was an arms negotiator in Geneva for Reagan. Even before the end
of the presidential campaign, Tower was at the top of Bush's list to
run the Pentagon, but his appointment has been delayed by an
extensive background check of his dealings with defense contractors
and aspects of his personal life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
