<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--PeanutQuota     12-15 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Peanut Quota,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peanut Quota Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national peanut marketing quota for 1989
will be 1.44 million tons, up 37,800 tons from last year's quota,
the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Officials said the quota for 1989 was unchanged from the level
proposed last month. By law, USDA is required to announce a final
decision on the proposed quota by Dec. 15.
   The national quota is required by law to be equal to the
estimated quantity of peanuts that will be needed for domestic
edible, seed and related uses in the 1989-90 marketing year, which
will begin Aug. 1, 1989. The quota cannot be less than 1.1 million
tons.
   Officials said the 1989 poundage quota will be allocated to each
producing state based on the state's share of the 1988 quota.
Increases in a state's quota will be allocated among qualifying
peanut farms.
   Peanut farmers voted in a referendum in January 1986 to continue
the quota for crops through 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
