<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     12-15 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Davis Drops From Race, Supports Evans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black alderman dropped out of the race for mayor
Thursday, warning of a return to ``machine politics'' unless blacks
can agree upon a candidate to oppose the son of the late Mayor
Richard J. Daley.
   In announcing his withdrawal, Alderman Danny Davis predicted Cook
County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley, son of the legendary
political boss, would ``without a doubt'' win the April 4 mayor's
race unless either Alderman Timothy Evans or Mayor Eugene Sawyer,
both of whom are black, drop out of the race.
   Davis gave his support to Evans, who was the leading black
candidate in a recent newspaper poll.
   Daley is considered the front-runner, based on recent polls.
Sawyer, Evans and Daley square off in a Feb. 28 Democratic primary.
   A Daley administration, according to Davis, would be a
``reinstitution of what we call plantation politics in many areas of
Chicago. Feudal system politics ... where clout becomes the passport
to city services, clout becomes the passport to jobs, clout becomes
the passport to benefits.''
   David Wilhelm, Daley's campaign manager, called Davis' comments
``unfortunate,'' and said, ``they're talking about the past. Our
campaign is focused on the future.''
   Sawyer, elected mayor by the City Council after the death last
November of Harold Washington, has raised more than $2 million for
his campaign. But Davis said he never considered endorsing Sawyer.
   ``The Evans support comes from the progressive, the activist base
group of the coalition that generated and sustained the Washington
era,'' Davis said. ``So I would have a much greater feeling that
machine influence would not play nearly as much of a role in an
Evans administration as it would in a Sawyer administration.''
   A Chicago Tribune poll taken Dec. 2-5 of 1,038 registered voters
indicated that of 12 declared or potential candidates, Daley was the
choice of 29 percent. Evans had 17 percent, Sawyer had 10 percent
and Jesse Jackson, who is not a candidate, had 10 percent.
   In that poll, which had an error range of 3 percentage points,
Davis received 3 percent of the votes.
   Winning the Democratic primary generally has been tantamount to
winning the general election in Chicago's recent history. That
changed somewhat in 1983 when Republican Bernard Epton made a strong
showing in a losing effort against Washington.
</TEXT>
