<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-ChildVictims     12-15 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Child Victims,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Find First Body In Serial Child Abductions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found the naked body of a 4-year-old girl in
a campground near Tokyo on Thursday, the first confirmed death in a
series of crimes against children that have traumatized the city's
suburbs.
   A 7-year-old girl and another 4-year-old remain missing in
Saitama prefecture west of Tokyo in a series of disappearances that
began in August.
   Six times since October, children at play have been stabbed by
strangers in Saitama and in Chiba prefecture, east of the capital.
None of the stabbing victims, ranging in age from 2 to 4, was
fatally injured.
   Police said they are treating the incidents as cases of sexual
perversion.
   The stabbings and abductions of toddlers by unidentified stalkers
have caused panic in the normally placid suburbs. In a country that
prides itself on a low crime rate, the crimes also have attracted
the nation's attention.
   ``I never thought a thing like this could happen here,'' a
housewife told the Japan Broadcasting Corp. the night before Erika
Namba's naked body was found in a campground 20 miles from her home.
``We moved here because we thought this would be a good place to
raise children.''
   Police searched the campground after officials there reported
finding articles of clothing with Erika's name on them.
   In the middle-class developments where the missing girls lived,
hundreds of office workers and high school students have joined
police in fruitless searches of playgrounds and nearby scrubland.
   Housewives have posted fliers bearing likenesses of the girls,
all of whom disappeared in the bustling neighborhoods in the
afternoon hours after school let out and before darkness fell.
   Police helicopters and patrol cars have broadcast warnings urging
children to get home before dark, and school principals have
admonished pupils to avoid strangers and see each other home.
   But despite a combined turnout of almost 6,000 police officers in
Chiba and a similar number in Saitama, police report no arrests and
few leads.
   On Wednesday, they released a drawing _ based on another child's
description _ of a man seen with Erika shortly before she
disappeared. It showed a face covered by sunglasses and a gauze mask.
   ``Little children don't have large vocabularies,'' said Koji
Tateishi, an assistant inspector with the Chiba Prefectural Police.
In the stabbings, ``what happens to them happens in a flash. They
can't really tell us about it.''
   ``We're treating these as cases of sexual perversion,'' he said.
   Since Erika was reported missing on Friday and 3-year-old Sachiyo
Abe was stabbed in the stomach on a quiet street in Chiba a day
later, coverage on nightly news programs and in nationwide
newspapers has intensified to a level unseen since the kidnap-murder
of a small boy in September 1987.
   The country followed nightly news reports on the ordeal of
5-year-old Yoshiaki Ogiwara. The reports described his abduction
near his home, anonymous calls demanding a 20 million yen ransom
(then $140,000) from his fireman father, and the discovery of the
boy's body in a ravine two days later.
   Outraged media commentators then spoke of the unraveling of
Japanese society and waning confidence in a formidable police force
that boasted a 1987 record of arrests in 62.6 percent of all
reported non-traffic crimes, compared with 20.7 percent in the
United States.
   Despite a perceived increase in crimes against children, overall
crime in Japan actually declined 0.2 percent in 1987.
   But in the Chiba section where Sachiyo Abe was stabbed, fear has
curtailed late-afternoon activity at the neighborhood park,
housewife Chisato Shiba said.
   She continues to take her 15-month-old son outside to play, but
``even more than before, I make it a point to watch him very
closely,'' she said. ``The thing is, there's really no way to
prevent these things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
