<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ParkerPardon 1stLd-Writethru a0583 12-15 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parker Pardon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board of Pardons Rejects Request From Convicted Killer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-10 bgng `Parker, 57 ...' with five grafs to
CLARIFY that conviction was overturned, Parker wasn't retried and
Parker was paroled.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of murdering his wife 33
years ago will not get a pardon hearing even though another man
confessed to the slaying before his death last summer, the Nebraska
Board of Pardons ruled today.
   Attorney General Robert Spire, one of three members of the board,
said Darrel Parker can explore other avenues, but he declined to
elaborate. The ruling was unanimous.
   Spire said the board can consider Parker's request for a pardon
only if there is a ``clear miscarriage of justice.'' The board,
Spire said, ``is not a court, not a super appeals board.''
   Parker, 57, former parks supervisor in Moline, Ill., served 13
years in prison for the 1955 murder of his wife, Nancy. An appeals
court overturned his conviction on the ground that police had
coerced a confession, but prosecutors did not retry him, and he was
paroled in 1969.
   Another convicted murderer, Wesley Peery, had meanwhile told his
lawyers that he killed Mrs. Parker, giving them intimate details of
the killing, but made them promise not to reveal his confession
until after his death.
   The lawyers, Stanley Cohen and Toney Redman, came forward after
Peery, 63, died of a heart attack on death row in July.
   Parker's lawyer, Richard Bruckner, said Parker told him all he
wanted ``is a piece of paper _ a complete pardon finally clearing my
name.'' Bruckner did not attend today's board hearing and had no
immediate comment on the ruling.
   Secretary of State Allen Beermann, another member of the pardon
board, said Parker could seek a new trial.
   The pardon board, which also includes Gov. Kay Orr, was given a
sealed transcript of Peery's admission and considered Parker's
request for a pardon hearing a day after the 33rd anniversary of
Mrs. Parker's death.
   Peery's confession was among two years of taped and written
interviews he gave to Cohen and Redman in the hope a book would be
written about his exploits. He boasted of killing 12 people over
four decades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
