<2ND_LINE>PM-Calif Wind, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0584,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane-Force Winds Hit Northern California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with aircraft carrier's arrival delayed,
more than 300,000 lost power. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane-force winds wreaked havoc across
northern California today, overturning trucks, toppling trees onto
homes, tearing boats from their moorings and cutting power to more
than 300,000 customers.
   No serious injuries were reported.
   The arrival of the aircraft carrier USS Carl Vinson at the
Alameda Naval Air Station after a six-month tour of duty was delayed
until late afternoon for fear that the morning gusts might push the
huge warship off course, officials said.
   Several big-rig trucks that had stopped along the 10-mile
Altamont Pass 40 miles southeast of here were blown over, said a
Highway Patrol spokesman.
   The winds, clocked at up to 102 mph in areas, left boats adrift
along Richardson Bay and San Francisco Bay, said the Coast Guard.
Winds howled through the waterfront, leaving heaps of debris, signs
and odd hunks of metal in the streets.
   Homes throughout northern California were plunged into the dark
early today. Pacific Gas & Electric Co. said about 302,000 customers
lost power for varying amounts of time. The number without power by
mid-morning was not immediately known.
   The winds tilted a barge near the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge and
it dumped its load of rocks near one of the span's towers, the Coast
Guard said. The bridge was not damaged.
   Winds were clocked at 102 mph atop Mount Diablo 40 miles east of
San Francisco, said meteorologist Mike Pechner. Hurricane-force
winds are 74 mph or greater.
</TEXT>
