<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteinbergTrial     12-15 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg Trial,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge In Steinberg Trial May Give `Accomplice' Instructions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in Joel Steinberg's murder trial will
probably tell the jury that his live-in lover was an accomplice in
the death of the girl they raised, a move that could undermine her
testimony, according to a source.
   Hedda Nussbaum's testimony is central to the case against
Steinberg, who is accused in the 1987 fatal beating of 6-year-old
Lisa Steinberg.
   The source, who is involved in the case and spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said Wednesday that state Supreme Court
Justice Harold Rothwax probably will tell the jury to consider Ms.
Nussbaum an accomplice.
   Depending on how the judge phrases the instruction, it could mean
the jury will not be permitted to use her testimony to convict
Steinberg unless there is corroborating evidence.
   Today's session was delayed, however, when Rothwax was hit by a
car and suffered two broken wrists as he rode his bike to court,
police said.
   If Rothwax tells the six men and six women to consider her an
accomplice ``as a matter of fact,'' he lets them decide whether her
actions or inaction contributed to the child's death. If the jurors
decide she contributed to the death, then her testimony must be
supported by other evidence.
   If the judge instructs them that Ms. Nussbaum was an accomplice
as a ``matter of law,'' then the panel has no choice and is obliged
to use Ms. Nussbaum's testimony only if it is supported by other
evidence or testimony.
   Steinberg, 47, is a disbarred lawyer charged in the death of the
girl he illegally obtained at birth from an unwed teen-ager. The
girl was removed from his Greenwich Village apartment and died in a
hospital three days later of a head injury.
   Steinberg has denied hitting the girl, but Ms. Nussbaum said
Steinberg told her the night Lisa was fatally injured that he had
``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want to get up.''
   Ms. Nussbaum testified that Steinberg then went to dinner with a
friend. She said that during the three hours that he was out, she
did nothing to help the child.
   Medical experts testified that Lisa could probably have been
saved if help had been summoned earlier.
   Ms. Nussbaum originally was charged with murder. Prosecutors
dropped charges on the ground that she had been so beaten down
physically and mentally by Steinberg that she was unable to act. Ms.
Nussbaum agreed to testify against Steinberg.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former editor of children's books, spent
seven days on the witness stand recalling 12 brutal and bizarre
years with Steinberg.
</TEXT>
