<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonny Bono could come to be known as
the face that erased the budget deficit.
   It will take a lot of T-shirt sales at $13 a pop to wipe out the
city's $2.3 million deficit, but how many other places can fight
budget woes by peddling the mayor's likeness?
   So far, 1,100 admirers have sent in checks for the shirts bearing
either of two messages: ``I Want You Babe,'' or ``Meet Me in Palm
Springs,'' city officials said.
   The shirts have helped the city raise $7,500 toward erasing
budget woes, city spokeswoman Ann Erdman said.
   The 53-year-old Bono, who owns Bono's restaurant in this desert
resort, 110 miles east of Los Angeles, was elected mayor April 12, a
day after ex-wife and ex-singing partner Cher won an Academy Award
for her performance in the movie ``Moonstruck.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award-winning actress Greer Garson says the
groundbreaking ceremony for a new hospital unit was interrupted by
laughter because, ``I forgot my lines.''
   The ceremony was Wednesday for the Fogelson Education Unit, named
in honor of her late husband, at Presbyterian Hospital.
   Ms. Garson and her husband, Col. E. E. ``Buddy'' Fogelson, a
Dallas oilman, lawyer and rancher, donated a $1 million challenge
grant to help in construction of the unit.
   Fogelson died in 1987 at the age of 87 after a lengthy battle
with Parkinson's disease.
   ``The center is not only for Buddy, but for the doctors who cared
for him,'' the actress said. The center is a tribute ``to the good
care afforded my husband and me during the past several years.''
   She dismissed the forgotten lines saying, ``Oh well. We'll have
to do it at the opening (of the unit).''
   Mrs. Garson moved to Dallas in 1949 after she married Fogelson.
She also maintains homes in California and New Mexico. She won the
Academy Award in 1942 for best actress for her performance in ``Mrs.
Miniver.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican author Octavio Paz, 74, was awarded the De
Tocqueville Prize by the Institute of France on Thursday.
   The award and a cash prize of $17,000 are given for work
reflecting humanitarian ideals.
   Paz is the author of a range of works from poetry and prose to
essays and plays, often exploring the difference between Western and
Oriental concepts of creation. His books include ``The Labyrinth of
Solitude,'' and ``The Monkey Grammarian.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version moved on sports wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bart Starr, a former University of
Alabama quarterback who guided the Green Bay Packers to five
National Football League championships, has won nearly $2.4 million
in a lawsuit.
   A federal court jury awarded Starr the damages Wednesday in his
lawsuit against a former business partner in an automobile
dealership.
   ``We are very grateful to the jury for their decision,'' Starr
said after leaving U.S. District Judge Sam Pointer's courtroom. ``It
has been a very emotional time for us.''
   Besides the stress of the 18-month lawsuit, Starr's son, Bret,
died this summer from an apparent drug overdose.
   The jury awarded $2,387,423 to Starr after finding that Thomas M.
Acheson, Starr's partner in the dealership, breached a 1972
agreement.
   Both sides have 10 days to file further motions. Acheson's
attorneys indicated they would file motions to set aside the verdict.
   ``I believe that the settlement asked for is totally out of line
and the verdict is not supportable,'' Acheson said in a statement.
