<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of Gov. Ray Mabus have put together
a photo essay book on his childhood and inauguration last January.
   It includes contributions from two Pulitzer Prize-winning
Mississippians: a prologue by author Eudora Welty and an epilogue by
playwright Beth Henley, a close friend of Mabus' wife, Julie.
   The 58-page book, published by Oakdale Press of Jackson, was
written by free-lance writer Carroll Brinson of Jackson.
   Brinson readily concedes his bias comes through in the book,
which has an initial printing of 3,000 copies. ``I have been an
admirer of Gov. Mabus' for a number of years,'' Brinson said
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Johnny Cash is scheduled
to undergo open heart surgery Monday, joining close friend Waylon
Jennings, who is recovering from a similar procedure at the same
hospital.
   Cash, 56, was admitted Wednesday to Baptist Hospital after tests
were performed, doctors said.
   Reba Hancock, Cash's sister, said the tests showed there may be a
blockage.
   ``John had no chest pain,'' she said. ``He was just experiencing
a few problems, and went in for some tests.''
   In the 1960s, Cash overcame a 100-pill-a-day addiction, and he
was treated in 1984 for morphine abuse that he said he developed
while undergoing teatment and surgery for ulcers.
   Cash is known for his hit songs ``A Boy Named Sue,'' ``I Walk the
Line'' and ``Ring of Fire.''
   Already in Baptist Hospital is his pal Jennings, 51, who is
listed in stable condition after undergoing triple bypass heart
surgery Monday.
   Jennings, 51, was the narrator of the TV show ``The Dukes of
Hazzard'' and had a hit song by that name. His other hits include
``Mammas, Don't Let Your Babies Grow Up to Be Cowboys,'' a duet with
Willie Nelson.
