<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Factions Bjt   12-15 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Factions, Bjt,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat's Gamble Could Cause Radical Backlash</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American decision to talk with the PLO
is the biggest step toward Middle East peace in a decade, but
radical Palestinians called Yasser Arafat a traitor Thursday and
said the bloodshed will continue.
   Arafat's renunciation of terrorism and recognition of Israel's
right to exist, coupled with the U.S. response after years of
shunning the Palestine Liberation Organization, is the most dramatic
development since Egypt signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   His move could be the turning point in the 40 years of
Arab-Israeli conflict, but it also is the PLO chairman's greatest
gamble and could explode in his face.
   Such radical Palestinian factions as the Abu Nidal group may
launch a new wave of terrorism intended to wreck the initiative.
Militants within the PLO have stayed their hands for the moment, but
many feel Arafat made too many concessions.
   The Popular Front for Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist group
that reconciled with Arafat last year after a four-year
estrangement, accused him of ``capitulation.''
   Its leader, George Habash, said in a statement sent to The
Associated Press in Nicosia from Damascus, Syria, that it welcomed
the U.S. decision but felt Washington acted only to ``end the
diplomatic isolation that followed its refusal to grant Chairman
Yasser Arafat a visa to go to New York.''
   ``Therefore, we urge our masses to keep up the struggle to force
Israel and the United States to recognize the state of Palestine and
all legitimate Palestinin rights,'' he said.
   After the United States refused Arafat a visa to address the U.N.
General Assembly in New York, the assembly moved its session to
Geneva.
   Saeed Mousa, who leads a Syrian-based breakaway faction called
Fatah-Uprising, said Arafat was ``a traitor ... for his surrenderist
concessions to the United States and the Israeli enemy.''
   A Mousa spokesman accused the PLO chairman later of paying ``an
exhorbitant price, the recognition of Israel, for this American
decision'' and declared: ``Arafat is not able to fulfill his
commitments, especially his commitment to give up the armed struggle
against Israel.''
   Mousa and other dissidents left the PLO in 1983 in a
Syrian-supported mutiny.
   Ahmed Jibril of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command, also backed by Syria, said in Damascus:
``Arafat has recognized (Israel) and offered four-fifths of the
Palestinian land to'' the Jewish state.
   ``By renouncing violence and terrorism, Arafat is condemning
anyone who uses the gun against the Israeli occupier,'' Jibril said.
``Arafat has offered Israel what he doesn't have. The land of
Palestine is not the property of any organization or any
individual.''
   Six weeks ago, West German authorities arrested 13 people
suspected of belonging to Jibril's group who said they were planning
terrorist attacks.
   The extremist Saiqa faction, whose name in Arabic means
``lightning,'' said in Damascus: ``We shall see to it that the PLO
gets back on its original revolutionary course of struggle.''
   Arafat and his lieutenants would be targets of the radicals,
along with Israelis and Americans.
   Since his first hints at moderation 15 years ago, Arafat has had
to fight not only the Israelis but Palestinian extremists and
hard-line Arab nations led by Syria. Hafez Assad, president of
Syria, has sought for years to gain control of the PLO.
   Gunmen working for Abu Nidal have killed a score of Arafat aides,
and the Israeli secret service has assassinated others. The last
victim of Israel was Khalil al-Wazir, the PLO chairman's right-hand
man, shot to death April 16 at his home in Tunis, according to
Israeli security sources.
   Last month, Arafat steered the PLO legislature to implicitly
recognizing Israel by accepting U.N. Security Council Resolutions
242 and 338 as the basis of an international Middle East peace
conference.
   The Palestine National Council also declared an independent
state, presumably to be located in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
where Palestinians have been in revolt against Israeli occupation
for a year.
   Habash's guerrilla group and others went along with the
compromise at the Algiers meeting for the sake of unity, but Habash
said to Arafat:
   ``We're backing your efforts because this is what the majority
wants, but we don't believe moderation will pay. We can't wait
forever. If you fail, you have to come back to this council to say
so and we can then decide the future course.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ed Blanche is Middle East news editor of The
Associated Press, based in Nicosia. He has covered the PLO and
international terrorism since 1967.
</TEXT>
