<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SchoolBeepers     12-15 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--School Beepers,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Bans Beepers In Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has unanimously approved an
ordinance banning beepers in all public and private schools, a move
educators hope will put a dent in drug sales and prostitution.
   ``We know their mothers are not beeping them,'' Alderman Robert
Shaw said earlier at a committee meeting.
   School officials say students are often beeped in classrooms to
make drug deals or to engage in prostitution.
   ``We've got girls 11 years old. They get a call and they're out
of school to turn a trick,'' public schools security chief George
Sims said.
   The beeper ban was part of an omnibus ordinance approved by
aldermen Wednesday.
   School Superintendent Manford Byrd issued an executive order in
September banning the beepers, but Sims said the result was irate
parents who didn't like being called down to school because of the
infraction.
   The ordinance takes the issue out of the hands of school
administrators and gives it to the police. Violators are subject to
fines of $200 to $500.
</TEXT>
