<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Tomorrow'sTeachers     12-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tomorrow's Teachers,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Future Teachers Get Free College Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen of Chicago's best and brightest high
school seniors are being enticed into the teaching profession in a
corporate-sponsored scholarship program.
   The 15 students introduced Wednesday as Academy of Educators
Scholars will receive a free, four-year education if they graduate
from college and teach for at least five years. And if they land a
classroom job in Chicago, the students will receive a $12,000 bonus.
   ``All my friends are aspiring lawyers and aspiring physicians,
and all of them want to make a lot of money,'' said Afrika Turner,
17. ``I never wanted to be a nurse or a firewoman, I always wanted
to be a teacher.''
   The program offered by the Foundation for Excellence in Teaching
is being financed by Kraft Inc., Arthur Andersen & Co., GATX Corp.
and a number of individuals.
   Martin Koldyke, who helped start the foundation, said the program
is an investment in the city's youth.
   ``In the venture capital business, you have to project for the
future ... and this is the future,'' said Koldyke, general partner
of Frontenac Co., a venture capital firm.
   The program and others like it have the support of the
680,000-member American Federation of Teachers, which has lobbied
Congress for a similar federal program, said spokesman Scott
Treibitz in Washington.
   ``Having goverment do it is really the norm. I think what is a
little out of the ordinary is having the corporation underwrite this
and I think you will see more and more of that down the line,''
Treibitz said.
   He added corporations ``are begining to realize that they have a
lot at stake and they need to improve the schools.''
   Koldyke said 30 teachers who were winners of the foundation's
Golden Apple awards evaluated the files of 190 promising seniors
nominated by the city's public and private high schools.
   The 15 winners can attend one of four schools: Northwestern
University, DePaul University, University of Illinois-Chicago or the
National College of Education.
   Marvin Lynn, 17, said he jumped at the chance for a scholarship.
   ``I want to be a music educator _ teach high school students to
sing classical music and some gospel,'' Lynn said. ``I think I might
have afforded college without this, but I would have been in debt
for a long time.''
   For Koldyke, who taught for a year in Chicago in 1965, supplying
gifted teachers to the city schools has an element of personal
satisfaction.
   ``I wasn't a very good teacher,'' he said, ``and I came to
realize that it was an extremely tough profession.''
</TEXT>
