<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlaskaChristmas     12-15 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Christmas,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Open House at Governor's Mansion Draws 2,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Michael in 2nd graf, Koren in 6th graf cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following a 76-year-old holiday tradition,
about 2,000 Alaskans lined up in the slush to get a rare look inside
the governor's mansion, shake the chief executive's hand and sip
warm cider.
   Gov. Steve Cowper and his wife, Michael, played host at the
Christmas open house Wednesday night for the third consecutive year
in the colonial mansion overlooking the state capital.
   Except for two years during World War II, the open house has been
an annual event since the imposing, three-story home was built for
territorial Gov. Walter Clark in 1912.
   ``I've been to about 38 of them out of the 40 years I've been
here,'' said 92-year-old Ethel M. Montgomery. ``This is my house and
I love it.''
   The feeling that the house is a state treasure that belongs to
all Alaskans brings them out in every shape, age and occupation.
   ``You wouldn't be able to get away with it in a place with more
population,'' said Koren Bosworth, one of Juneau's 30,000 residents.
``It's nice. It gives people a feeling they're part of it.''
   Guests mingled about the main floor of the 15-room mansion
carrying plates of food and cups of cider or punch, while the
Cowpers and Lt. Gov. Stephen McAlpine and his wife greeted people.
The upstairs living quarters and the basement were off limits.
   In the living room, guests were entertained by violinists and a
chorus, while children lined up to talk to Santa and Mrs. Claus.
   Sandy Fiscus, who was sampling the refreshments with her
12-year-old daughter Robin, said they attend the open house every
year.
   The governor's chef, John DeCherney, and the mansion staff begin
planning for the three-hour affair in July. Baking begins in
September and most of the cookies, breads and hors d'oeuvres are
stored in the freezer.
   This year the treats included 1,500 egg rolls, 1,400 artichoke
pastries, 1,350 sausage pastries, 1,400 deviled eggs and 20 pounds
of Brie cheese stuffed with apples and pears. By the end, only a few
treats remained.
   For many, the open house has become a family tradition. Some
parents brought video cameras, while others took snapshots.
   The largest attendance at the open house came in 1983, when an
estimated 4,000 people filed through the mansion. Interest was
sparked that year by controversy over a $2.7 million mansion
restoration and redecoration project during the term of former Gov.
Bill Sheffield.
   The state foots the bill for the open house, with expenses coming
out of the mansion budget, Cowper spokesman David Ramseur said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1459EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PostOfficeSiege 7thLd-Writethru a0621 12-15 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Post Office Siege, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0621,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Worker Surrenders After Wounding Three Co-Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with hostage identified as
girlfriend. PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Murphy made ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mail handler shot three co-workers in the
main New Orleans post office, then holed up inside for 13 hours with
his girlfriend as a hostage, firing birdshot at random from under a
door today, authorities said.
   Warren Murphy threw out his shotgun and surrendered this morning
after all-night telephone negotiations with FBI and police,
including a cousin who is a police officer. His girlfriend appeared
unhurt, said FBI spokeswoman Nancy Fisher.
   The rampage was prompted by Murphy's concern for the welfare of
his two children in his wife's custody in Washington, said Police
Superintendent Warren Woodfork, who got him to surrender. ``I just
tried to appeal to him as a father,'' Woodfork said.
   None of the three co-workers hit by birdshot from Murphy's gun
suffered life-threatening wounds, hospital officials said. One
person was shot in the eye.
   Murphy, who is about 40, was a six-year mail handler who had
recently been promoted but whose wife had left him, post office
spokesman Cesta Ayers said.
   ``He feels like he doesn't like the conditions which they (his
children) are living under, and I assured him that I would look into
that,'' Woodfork said. ``And if his kids are being neglected, I
would do all I could to try to get some intervention to maybe get
the kids back here in the custody of their grandmother.''
   Woodfork said Murphy wasn't angry at his girlfriend and
co-worker, Carol Smith, 29. ``After the shooting started he just
grabbed her,'' the police superintendent said.
   Murphy made only one demand during the siege, telling negotiators
he didn't want to see any reporters. Police moved all reporters and
photographers off the sidewalk to a parking garage across the street.
   Murphy came to work Wednesday night and ``got into some sort of
argument with a co-worker, and pulled a weapon out of a bag he had
secured in the area,'' said Volney Hayes, spokesman for the FBI in
an adjacent building.
   The 8:30 p.m. shootings chased about 400 workers from the
building, which takes up most of a city block across the street from
the Superdome. About 100 workers took cover and hid in the building
for four hours before being escorted out by officers making a
room-by-room search for the gunman.
   Murphy chased off FBI agents with gunfire when they cornered him
in a room used for coffee breaks, Hayes said. During the night,
Murphy apparently became frustrated and fired about 10 more shots,
Hayes said. No one was hurt.
   ``They were just random shots,'' Hayes said. ``They haven't been
at anyone ... just stick the barrel under the door and fire.''
   Gunfire hit the telephone officers and relatives had used to try
to talk Murphy into surrendering. Another phone was tossed to him.
   Hayes said he thought Murphy's shotgun had been brought in
earlier, but he gave no further details except to say two shots were
fired and one of the wounded was the person Murphy argued with. He
did not identify the victims.
   Two people, one hit in a thigh and the other in an arm, were in
stable condition at area hospitals, officials said. A third person
was wounded in the eye and underwent surgery at Charity Hospital.
   When the shooting began, Pat Wingerter of New Orleans was
standing in line with his Christmas cards.
   ``I was going to mail this box of stuff I have and the security
guard came down, he was real excited,'' Wingerter said. ``The guard
was screaming, `There's a guy with a gun!'''
   Wingerter said the security guard ran to the door to make sure
the half dozen or so postal workers and customers escaped.
   ``I heard one shot and then the people started coming out,'' he
said. ``Even after the shot, there were people driving up mailing
letters for about five minutes. It was crazy.''
   The New Orleans post office was the scene of another shooting, in
1980 when postal worker Curtis Collins burst in and killed his
35-year-old supervisor with a .30-caliber carbine.
   On Aug. 20, 1986, part-time mailman Patrick Henry Sherrill walked
into the post office in Edmond, Okla., with guns and ammunition in
his mail bag and began shooting. He killed 14 postal workers and
wounded six others before killing himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO     12-15 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO United On Moderate Strategy, But It's Fragile</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PLO-Factions, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO, once a ragtag army of militants
pursuing the quixotic aim of crushing Israel, has evolved into a
Palestinian government-in-waiting embracing a wide range of
ideologies.
   But the unity is fragile.
   The nine guerrilla factions and other political groups which
constitute the 23-year-old movement are held together by their
Palestinian nationalism. They are prey to the divisive and violent
currents of Arab politics.
   They range from the Marxist guerrillas of George Habash's Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, which endorsed Arafat's
strategy of moderation with some reluctance, to Islamic
fundamentalists.
   The outcome of the talks will be crucial for Arafat's strategy of
moderation.
   That depends to a large degree on him holding the radical
elements of his disparate organization in check long enough to
attain solid political gains _ not just from the United States, but
from Israel.
   The PLO represents a widely divergent constituency in the 5.5
million strong Palestinian diaspora, from poor peasants eking a
living on the scrubland of the Israeli-occupied West Bank to
intellectuals in Western capitals.
   Some, like Habash, are Greek Orthodox Christians. Most, like PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat, are Moslems.
   The PLO is more than just a military organization dedicated to
regaining the Palestinian homeland lost in 1948. Arafat, 59, has
built it into an institution that provides social, educational and
medical services that are more effective than those run by some Arab
governments.
   Naseer Aruri, professor of political science at Southeastern
Massachussetts University, noted recently that this infrastructure
``was the real target'' of Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon, which
was aimed at crushing the PLO.
   The PLO guerrilla factions retain considerable autonomy and are
often backed by different Arab countries, such as Syria, Libya,
Algeria and Iraq, who have frequently sought to manipulate the PLO.
   Since Arafat became chairman 19 years ago, the PLO has often been
wracked by schisms. To hold the movement together, he has had to
constantly compromise, often when a decisive move could have meant a
breakthrough in his efforts to make political gains.
   His success in steering the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile and its highest decision-making body, to endorse
recognition of Israel and renounce terrorism was largely due the
year-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
   The uprising gave the Palestinian struggle a crucial political
dimension. The revolt arose from frustration at the PLO's failure to
achieve political advances and was the catalyst that helped swing
things Arafat's way.
   The PLO has not announced who will talk with U.S. officials. But
the Palestinian negotiators will be the pointmen for Arafat; Habash,
62, a charismatic physician; and Nayef Hawatmeh, 57, leader of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   These three often meet behind closed doors before convening the
PLO's ruling 15-man executive committee to formulate policy.
   Another key figure will be Farouk Kadoumi, head of the PLO's
political department and its de facto ``foreign minister'' since
1973.
   Khaled Hassan, and his younger brother Hani, have been close
Arafat advisers for years. Both are members of Arafat's Fatah
faction, the largest group in the PLO, and often act as his
emissaries to Arab and European governments.
   Bassam Abu Sharif is another important figure who will be closely
involved behind the scenes with a U.S. team led by Robert H.
Pelletreau Jr., America's ambassador to Tunisia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
