<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt   12-15 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt,0808</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Teams Head Home as Hope for Finding Survivors Fades</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPITAK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign relief workers said Thursday they
were giving up hope of finding more survivors of the Armenian
earthquake, and crews prepared to evacuate the last residents of
this hard-hit town and raze it.
   Nouradian Norig Kritkorianizh, the first secretary of Spitak's
Communist Party, said in an interview that crews would take measures
to prevent infectious diseases and begin razing the city on Sunday.
   About 15,000 of Spitak's 25,000 people died in the Dec. 7 quake
that destroyed most of city, he said.
   Altogether, the quake killed 55,000 people in Soviet Armenia and
left 500,000 of the area's 700,000 people homeless.
   Foreign relief experts and Soviet officials said hope was fading
to find more survivors, and the Tass news agency said searchers had
found only one person alive in the past 24 hours. That person was
found in Spitak, it said.
   Voices and other signs of life in the ruins of destroyed cities
dropped off sharply after Monday night, when temperatures plummeted
to below freezing, Julia Taft, director of the U.S. Foreign Disaster
Assistance office said at a Moscow news conference.
   ``The hope of finding any more (survivors) is ended,'' she said.
   Green military vans with mounted speakers toured the muddy
streets asking people to leave. Most women and children already were
gone.
   ``We believe the evacuation will take about three days,''
Kritkorianizh said. About 5,000 men needed to begin rebuilding the
city in early spring will be given temporary housing about one mile
from Spitak, he said.
   Trucks were distributing milk, bread, sausages, meat and oranges
to the survivors in Spitak, where it remained cold and damp.
   Some people had set up what was left of their household
belongings _ upholstered chairs, mattresses and even an occassional
brass bed _ around crackling bonfires where it was warmer than
inside tents.
   A large group of people were pressing against the gates of what
was once the city's central market, where soldiers were distributing
warm coats.
   Soviet officials vowed to continue the search until there is no
more hope of bringing people out alive but said no more doctors or
fire brigades are needed.
   ``Yesterday (Wednesday) Health Minister Yevgenvy Chazov said the
search was to continue but that with the lapse of time hopes grow
smaller and smaller. They are still looking for people in the
ruins,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said at a
news briefing.
   Teams from France and Britain have already returned home. Willie
McMartin, head of the 14-member International Rescue Corps from
Britain said he doubted anybody was still alive. ``If I thought
there was someone still alive I would not be sitting here,''
McMartin told reporters at London's Heathrow airport.
   McMartin said his group was physically exhausted and that the
Soviets were beginning to employ bulldozers, making it difficult for
them to use their high technology equipment to find victims.
   Rows of bulldozers were seen parked a few blocks from the main
square in Leninakan, Armenia's second-largest city located to the
west of Spitak.
   George Reid, spokesman for the League of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies, said the Soviets had decided to call off the
search and rescue on Dec. 20 and that some of the foreign relief
teams were leaving.
   ``It is a terrible dilemna for authorities caught between the
need for proper sanitation and the need to respect relatives who are
still hanging on,'' he told The Associated Press.
   He said that 25,000 bodies had been counted based on figures
provided to the Red Cross by the Soviet Council of Ministers. Tass
reported Wednesday that 21,755 bodies had been identified and
counted so far.
   Thousands of corpses remained buried in rubble.
   ``There is a danger of typhoid, cholera, and dysentery from the
poor sanitation in the disaster area which has likely led to
contamination of the water supply by insects and rodents,'' Dr. Jan
Borg of the Netherlands Red Cross said in an interview in Yerevan.
   Reporters visitng Leninakan on Thursday saw hundreds of sacks of
lime piled at a hospital, apparently in preparation for spreading on
corpses.
   While the relief teams were pulling out, looters were moving in.
   Police have detained 179 people accused of stealing foreign
relief packages and looting in the last 24 hours, Tass said.
   ``Monstrous as it sounds, there are also others _ better
described as shadows rather than as human beings. .. They roam
around the ruins _ not looking anybody in the face, they roam around
the ruins _ not to save but to steal,'' Armenia's Deputy Interior
Minister Viktor Erin told Tass.
</TEXT>
