<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BroadcastBattle     12-15 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Broadcast Battle,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Asks FCC To Deny High School Station's License Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc., new owner of WCIX-TV, wants the Federal
Communications Commission to take a high school radio station off
the air, saying the station's signal interferes with the television
station's audio transmission.
   In papers filed Tuesday with the agency, CBS asked that WKPX,
Piper High School's 3,000-watt progressive rock station, be denied a
permanent license.
   WKPX has operated under a construction permit since it went on
the air in February 1983. WCIX filed a protest shortly afterward.
   Steve Salo, a student in Piper's evening radio class, said those
involved in the station ``see this as the big guy coming down on the
little guy.''
   ``And the little guy, in this case, is providing education to
kids, promoting the arts, promoting local groups,'' Salo said.
   But Allen Shacklan, vice president for programming for CBS
television stations, said WKPX shouldn't have been allowed to
broadcast on its frequency in the first place.
   ``It looks like the FCC made a terrible mistake in ever granting
that permit,'' he said.
   At that time, Shacklan said, the FCC was in the midst of a
proceeding that would prohibit radio stations at the low end of the
FM band in areas where they conflict with television audio
transmissions.
   He said CBS has offered a proposal to WKPX that would allow it to
stay on the air, but would not discuss details. WKPX officials
wouldn't talk about it either, but said it was unacceptable.
   CBS takes control of WCIX on Jan. 3. No date has been set for an
FCC decision.
</TEXT>
