<DOCNO> AP881215-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CountryHam     12-15 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Country Ham,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Still Not Ready To Issue New Rules on Country Ham Processing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once again the Agriculture Department is going
to let processors keep on making old-fashioned country hams until
paperwork on a new food safety requirment is completed.
   The deadline for ham producers to comply with new federal
regulations was supposed to be Dec. 31, 1988. But then the previous
deadline was supposed to be last Dec. 31. And the one before that
was Dec. 31, 1986. There also was one on Aug. 6, 1985.
   Now, the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service said
Thursday, the new deadline will be Dec. 31, 1989 _ or whenever the
agency finally approves the new rules, spokeswoman Irene Goins said.
   The lengthy rule-making procedure involves those hams often seen
on grocery shelves in cloth bags, or hanging from rafters in country
stores. They must be scrubbed to remove mold and then soaked or
boiled a couple of times to reduce the salt content.
   They're the kind of hams for which someone had to invent red-eye
gravy and, in some parts of the country, grits.
   As the USDA defines them, they're ``uncooked, cured, dried,
smoked or unsmoked pork products made from solid meat.''
   Typically, country or dry-cured hams are treated with salt and
then put in a smokehouse to cure and age, a total process that can
take months or even years.
   Most hams sold in supermarkets are wet-cured quickly in brine
solutions and cooked before sale to consumers.
   In March 1983 the USDA proposed rules intended to help prevent
trichinosis, a disease caused by microscopic parasitic worms, or
trichinae, that can occur in improperly cooked pork. The proposed
rules were directed at ready-to-eat pork products and dry-cured
country hams.
   Shortly after the original proposal was adopted on Feb. 6, 1985,
the agency learned that some federally inspected ham producers were
using old-fashioned methods that didn't meet the new USDA
requirements and were ordered to show by Aug. 6, 1985, that their
curing procedures were safe.
   The country ham industry protested, so the USDA allowed more
time. One compelling reason for the extensions of time for
compliance was that no trichina problems had been associated with
the dry-cured hams.
   ``These traditional processing methods have been permitted
because they are decades-old methods believed to be effective in
destroying trichinae,'' says Ronald J. Prucha, acting administrator
of the USDA agency.
   ``We are researching the safety of traditional trichina control
methods and developing a proposed rule for issuance in early 1989,''
he said. ``After we receive public comments on that proposal, we
will develop new regulations.''
   But just in case the USDA's rule-making machine is slower than
officials hope, the compliance deadline was extended another full
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
