<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-PLO Bjt   12-15 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-PLO, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Avoids One Problem, But Inherits Another</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. agreement to talk with the Palestine
Liberation Organization spares President-elect Bush one politically
difficult decision, but gives him another arduous task: overseeing
that dialogue.
   The decision by the Reagan adminstration guarantees that the
Middle East's explosive problems will face Bush as soon as he enters
the Oval Office on Jan. 20, even though the vice president said
Thursday, ``There's no game plan, there's no five-point program.''
   Although initial contacts with the PLO are to begin in Tunis,
Tunisia, later this week, there is little doubt that the turnabout
decision clears the way for the Bush administration to try to bring
Israel and the Palestinians into direct negotiations.
   With tensions high on both sides of the 40-year-old dispute, such
a task could be monumental.
   Bush not only will have to deal with PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat,
whom just a week before the Reagan adminstration had branded a
terrorist, but he'll have to do it in a way that avoids souring
relations with Israel.
   Bush stressed Thursday that the initiative, which he fully
supported, was ``a dialogue, not negotations.''
   ``Let's see how things evolve. My position remains the same. I
want to see direct talks between, for example, between King Hussein
of Jordan and the Israelis,'' he told reporters.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater denied that
President Reagan made the tough decision so Bush wouldn't have to do
it. But he conceded the action could be helpful to the next
administration.
   ``This is one step further down the road in the pace process and
should provide for new options,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said Reagan had conferred with Bush before making the final
decision, although had not given Bush veto power over it.
   Secretary of State George Shultz's announcement Wednesday that
the United States would initiate a ``substantive dialogue'' with the
PLO saved Bush from having to expend his own political capital in
sorting out the issue.
   Less than a month after he denied Arafat a visa and barred him
speaking at the United Nations in New York on grounds he was a
terrorist, Shultz said the PLO leader had met three conditions long
insisted on by the administration.
   Bush said he fully supported the decision to open talks with the
PLO, in light of Arafat's assertion that he had met the three U.S.
conditions: recognition of Israel's right to exist, a renunciation
of terrorism and acceptance of two U.N. peace resolutions.
   Although U.S. officials have stressed that this country remains
committed to the security of Israel and still opposes an independent
Palestinian state, the decision reversed a longstanding U.S. refusal
to deal with the PLO.
   Israel has shown no indications it is willing to follow suit. Its
government still refuses to deal with what it views as a terrorist
organization devoted to its destruction.
   Major disputes continue to divide Israel and the Palestinians,
including the status of Jerusalem.
   While Bush has had more experience in foreign affairs than any
president since Richard Nixon, his choice for secretary of state,
James A. Baker III, has relatively little background in that area.
   However, Baker's reputation as a non-ideological problem solver,
honed in exchange-rate and trade negotiations with U.S. economic
allies in his 2{ years as treasury secretary, could help make up for
this lack of experience.
   Bush's campaign record provides few clues to the kind of
positions he might take as talks progress on the Palestinian issue.
   For the most part, the vice president dodged most specific
questions concerning the Middle East, as did Democratic rival
Michael Dukakis.
   Bush did speak forcefully during the campaign of his dedication
to U.S.-Israeli strategic cooperation, and he said he would not deal
with the PLO or back an independent Palestinian state _ echoing
administration positions of the day.
   It remains to be seen whether Reagan and Shultz's legacy to Bush
and Baker will be a blessing or a curse.
   Asked Thursday if he would prefer that the talks wait until his
administration starts next month, Bush replied: ``I become president
on Jan. 20. On Jan. 21, I'll tell you what I want to do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Tom Raum covered George Bush's presidential
campaign and now reports on the transition for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
