<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Education-Congress     12-15 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Education-Congress,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educators Ask Congressional Panel To Boost Federal Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government needs to funnel more money to
the nation's colleges and universities and to the students who wish
to attend them, a group of educators told a congressional panel on
Thursday.
   Witnesses appearing before the Joint Economic Committee's
education and health subcommittee said that diverting more resources
to post-secondary education would pay off in the long run with a
higher-skilled work force.
   ``What we have done up to the present time in order to create a
work force as motivated, skilled and dedicated as those we confront
in Japan, West Germany and other industrialized nations has
obviously not been adequate and can even be called tragically
inadequate,'' said Stephen Joel Trachtenberg, president of George
Washington University.
   The subcommittee released a report on Wednesday, the first day of
the two-day hearing, that recommended ways to better American
schools, including lengthening the school year, improving vocational
education and other programs, and increasing the emphasis on basic
skills such as reading and studying.
   But on Thursday, the panel's chairman, Rep. James Scheuer,
D-N.Y., emphasized what he said was a need to consider making
post-secondary education available to all qualified students.
   ``Kindergarten through grade 12 education, which was adequate for
the work force of a predominantly agricultural nation adapting to
industrialization, is simply obsolete in today's complex and
sophisticated high-tech environment,'' Scheuer said.
   The educators who addressed the committee agreed, and argued that
federal aid to colleges and universities has eroded in recent years.
   Robert H. Atwell, president of the American Council on Education,
said the inflation-adjusted value of the maximum Pell Grant award
for colleges costs has declined by 13 percent during the 1980s.
   Atwell also noted that the numbers of minority students are
projected to increase from one-fifth of all American children under
age 17 to one-third by the year 2000. In addition, by the turn of
the century, more than one in seven workers will be non-white, he
said.
   ``The federal government, the states and institutions must
develop a partnership in providing the financial resources and
educational programs that will enable all our citizens to develop to
their full potential,'' he said.
</TEXT>
