<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1909EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavannahRiver     12-15 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savannah River,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Concerned About Earthquake Safety at Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scientific advisory panel has urged the
Department of Energy to bolster the resistance to earthquakes of a
weapons production reactor at the trouble-plagued Savannah River
Plant.
   The panel also has concluded that to avoid confusion during a
crisis, fewer personnel should be regularly assigned to the control
room of the K reactor at the facility near Aiken, S.C. The reactor
currently is shut down because of maintenance and safety concerns.
   The recommendations came in a letter, released Thursday, to
Energy Secretary John S. Herrington from the department's Advisory
Committee on Nuclear Facility Safety, which DOE established earlier
this year to assess safety programs at the nuclear plant.
   The three reactors at Savannah River are the nation's only source
for tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen vital to boosting the
explosive power of modern nuclear warheads. Because tritium decays
at a rate of 5.5 percent a year, it needs to be replenished
regularly.
   The advisory committee, chaired by John F. Ahearne, a former
chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, declined to endorse a
detailed DOE report presenting the department's strategy for
restarting the K reactor.
   The just-completed DOE report outlined more than 160 separate
tasks, calling for a complete overhaul of training, safety,
management, operating and inspection procedures.
   In the advisory panel's 11-page letter to Herrington, Ahearne
said that ``in our opinion ... the restart strategy document
represents only an initial step in DOE's efforts to develop sound
operations at SRP (the Savannah River Plant).''
   He added that ``we have broad concerns regarding safety
philosophy, the overall criteria for restart and management.''
   A DOE spokesman, Douglas Elmets, said in response to the letter:
``Secretary Herrington has received this very constructive document.
We believe that this an important part of the process, and we will
respond in due course. Secretary Herrington takes very seriously the
recommendations of the advisory committee.''
   Regarding earthquakes, Ahearne wrote, ``the seismic resistance
issue in the restart strategy appears to be narrowly focused, does
not indicate what must be completed before restart and tends to
weaken the defense-in-depth philosophy.''
   ``The seismic resistance criterion requires the capability to
shut down, cool and monitor core status for a design basis
earthquake (0.2 g), but it is not stated whether or not this needs
to be completed before startup,'' he said.
   The ``g'' figure represents the strength of shaking that a
structure undergoes during an earthquake. A level of 0.2 g would be
approximately equivalent to the force exerted by a nearby quake with
a magnitude of 6 on the Richter scale.
   Ahearne noted in the letter that ``seismic criteria for the
confinement system and the ECS (emergency core cooling system) were
not included because neither is considered to be a `primary safety
system.' Crucial instruments are to be seismically qualified, but
the instrumentation system (wiring, sensors, etc.) is neglected.''
   ``We recommend that the ECS and confinement systems be
seismically upgraded prior to restart,'' he said.
   Overall, Ahearne wrote, ``a rationale should be developed for
deciding which upgrades are of immediate concern, which can be
delayed until after restart and for how long.''
   On the control room issue, the letter to Herrington said current
plans call for at least 12 people being in the K reactor control
room when the reactor is restarted.
   They include five reactor operators, a technical support
engineer, a shift adviser, a DOE Savannah River office onsite
engineer, an environmental safety and health inspector, a DOE
headquarters observer, a contractor oversight representative and a
contract operations manager.
   ``This number is clearly excessive,'' Ahearne wrote. ``Indeed, it
is difficult to see how such a large group could communicate
effectively to provide prompt attention to any crisis situation. The
list of people required for plant control room duties should be
reviewed carefully and access limited to essential personnel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
