<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SpermDonor     12-15 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sperm Donor,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Denies Visitation Rights To Sperm Donor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch court on Thursday denied
visitation rights to a sperm donor who sued for permission to visit
his biological child, a court spokesman said.
   In the case, which has gained widespread national attention, a
man who donated his sperm to a woman in a lesbian relationship
sought the right to periodically meet the 15-month-old daughter born
as a result of the artificial insemination.
   The donor claimed that an ``emotional attachment'' to the child
developed over visits to the lesbian couple before and after the
birth.
   A month ago, the Utrecht court ruled that the father was entitled
``in principle'' to sue for his rights. But Dutch family law does
not contain specific provisions outlining the rights of sperm donors.
   The identities of both the plaintiff and the defendants in the
lawsuit were not disclosed for reasons of privacy, and court
hearings six weeks ago took place behind closed doors.
   In its ruling Thursday, the court said that ``in this particular
case, the tensions caused by periodical visits would be very
serious, and that is not in the interest of the child.''
   The ruling also said that ``in cases such as this, visitation
rights should only be granted in extraordinary circumstances.'' It
did not elaborate.
   During the hearings, the lesbian couple claimed that the
friendship with the donor had ended and that serious personal
conflicts had developed, according to their lawyer, Arnoud Willems.
   He added that the couple had rejected the idea of an anonymous
donor so that the father could be identified if the child later
would ask for his name.
   Artificial insemination by donated sperm is a widespread practice
in the Netherlands, but the strict confidentiality that prevents
identification of the parties involved usually precludes such legal
battles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Flue-Cured     12-15 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flue-Cured,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco Quotas Raised</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second consecutive year, flue-cured
tobacco farmers in 1989 will see a hefty boost in federal marketing
quotas, the Agriculture Department announced Thursday.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said the 1989 flue-cured quota
will be 890.5 million pounds, up 18 percent from this year's 755
million pounds. The national acreage allotment will be increased to
426,485 acres from 379,588 acres in 1988.
   Allowing for overmarketings and undermarketings, the effective
quota for 1989 will be up by about 90 million pounds from this year.
   Myers said the flue-cured price support will be boosted to $1.468
per pound, an increase of 2.6 cents from 1988.
   The basic quota was increased on the 1988 flue-cured tobacco crop
for the first time since 1975, according to USDA analysts,
reflecting a draw-down on stockpiles and brisk demand.
   Myers said flue-cured tobacco farmers will vote in a mail
referendum to be held Jan. 9-12 on whether to continue federal
marketing quotas for the following three years, 1990, 1991 and 1992.
A two-thirds majority will be required for the controls to continue.
</TEXT>
