<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Children     12-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Children,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Urged To Act On Campaign Pledges To Help Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading advocate for America's children on
Thursday urged President-elect Bush to make good on his campaign
promises to offer more government help to disadvantaged youth,
saying that eventually would save tax money as well as lives.
   Marian Wright Edelman, president of the private Children's
Defense Fund, said the 1988 elections brought children's needs into
the national spotlight, and that ``the debate over the next four to
eight years will be on the form, level and timetable'' of programs
to help youngsters and improve child care.
   In a speech to the National Press Club, Ms. Edelman said Bush's
campaign proposal for a $2.2 billion children's tax credit is a
``welcome supplement'' to the child care bill that was considered
but not enacted by the outgoing Congress.
   She noted Bush also called during the campaign for support of the
federal nutrition program for pregnant women and children, increased
Head Start education efforts, expanded Medicaid health coverage for
low-income families, and new education initiatives.
   ``I have confidence that he will keep his word,'' Ms. Edelman
said. ``... I look forward, on many occasions, beginning in the
State of the Union address, to his fulfilling it.''
   She said that failing to meet children's needs early in life
results in more costly problems later. ``At a time of massive
deficits, America cannot afford to waste resources by failing to
prevent and curb the deficits which cripple our children and cost
billions in later remedial and custodial dollars,'' she said.
   Ms. Edelman's remarks were excerpted from her organization's
upcoming report, ``A Children's Defense Budget: A Vision for
America's Children,'' to be released in January 1989.
   She recited a litany of troubling statistics about the levels of
children living in poverty, infant mortality, gaps in prenatal care,
low birthweight babies, children infected with the AIDS virus,
broken families and homelessness.
   But she added: ``This is, for all its shadows, not a gloom and
doom speech. It is a get-off-our-national-duff and save-our-future
speech.''
   Ms. Edelman said her organization's most immediate goals include:
health insurance for poor families, expanding the federal nutrition
program to cover all pregnant women, infants and children, making
Head Start available to all needy children, ensuring that all
children are fully immunized, making quality child care available to
all families, and increasing the minimum wage.
   ``We believe these goals are doable in four or five years and
should be pursued as fast as the delivery systems of these
successful programs can effectively serve more children,'' she said.
``The longer we wait the more children we will lose.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
