<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0599 12-15 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0599,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Cautiously Welcome Dialogue With PLO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with Kennedy, Chafee comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading members of Congress gave the new
opening between the United States and the Palestine Liberation
Organization a wary welcome Thursday and sought to reassure Israel
that U.S. officials will be alert to any PLO tricks.
   ``This is good news and the right path to follow,'' said Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. ``I think we would best be very careful that the PLO
continue to show real seriousness and be wary of any deception.''
   Sen. George Mitchell, the newly elected Senate majority leader,
welcomed the U.S. move and called it a ``significant step toward
advancing the peace process.''
   ``It is consistent with what has been bipartisan American policy
for over a decade,'' Mitchell, D-Maine, said in a statement. ``Under
that policy, the U.S. seeks to encourage direct negotiations between
the parties, without preconditions, intended to achieve a stable and
lasting peace.''
   Mitchell said PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's acceptance of Israel's
right to exist and renunciation of terrorism were ``important
statements'' but ``in light of the PLO's record ... must be viewed
with caution.''
   He added that the U.S. action ``in no way represents or implies
... recognition of an independent Palestinian state'' and reaffirmed
``strong and unwavering support'' for Israel's security.
   The current Senate majority leader, Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., called
the opening ``a diplomatic turn of events that should not go
unrecognized. It is an opportunity that must be pushed forward
despite the risks.''
   Byrd added: ``As Israel's real friends, it is time to recognize
the shift in posture by the PLO. Our commitment to Israel is firm
and unswerving. But it must be tempered by the realization that
there are times when we must take those first tenuous steps toward
peace.''
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, also sought to reassure Israel, saying the U.S. dialogue
with the PLO does not mean any lessening of U.S. economic and
military support to its ally.
   ``It will ... take more than words to convince Israel,'' Fascell
said. ``Only the Israelis can determine what is best for their own
security. So it should also be made very clear that there will be no
attempt to impose a settlement on Israel.''
   Continued aid to Israel, the top recipient of U.S. assistance, is
necessary both to calm Israeli fears and ``as a clear signal to the
PLO and other parties that the United States is committed firmly to
the independence of Israel within secure borders,'' he said.
   Another staunch Israel supporter and Foreign Affairs Committee
member, Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif., said he believed Secretary of
State George Shultz was sincere in believing the opening would
advance the cause of Middle East peace.
   ``I remain highly distrustful of the PLO and of Mr. Arafat,''
Berman said in an interview. ``A carefully worded and hedged
statement (in Geneva) has to be put into the light of 20 years of
terrorism and commitment to the destruction of Israel. I remain
highly skeptical about the PLO's intentions.''
   But Berman added, ``I think we should put those intentions to a
test.'' Moves to call off the Palestinian uprising in the West Bank
and Gaza, and a rewriting of the PLO charter to eliminate a pledge
to destroy Israel would help prove the organization's good faith, he
said.
   ``It's a risky move. I hope what we've done here contributes to
negotiations towards peace,'' he said. ``You cannot simply operate
on the basis that the status quo can go on in perpetuity.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the change in U.S. policy
``may well be a historic step on the road to lasting peace in the
Middle East. Only time will tell whether the PLO is genuinely
prepared to live up the far-reaching conditions they have now
accepted.''
   ``It's a very positive thing,'' said Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.
``There are two parties to the conflict out there, the Israelis and
the Palestinians. To not talk to one of the groups is to ignore
reality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
