<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Palestinians 1stLd-Writethru   12-15 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0601,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Celebrate U.S. Decision, Fundamentalists Object</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with five more wounded. Pick
up 4th pvs, `Dozens of...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Israel-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians elated by the U.S. decision to talk
to the PLO celebrated in the streets Thursday and credited their
year-old uprising against Israeli rule for the change in U.S. policy.
   But Moslem fundamentalists rejected the decision as an American
deception, threatening to deepen divisions among Palestinians in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. ``America is Israel, and Israel
is America,'' said Gaza City prayer leader Ahmed Yassin.
   Washington's move failed to stop anti-Israeli protests in the
occupied lands. Sixteen Palestinians were wounded in clashes with
Israeli troops, including an 11-year-old shot with a plastic bullet
in the right eye, Arab hospital officials said.
   The wounded also included a 23-year-old Palestinian who suffered
a serious gunshot wound to the liver in the Gaza Strip town of Rafah.
   The army confirmed two of the wounded and said it was checking
further.
   Dozens of Palestinians marched through the streets of the West
Bank city of Ramallah, chanting pro-PLO slogans and carrying banners
reading ``Yes to the PLO'' and ``Yes to the Palestinian state.''
   A slogan sprayed on a wall in Ramallah read: ``The American
position is a victory for the uprising and Palestinian diplomacy.''
   Residents of Gaza City also expressed elation. ``Finally, the
Americans are realizing that there is a Palestinian people,'' said a
35-year-old man who refused to give his name.
   The sentiments were echoed by Palestinian leaders.
   ``The uprising has succeeded beyond our expectations by changing
the political climate,'' said Hanna Siniora, a PLO supporter and
editor of the daily Al Fajr newspaper in Arab east Jerusalem.
   Siniora said Palestinians in the occupied lands had put the PLO
leadership under great pressure to translate the uprising into
political gains, and this pressure led to recent PLO statements of
moderation.
   ``All of a sudden, we were able to say publicly what we had been
saying privately before: `Let's recognize Israel,''' Siniora told
The Associated Press.
   Clear recognition of Israel was one of three conditions set by
Washington for talks with the PLO. The others were renunciation of
terror and acceptance of U.N. resolutions recognizing the right of
all nations in the region to live within secure borders.
   Siniora acknowledged that Palestinians were deeply divided over
the next steps. ``The road to peace is full of obstacles, such as
the opposition of hardliners on both sides,'' he said.
   Moslem fundamentalists and hard-line PLO factions refuse to
recognize Israel. They say all of Israel should be returned to
Palestinian control.
   Yassin, a prominent Moslem fundamentalist, said PLO chief Yasser
Arafat made too many concessions to win Washington's approval.
``Arafat gave everything to Israel, and he got nothing in return but
promises,'' the wheelchair-bound prayer leader said in an interview.
   He also expressed skepticism over the new U.S. policy. ``To all
appearances, there is a change in American policy, but deep inside,
there is nothing new,'' he said.
   But other Palestinians said the U.S. decision marked a
breakthrough in the stalled Middle East peace process, and they
urged Israel to end its refusal to talk with the PLO.
   ``I think the Americans will pressure Israel, and the world
cannot live with (Prime Minister Yitzhak) Shamir's stubbornness,''
said Saeed Kanaan, a PLO supporter and businessman in Nablus. ``No
doubt, Israel is going to be isolated.''
</TEXT>
