<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Letters     12-15 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Letters,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>George Washington, Taft Letters Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shew in graf 5 is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late 18th century letter from George Washington
to critics of a treaty with Britain sold for $27,450 Thursday,
Sotheby's auction house reported.
   Bidders paid more than $1.9 million for a range of historical
letters and manuscripts but a collection of U.S. presidential
autographs was not sold because it failed to reach the minimum set
by the seller, Sotheby's said.
   Washington's letter was sent in 1795 to a group of officials
protesting a treaty John Jay negotiated to settle differences
remaining after the Revolutionary War.
   Jay's treaty was criticized because the British continued
violating the Treaty of Paris.
   ``I cannot but hope, that experience will shew, that the public
interest required the course which has been pursued,'' the first
president wrote to the officials.
   Quaritch, a London firm of book dealers, bought the letter, and
also paid $4,220 for autographed memorabilia of President William H.
Taft about American Jews traveling in Russia in 1911.
   In 1913, the United States broke its treaty with Russia over the
terms under which American Jews could visit that. The Russian
government said they could visit only on business.
   According to the Sotheby's catalogue, the two letters and series
of notes ``give a fascinating insight into the thought processes
involved in White House decision-making'' on the matter.
   The collection of presidential autographs, from George Washington
to Lyndon Johnson, did not reach its minimum value of $57,000-76,000.
</TEXT>
