<2ND_LINE>AM-Cricket Clash,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cricket Sparks Ethnic Clash That Kills Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wayward ball from a cricket match set
off ethnic fights in which six people were killed, authorities in
this southern port said Thursday.
   Police and witnesses said the trouble started Wednesday when some
Mohajirs, Moslem immigrants from India, hit a cricket ball into a
house owned by Pathans, an ethnic Pakistani group.
   A youth who tried to retrieve the ball was beaten and died of
head injuries, and news of his death prompted clashes Thursday at a
juncture of e Pathan and Mohajir neighborhoods in central Karachi,
the reports said.
   Hospital officials reported the death toll.
   Security forces patrolled the streets Thursday night and there
were no further reports of fighting.
   Mohajirs, who complain of discrimination, and Pathans, originally
from northwestern Pakistan, have battled repeatedly for a decade.
Nearly 300 were killed in December 1986 during riots in Karachi, a
city of 9 million.
</TEXT>
