<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     12-15 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Pressured to Postpone Vote as Violence Escalates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious, professional and social
leaders urged the government on Thursday to postpone presidential
elections until a wave of ethnic violence that killed 109 people
this week subsides.
   At the same time, rival Sinhalese and Tamil guerrillas called for
boycott of Monday's election. Sinhalese extremists said the
government was incapable of conducting fair balloting, and
separatist Tamils blamed the two main candidates for violence that
has wracked this Indian Ocean island for five years.
   A military spokesman said Sinhalese radicals shot and stabbed to
death eight villagers in the south. He said the extremists left
scribbled warnings saying: ``This is the fate of government spies.''
   Later Thursday, soldiers captured an underground hide-out used by
the Sinhalese attackers, who have waged a campaign of terror and
intimidation to overthrow the government, the spokesman said. Four
rebels were killed and 23 surrendered, the spokesman said on
condition of anonymity, he said.
   A government statement said 21 prisoners were killed by police
after anti-government militants bombed open a wall of the
medium-security Welikade prison near Colombo on Tuesday night.
Earlier, officials said only two died.
   A total of 221 prisoners escaped but 133 were recaptured, the
statement said. The remainder remain free.
   The United Organization for Peace and Democracy, an umbrella for
30 professional, religious and social groups, said President Junius
R. Jayewardene should call off the elections because of the
escalating violence.
   Jayewardene, a Sinhalese, is prohibited by law from seeking a
third six-year term. The 82-year-old leader has said he will
dissolve Parliament and step aside Tuesday. Opposition leaders say
that will be too late.
   Sri Lanka has 9.3 million eligible voters among its 16 million
people.
   Sinhalese extremists say the government's peace accord with
Tamils grants too many concessions to the minority people who have
been fighting for a separate homeland in the north and east. Nearly
10,000 people have died since the war started in 1983.
   Predominantly Hindu Tamils, who are 18 percent of the island's
population, contend they are denied jobs, education and money for
development by the Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   The biggest and most militant Tamil group, the Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam, said Thursday said the two main presidential
candidates _ Ramasinghe Premadasa of the governing United National
Party and Sirimavo Bandaranaike of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party _
``have been instrumental in creating the ethnic conflict and have
been responsible for the genocide of Tamils.''
</TEXT>
