<HEAD>Sugar Import Quota Boosted 17 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will allow a 17 percent
increase in the amount of raw sugar that can be imported from 39
foreign countries in 1989, the Agriculture Department announced
Thursday.
   Deputy Secretary Peter Meyers said next year's quota was set at
about 1.24 million short tons of 2,000 pounds each, up from about
1.06 million tons in calendar 1988.
   The Dominican Republic led the list with a 1989 allocation of
185,328 metric tons, followed by Philippines, 166,374, and Brazil,
152,685.
   Officials said the quota for Panama, 30,537 tons, ``is not
allowed to be shipped at this time'' and may later be allocated to
other countries, as was done last July with Panama's 1988 quota.
   Reduced production because of this year's drought and rising
demand were the main reasons for boosting the quota so sharply,
officials said.
   In metric tons, which have about 2,205 pounds each, the 1989
quota will be almost 1.13 million tons. Metric units were used to
establish next year's quota to meet the terms of a new U.S. tariff
system, which will take effect Jan. 1.
   Alan Holmer, deputy U.S. trade representative, announced
country-by-country allocations for 1989. In metric tons, those
include:
   Argentina, 45,279.
   Barbados, 7,444.
   Bolivia, 8,424.
   Canada, 11,583.
   Congo, 7,258.
   Dominican Republic, 185,328.
   El Salvador, 30,378.24.
   Gabon, 7,258.
   Guyana, 12,636.
   Honduras, 19,197.36.
   Cote D'Ivoire, 7,258.
   Madagascar, 7,258.
   Mauritius, 12,636.
   Mozambique, 13,689.
   Papua New Guinea, 7,258.
   Peru, 43,173.
   St. Kitts, 7,258.
   Taiwan, 12,636.
   Trinidad-Tobago, 7,444.
   Zimbabwe, 12,636.
   Australia, 87,399.
   Belize, 11,583.
   Brazil, 152,685.
   Columbia, 25,272.
   Costa Rica, 20,795.4
   Ecuador, 11,583.
   Fiji, 9,477.
   Guatemala, 50,544.
   Haiti, 7,258.
   India, 8,424.
   Jamaica, 11,583.
   Malawi, 10,530.
   Mexico, 7,258.
   Panama, 30,537.
   Paraguay, 7,258.
   Philippines, 166,374.
   Swaziland, 16,848.
   Thailand, 14,742.
