<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoundationFraud     12-15 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foundation Fraud,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foundation Scandal: AG Says It Was Charity for the Rich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of a charitable foundation were accused
Thursday of siphoning off nearly $7 million to support their own
lavish habits, including chauffeured limousines, nights at the opera
and trips to Florida and Israel.
   In a lawsuit filed in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, state
Attorney General Robert Abrams said officials of the Nate B. and
Frances Spingold Foundation systematically looted the organization's
coffers from 1983 to 1988, depleting its assets by almost 50 percent.
   In particular, Abrams said James R. Halperin, the foundation's
chief administrative officer, took more than $5 million in salary to
perform ``simple administrative duties.''
   Abrams said Halperin _ and not the charities he was supposed to
support _ was the chief beneficiary of the foundation.
   Halperin, a Manhattan lawyer, allegedly billed the foundation at
a rate of $275 to $350 an hour for his services. His hours
increased, according to the attorney general's office, from an
average of 29 per week in 1984 to an average of 77 per week in 1986
and 1987.
   In its lawsuit, the attorney general's office demanded the
removal of Halperin and Melvyn Levitan as directors of the
foundation and demanded repayment of losses resulting from their
alleged misconduct.
   At Abrams' request, state Supreme Court Justice Carmen Bauchamp
Ciparick issued a temporary restraining order barring Halperin and
four other defendants from using any more of the foundation's funds.
   Calls to the foundation for comment were referred to Halperin's
lawyer, Gerald Shargel, who was in court and could not immediately
be reached.
   According Abrams' office, the Spingold foundation was established
in 1955 by Nate B. and Frances Spingold to make contributions to
charitable, educational and religious organizations.
   The foundation's assets have decreased from $12.5 million in 1983
to $6.4 million this year, his office said. No figures were
available on how much the foundation gave to organizations during
that period.
   Nate Spingold died in 1958; his wife and her son, Herbert
Levitan, supervised the foundation until both of them died of
natural causes in 1976.
   Halperin has served as director and chief administrative officer
of the foundation since 1975, while Melvyn Levitan, Mrs. Spingold's
grandson, has been a director since 1977 and president of the
foundation since July 1987.
   The others named in the suit are Nedda Strasbourger, Frimi
Mendlowitz and Adrienne Halperin.
   According to an affidavit filed by Abrams' office, the
defendants' alleged excesses included dinners; a trip by Halperin
and his wife to Florida; the purchase of an unneeded luxury office
for the foundation; and a trip to Israel.
   In addition, the affidavit charged that Halperin leased
automobiles, including a Mercedes and a Cadillac, at foundation
expense, and that he and other directors allegedly hired chauffeured
limousines to take them ``to the theater, opera and ballet, and to
department stores for shopping, gala benefits, and airports.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
