<HEAD>Convicted Terrorist Ordered Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada ordered on Thursday that a
convicted Palestinian terrorist leave the country, but appeals could
delay deportation for years.
   The decision by an immigration adjudicator in Hamilton concluded
an 11-month deportation hearing for Mahmoud Mohammad Issa Mohammad,
convicted in Greece of manslaughter and other charges in connection
with a raid on an Israeli airliner at the Athens airport in 1968.
   He received a 17-year sentence in 1970 but was released later
that year after Palestinian terrorists seized a Greek airliner and
the release of Mohammad and six other prisoners. Mohammad, 46, came
to Canada in February 1987.
   Canada sought his deportation on grounds he lied on his
application for residency by not mentioning his criminal record and
membership in the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   Mohammad has said he wants to put his past behind him and is
claiming refugee status. He lives in Brantford, Ontario, with his
wife and three children and works as a construction subcontractor.
</TEXT>
