<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Haddow     12-15 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haddow,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former HHS Official, Others Sued in Speechwriting Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday accused former
Health and Human Services Department official C. McClain Haddow, a
former speechwriter and their wives of submitting false claim and
conflicts of interest.
   A civil suit filed in U.S. District Court alleged that Haddow,
with the assistance of Gordon Jones of Springfield, Va., arranged to
have HHS award a half-dozen contracts for writing speeches for
then-HHS Secretary Margaret Heckler to Jones' wife, Susan, and the
couple's company, Jones Ink Inc.
   The speeches were actually written by Alice Haddow or other
people and $21,790 paid by HHS to the Joneses was passed on to the
Haddows, the complaint alleged. Haddow at the time was chief of
staff to Mrs. Heckler.
   The suit said that Haddow and Jones ``knowingly caused to be
submitted to HHS'' a form saying that Mrs. Jones had done editing
and speechwriting and had performed those duties for congressional
and senatorial clients when she had not done so.
   Jones, now a senior fellow at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank in Wshington, declined to comment on the
suit.
   In July 1987, Haddow pleaded guilty to conflicts of interest
involving an organization known as the T. Bear Foundation Inc., and
the speechwriting matters. He served three months in prison before
being released last May.
   In addition, the suit said that from November 1984 to October
1985 Haddow and his wife secretly arranged to receive $33,540 of
$37,400 in payments made by the T. Bear Foundation to Magoon and
Associates, a company hired to perform fund-raising activities.
Haddow was a member of the foundation's board.
   The suit seeks $75,990 in treble damages and $70,000 in civil
penalties for the speechwriting in addition to the $33,540 that the
Haddows allegedly received from the proceeds of the T. Bear
Foundation contract.
</TEXT>
