<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Honoraria 1stLd-Writethru a0673 12-15 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honoraria, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling Rostenkowski 10th graf et seq</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Free' Speech Could Prove Costly To Members Of Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Young had a busy speaking schedule in
the first weeks of 1987, jetting to places like Atlanta, Los
Angeles, Dallas and Seattle as part of the multimillion-dollar
congressional honoraria circuit.
   Between Jan. 5 and Feb. 6, the Florida Republican made 18
speeches, all of them to major defense contractors who have more
than passing interest in hearing from a member of a House
Appropriations subcommittee that has a major role in Pentagon
spending.
   The whirlwind schedule was not without its reward: $29,000 in
speaking fees from the likes of Rockwell, Lockheed and Boeing, an
amount that the Census Bureau says is just $1,853 below what the
median U.S. household collected in income for all of 1987.
   Young didn't keep all of his earnings. His financial disclosure
statement says he gave $3,200 to charity, which brought his
speechmaking net to $25,800, or $84 less than House rules allowed
him to keep. He made no more for-pay speeches after Feb. 6.
   Harry Glenn, Young's press secretary, said Thursday the
lawmaker's honoraria appearances were lumped together because he
only schedules them during times when Congress either is not in
session or has a light schedule, as generally occurs in January. He
said Young generally works a 7 a.m.-10 p.m. day while on these
visits, meeting with company officials and touring plants, not just
speaking for a fee. ``He learned something from these trips,'' Glenn
said.
   Young is not unique among the 390 representatives and 87 senators
who in 1987 pulled in $9.8 million on the honoraria circuit _ a
controversial perk being targeted for oblivion by reformers, a
federal pay commission and influential lawmakers like House Speaker
Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   The commission said that public faith in the integrity of
Congress is threatened by the steady growth in honoraria, which rose
30 percent from 1986 to 1987.
   ``The only principled argument that can be made for the practice
of accepting honoraria is that official salaries are far too low and
must be supplemented for a public official to meet his family
obligations,'' the panel said.
   Its recommendation to the White House and Congress: ban honoraria
and raise congressional pay from $89,500 a year to $135,000.
   The champion honoraria earner for 1987 was Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, the panel that
originates most tax legislation in Congress.
   Rostenkowski is so much in demand by a broad segment of
businesses, industries and trade associations that his 22 paid
appearances in January 1987 brought in $76,500 in honoraria.
   Even though the powerful chief tax-writer of the House had taken
in more than nearly three times the $25,884 that House rules allowed
him to keep, Rostenkowski didn't withdraw from the 1987 honoraria
circuit.
   He kept talking, and by year's end his voice had brought in
$245,000 _ $25,844 for Dan Rostenkowski, $219,156 for the LaVerne
and Dan Rostenkowski Charity Fund.
   A spokesman says the fund's money was distributed about 50-50
among Chicago and non-Chicago health, ethnic, religious and
educational groups with bona fide charity status. Rostenkowski
doesn't release their names.
   ``We've been running a Robin Hood program _ taking from the tax
lawyers and giving to the poor,'' says the spokesman, who declined
to be quoted by name.
   In 1987, $2.25 million of the $9.8 million in congressional
honoraria ended up going to charities and nonprofit institutions _
an income source that could dry up if the White House and Congress
accept the pay commission's plan.
   Rostenkowski's spokesman says the chairman will continue his
philanthropy even if Congress votes to abolish speaking fees, which
are frequently paid by groups with a financial stake in a particular
lawmaker's committee and floor votes.
   The spokesman says Rostenkowski will help his favorite charities
raise money by volunteering to be a drawing card at their
fund-raising events.
   Rostenkowski was one of three lawmakers who went into six digits
on the 1987 honoraria circuit. In second place with $118,588 was
Budget Committee Chairman Bill Gray, D-Pa., who gave $94,938 to
charity. Third was Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan.,
$106,050, with $80,000 to charity. Both Gray and Dole kept less for
themselves than Capitol Hill rules permit.
   The House lets members keep honoraria earnings up to 30 percent
of official salary, or $26,850. In the Senate, the factor is 40
percent, or $35,800. In 1987, 44 senators took in less than this
amount. Twenty-six of them listed no charitable contributions on
their disclosure forms.
   The new Senate majority leader, George Mitchell, D-Maine, was
above average in honoraria earnings and below average in giving to
charity. He took in $42,225, about $6,000 above the norm, and gave
away $7,350, about $2,000 below the average senator's giving.
   One senator who will be able to watch next year's pay-honoraria
debate with detachment is Dan Quayle, R-Ind., who as vice president
will fall under the existing ban on paid speechmaking by the
executive branch and the judiciary.
   In 1987, Quayle was more active on the honoraria circuit than the
average senator. He collected $49,255, kept $34,953 and gave $14,302
to charity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
