<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Italy     12-15 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Italy,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Prime Minister Praises U.S. PLO Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita, with
President Reagan at his side, on Thursday praised the U.S. decision
to talk with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   De Mita, paying a farewell call on the retiring president, told
reporters through an interpreter that he thought Reagan's decision
``helps to work toward the solution of a delicate problem.''
   ``And now, talks will help us understand the conditions that are
there for negotiations,'' he said. ``The decision of the American
government is very important because it solves the problem of
finding a counterpart'' to talk for the Palestinian side, de Mita
said.
   Attending De Mita's meeting with Reagan were Secretary of State
George Shultz and national security adviser Colin Powell.
President-elect George Bush and Vice President-elect Dan Quayle
later had lunch with the allied leader.
   At their meeting, Reagan thanked De Mita again for the Italian
decision to provide a new home for a 72-plane Air Force fighter wing
that is being relocated from Spain, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   Most of the meeting was about Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's meeting with Reagan in New York, Gorbachev's U.N.
speech, ``the need for NATO unity'' and efforts to correct the
imbalance between NATO and Soviet bloc conventional forces, he added.
   De Mita told a news conference afterwards that the United Nations
had prepared a decision on how to deal with the Middle East, but the
decision had been paralyzed by the lack of an acceptable spokesman
for the Palestinians. The U.S. decision to negotiate with the PLO
was a way around the obstacle, he added.
   Asked what his advice to Israel would be at this moment, he
replied: ``Be serene. Neither the Italian nor the European position
favors one side against the other.''
   The Italian government favors a negotiated solution to the
conflict, he said.
   De Mita added that recent decisions by the Palestine National
Council in Algiers were contested by many Arabs and that the
statements of PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat were risky.
   Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti, who joined De Mita at the news
conference, said Wednesday's events had made it clear to those in
Israeli-occupied territory that the calmer they remain, the better
the results will be.
</TEXT>
