<1ST_LINE>u i AM-QuakeOrphans     12-15 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake Orphans,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychologists Work to Heal Mental Scars of Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen children and teen-agers seemed
to be enjoying themselves Thursday rummaging through boxes of
clothes and toys. But the laughter and the smiles vanished as they
remembered they didn't have a home or parents to return to.
   Eight days after an earthquake in northwestern Armenia sundered
homes and families, officials can only guess at the number of
children killed or left orphans.
   Many survivors are having nightmares, and the Soviet Children's
Fund, a charity, sent a team of 11 child psychologists to Armenia to
help.
   ``Who has trouble sleeping?'' psychologist Valeria Mukhina asked
the group of children, whose parents are dead or missing.
   Nearly all raised their hands and yelled, ``I do, I do!''
   The therapy session had begun.
   The youngsters, from seven to 15 years old, were sitting in a
recital hall of Yerevan's music conservatory. The building was
converted into a children's relief center and the hall was filled
with donated toys and clothes.
   ``Sit back and close your eyes,'' the pscychologist told the
children. ``Frightening pictures may come to you. But forget about
everything. Force yourself to see the best: the sky, birds.'' The
children broke in with their own suggestions: flowers, a warm sun.
   Their eyes still closed, children were told to imagine themselves
in a forest and told to care for dolls they had just received.
Mukhina seemed to be trying to establish the dolls as a symbol of
security to replace that which was lost with the disappearance of
their parents.
   ``Hold the doll, which loves you,'' she said, pushing the new
toys into the children's embrace. ``Take care of the dolls. Lead
them into the world. Keep everything frightening away from your
doll.'
   Then she concluded: ``When I count to three you will say goodbye
to your forest and tonight you will rejoin it and sleep peacefully.
   The suggestion worked so well that 12-year-old Lena Chudliny
didn't open her eyes again when the count ended. But when she woke
up, the shock of the quake returned and she began to cry.
   Albert Likhanov, head of the Children's Fund, was watching and
went over to embrace Lena and comfort her.
   Lena's 15-year-old brother Ruslan told in a matter-of-fact way
what he could not get out of his mind.
   ``We had an English class. We sat writing. The teacher said
tomorrow there will be a quiz. Then everything started to shake,''
Ruslan said, recalling when the quake struck his hometown of
Leninakan at 11:41 a.m.
   ```Let's get out!' we shouted,'' Ruslan said.
   A classmate of Ruslan's, who identified himself as Saak,
described how the class managed to get outside and saw one entire
class crushed as they tumbled from the third floor to the ground.
   Soldiers later pulled up in a tank and took the students away.
Ruslan said he doesn't know what happened to his parents.
   In an interview, Mukhina explained that she tries to help the
children cope with the tragedy by ``replacing negative emotions with
good thoughts.'' But she said the process is likely to take years.
   In the meantime the children are staying in a Yerevan school,
playing with their new toys and going to movies and concerts.
Authorities are arranging longer term care in sanitariums throughout
the Soviet Union, said Simon Alexanyants, an Armenian doctor
specializing in child health care.
   Some Armenians say the children should be kept in the small
southern republic of Armenia rather than being sent out to other
parts of the Soviet Union. But Alexanyants said all eventually will
return.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
