<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EPASanctions 1stLd-Writethru a0675 12-15 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA Sanctions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>^Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT to carbon monoxide, sted dioxide;
SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE with further comment; picks up 6th graf pvs,
bgng: Cuyahoga County...</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Threatens Aid Cutoff Over Cleveland Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on Thursday
gave Ohio officials two months to adopt an automobile pollution
inspection plan for the Cleveland area or face a cutoff of $20
million in federal highway funds.
   Unless the state Legislature complies with the federal Clean Air
Act by ordering tailpipe inspections in populous Cuyahoga County,
which includes Cleveland, federal highway money to the county will
be blocked 60 days after the order is published in the Federal
Register.
   In addition, carbon monoxide-spewing smokestack industries will
be denied new construction permits, and air pollution control grants
to Ohio will be reduced by $64,000 under the sanctions given final
EPA approval.
   If those penalties don't prod state lawmakers into enacting a
tailpipe inspection bill, the EPA is ready to wield yet another
club: the loss of sewage construction grant money, perhaps $20
million worth.
   Spokeswomen for Gov. Richard Celeste and the state Environmental
Protection Agency said avoiding the sanctions has become a top
priority for the new year.
   ``We are working with the governor's office on draft legislation
which we hope to introduce as early as possible in January,'' Ohio
EPA spokeswoman Jennifer Lane Maier said. ``I would give the federal
government what they've asked for.''
   Press Secretary Debra Phillips said the governor believes there
is time to beat the 60-day deadline.
   State Sen. Lee Fisher, a Cleveland Democrat, agreed. He predicted
the penalties would force the Legislature to enact a tailpipe
testing bill, though ``with a lot of kicking and screaming.''
   ``Ohio will come into compliance,'' he said. ``We can't afford to
lose those funds.''
   Cuyahoga County was singled out because of violations of federal
air pollution standards, specifically levels of carbon monoxide.
   In high concentrations, the poisonous gas can cause dizziness,
nausea, blurred vision, headaches and delayed reaction times.
   Tailpipe inspections are considered an effective antidote for
high carbon monoxide levels because 85 percent of the gas comes from
the exhaust fumes of cars and trucks.
   Though no other U.S. city currently is suffering the loss of
highway construction money, there are about 10 other areas under
construction bans, including Cincinnati's Kentucky suburbs, Chicago
and some of its suburbs, Albuquerque, N.M., and St. Cloud, Minn.,
EPA spokesman Chris Rice said.
   Highway funding sanctions were lifted recently against
Albuquerque after a year and a half; four areas in California were
under the same restrictions for nearly two years, but those also
have been lifted, he said.
   Even with the sanctions, many highway projects will continue to
get their full federal funding because the government doesn't
withhold money for safety improvements and projects that have a
beneficial effect on air quality.
</TEXT>
