<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Espionage     12-15 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Espionage,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Says British Intelligence Agency Among The Worst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition Labor Party on Thursday derided MI5,
Britain's counter-intelligence agency, as one of the worst secret
services in the West and said it has a long history of recruiting
and promoting Soviet agents.
   ``It has made itself ridiculous because it believes it is above
scrutiny,'' said Labor deputy leader Roy Hattersley.
   Hattersley spoke during a parliamentary debate on a bill proposed
by the Conservative government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
to license bugging and break-ins by the agency.
   The Security Services Bill will give a basis in law for the first
time to the 79-year-old agency, whose existence successive
governments long refused even to acknowledge.
   Hattersley's attack reflected complaints by the opposition and
civil liberties groups that the bill fails to provide any
parliamentary control over MI5. Its chiefs will continue to report
secretly to the prime minister and the home secretary.
   The agency became the focus of renewed public attention during a
three-year court battle, which the government finally lost this
year, to suppress the memoirs of ex-agent Peter Wright. His book
``Spycatcher'' includes charges that MI5 tried to destabilize a
Labor government.
   Several Soviet agents from the British upper classes _ Kim
Philby, Guy Burgess, Donald Maclean and Anthony Blunt _ were
recruited at Cambridge University in the 1930s to work for the
British secret services. MI5 and MI6, its sister
intelligence-gathering agency, have been dogged by subsequent spy
scandals.
   The European Court of Human Rights is hearing complaints arising
from charges in 1985 that MI5 agents tapped the telephones of
anti-nuclear campaigners and labor union leaders on the instructions
of Cabinet ministers.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd on Thursday denied that MI5 is
``locked in some time warp of the 1950s, forever fighting shadows
that have long since disappeared.''
   But he refused to comment on whether agents have tapped labor
leaders' telephones. ``I am not going to comment on past
operations,'' he said.
   Under the bill, agents will require a warrant, now unnecessary,
from Hurd to bug or break into property, and an independent
commissioner will monitor the granting of warrants.
   The bill also provides for a tribunal of lawyers to hear
complaints from people who suspect they are targets of improper
surveillance. But critics charge official secrecy laws ban revealing
the activities of the secret services.
</TEXT>
