<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Walesa     12-15 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Sees Chance For Reconciliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's Lech Walesa said Thursday that
he sees increasing prospects for agreement with the communist
government, perhaps through long-awaited ``round table'' talks that
would include his banned union movement and the church.
   ``There is a chance now. I don't know if it is honest or just a
fake. But I cannot destroy it. There are many new elements which we
must notice,'' Walesa said at his first news conference since
returning from France on Monday.
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski meanwhile told a Communist
Party audience, ``We are looking for roads of still wider national
reconciliation.
   ``There is still only one criterion: a feeling of responsiblity
for the country and the good of Poland,'' Jaruzelski said in a
speech Thursday marking the party's 40th anniversary.
   Parts of Walesa's news conference were broadcast Thursday night
on state-controlled television, the first time his weekly meeting
with reporters was treated by the TV as a normal news event.
   Walesa said Solidarity, the independent union movement in the
Soviet bloc, remains ready for ``serious talks which would assure
pluralism.''
   ``Now, at the end of the year, there are buds of hope to obtain
solutions accepted by both sides. The round table is a chance which
could give life to these hopes, which were born out of seven years
of mutual brawling.''
   Plans to hold the talks broke down in November when authorities
refused to guarantee their willingness to relegalize the labor
federation, crushed in the martial law crackdown seven years ago
this week.
   But Walesa's appearance in a nationwide TV debate on Nov. 30 and
the increasing attention given his views in the state-controlled
media this month indicated a growing acceptance of the Solidarity
leader by officials.
   Walesa's being allowed to go to France also underlined his
improved standing with officials.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban on Tuesday praised Walesa's
statements during his trip and said the talks could discuss the
future of trade union pluralism.
   Asked about Urban's comments, Walesa said, ``It is very close to
dotting the `i,' but the dot is still missing.''
   Opposition sources said Walesa will meet this weekend with a
council of 60 independent intellectuals and worker activists that he
consults on major policy issues.
   In another development, the party leadership announced a Central
Committee meeting for Tuesday and Wednesday to discuss political
reforms and the role of the party. Urban has said the plenum could
bring new impetus to national agreement.
   Walesa said Solidarity has been maintaining contacts with
authorities through a Roman Catholic Church intermediary, the Rev.
Alojzy Orszulik.
   He said the talks would cover unions, economic problems and ways
``to cooperate to improve living conditions.''
   Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, agreed this year to end a
wave of strikes demanding relegalization of Solidarity after the
government agreed to the talks.
</TEXT>
