<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-US     12-15 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-US,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Ease Pressure on Noriega, Ambassador Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush will
continue diplomatic and economic sanctions imposed in an effort to
force out Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the de facto ruler of Panama,
the U.S. ambassador says.
   Bush ``will not be disposed to abandon the pressure for change
and democracy in Panama ... no matter what Noriega might want,''
Ambassador Arthur Davis told a dinner Wedneday night of the American
Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Panama. The embassy released his
remarks Thursday.
   Davis said the United States would end sanctions when Noriega
resigned as as commander of the Panamanian military, a position he
uses to control the country.
   ``The beginning of political stability only can be achieved if
Noriega relinquishes power,'' Davis said.
   Noriega is under U.S. indictment on charges of drug trafficking
and money laundering. He denies the accusations.
   ``In 1988, we have observed in Panama a progressive deterioration
of human rights, a growing disdain for justice and respect for laws,
the unconstitutional ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle, and
the loss of confidence in the economy,'' Davis declared.
   He said the government nominally led by President Manuel Solis
Palma was unconstitutional. Noriega arranged Delvalle's dismissal by
the National Assembly on Feb. 26, after Delvalle had tried to fire
the general.
   Davis said U.S. sanctions were not to blame for Panama's economic
crisis and were not meant to hurt the Panamanian people.
   ``The Panamanian economy cannot begin its recovery unless the
political crisis of this country is resolved in a satisfactory
manner for all Panamanians,'' he said.
   Economic sanctions, which which forbid U.S. operations to pay
taxes to Panama, ``are doing what they were created to do: they're
preventing cash from reaching the hands of an illegal regime,''
Davis said.
   Noriega claims Washington seeks an excuse to violate the 1977
treaties under which control of the Panama Canal will be given to
Panama on Dec. 31, 1999. Davis said canal security can be guaranteed
only with ``genuine progress toward democracy and a civilian and
constitutional government in Panama.''
   Davis said presidential elections scheduled for May 7 would be
worthless if Noriega remained in his post.
   ``As long as Noriega clings to power, we don't believe that the
elections can be accepted by Panamanians as the product of an
authentic process,'' he said.
   Most opposition parties take a similar position, arguing that
sufficient election and press guarantees do not exist. The
government has closed three newspapers, three radio stations and a
television station.
</TEXT>
