<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-GanderCrash     12-15 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Gander Crash,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charter Company Accepts Board's Report On Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Arrow Air accepted the Canadian
Aviation Safety Board's conclusion that ice on the wings caused a
plane crash at Gander, Newfoundland, that killed 256 Americans three
years ago.
   The letter to the board from lawyer Humphrey Dawson was obtained
Thursday by the Canadian Press news agency. It said that while Arrow
does ``not agree with some matters contained in the report, they do
accept the report as published and do not propose in any way to
challenge the same.''
   He did not elaborate on which matters the company disagrees.
   Arrow Air was the operator of the charter DC-8 that crashed on
Dec. 12, 1985, killing 248 U.S. troops and eight crew members. The
soldiers were heading home to Fort Campbell, Ky., from peacekeeping
duties in the Middle East.
   The board concluded Dec. 8 that ice on the wings was the likely
cause, but a significant minority said in a separate opinion that an
in-flight fire caused the crash.
   The often public disputes during the long investigation and the
sharp split led to repeated calls here for a judicial inquiry.
   Dawson said Arrow doesn't want one.
   ``It is my clients' present view that they would not participate
in any such review or inquiry, a view with which I wholly concur,''
he said.
   ``I hope the board will now be able to put this sad incident and
its recently troubled history behind it having regard to the
important role it must play in civil aviation in Canada.''
   He said the release of the board's majority and minority reports
means ``the issues on the whole have been raised.''
</TEXT>
