<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Military     12-15 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Military,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Accuses US of Continuing to Supply Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega
accused the Reagan administration Thursday of continuing supply
flights to Nicaraguan rebels in violation of a congressional ban.
   Gen. Ortega, whose brother Daniel is president of Nicaragua, also
told a news conference that battle casualties in 1988 were
dramatically lower than the previous year's total.
   He claimed Nicaraguan radar detected 10 clandestine supply
flights into Nicaragua from El Salvador in November.
   The United States has supported the rebels, known as Contras,
since 1981, two years after a civil war in which the leftist
Sandinistas deposed the late President Anastasio Somoza.
   Congress stopped U.S. military aid to the rebels at the end of
February but allowed distribution of non-lethal aid to continue in
neighboring Honduras. About 10,000 rebels returned to base camps in
Honduras to get the food and uniforms.
   Ortega said rebel forces totaled no more than 7,000, of whom
about 2,000 were in Nicaragua.
   He said the presence of Contras in Nicaragua means a war
situation still exists and the rebels ``can do damage.''
   Nicaragua has an army of about 80,000, the largest in Central
America, and gets its military equipment from the Soviet bloc.
   The defense minister said government forces killed 2,226 rebels
in 1988, down from 5,339 the previous year, and 611 Sandinista
soldiers were killed compared with 1,613 in 1987.
   He said civilian casualties rose to 1,748 from 1,675 in 1987, but
did not break the number down into dead and wounded. Ortega said the
number rose because of kidnappings by rebel forces.
   The Sandinistas and Contras signed a cease-fire March 23 that
called for the rebels to stop fighting in exchange for democratic
concessions. Talks on details of the agreement reached a stalemate
in September.
   Both sides stopped offensive operations March 21, when the talks
began. The government has renewed the cease-fire each month since a
formal 60-day truce ended May 31.
   On Thursday, the defense minister claimed the Contras had killed
69 civilians since the March agreement, wounded 79 and kidnapped
372. He said 70 soldiers had been killed, 73 were wounded and seven
were missing.
   Ortega, flanked by the military high command, said Nicaraguans
should be prepared for a U.S. invasion. The Sandinistas have made
that claim repeatedly.
   He said Honduran forces have harassed Nicaraguan positions on the
border to provoke a confrontation that would give Honduras an excuse
to request help from the United States.
</TEXT>
