<DOCNO> AP881215-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthYemen     12-15 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Yemen,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Yemen Gets $5.6 Million in Loans for Health Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist government of South Yemen will
get loans of $5.6 million from the World Bank and the United Nations
to improve health care, it was announced Thursday.
   The World Bank has come under fire in Congress for making loans
to the Communist governments among its 151 members. The U.S.
government holds the largest single block of World Bank stock, but
does not have a veto over loans.
   Of the $5.6 million, $4.5 million will come from the World Bank's
International Development Association. Its loan is repayable in 40
years, including 10 years during which only interest is payable at
0.75 of 1 percent a year.
   The rest of the money is being lent by the World Health
Organization and three U.N. funds: for children, capital development
and population activities.
   The money will help the People's Democratic Republic of South
Yemen construct 19 new buildings, including a nursing school, and
upgrade 26 others. Some of it also will go for medical supplies and
family planning material. About 400,000 people in the remote areas
of the Arabian peninsula will benefit, according to the World Bank
announcement.
</TEXT>
