<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay     12-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers of March, Arrested Last Week, Stage Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political activists began a hunger
strike after they were arrested for organizing a human rights march
that police broke up last weekend, the wife of opposition leader
Domingo Laino said Thursday.
   ``My husband was detained in the central police station on Dec. 6
when he went to find out about the imprisonment of other
politicians,'' Rafaela Guanes de Laino said.
   She said that Laino, president of the Authenthic Radical Liberal
Party, has refused to accept solid food since Dec. 7 and the
approximately 25 others detained since last week have done the same
since Monday.
   ``My children are worried ... because the police haven't taken
him to the Supreme Court of Justice in compliance with a writ of
habeas corpus our lawyers filed,'' Mrs. Guanes de Laino said.
   Saturday's march commemorated the 40th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, a United Nations document
under which member nations pledge to safeguard life and liberty and
abolish torture and slavery.
   The government of President Gen. Alfredo Stroessner banned the
seven-block walk from the national cathedral to the local U.N.
office on the ground the intention was to disturb the peace.
   When hundreds of people showed up anyway, police attacked them
with electric prods, rubber batons, fists and feet. No serious
injuries were reported, but about 100 people were detained.
   Most were released this week, but the organizers _ leaders of
opposition political parties, independent unions, religious groups _
remain in jail.
   ``Irregular sectors are immersed in a plan to destabilize and
bring down the government,'' Sabino Montanaro, the interior minister
and president of the governing Colorado Party, told party leaders
Thursday.
  
</TEXT>
