<DOCNO> AP881215-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-USAnniversary     12-15 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US Anniversary,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China, U.S. Celebrate 10 Years of Relations, Ponder Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese and American officials on Thursday began
three days of scholarly discussions and banquets to mark the 10th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations.
   In the first of many toasts to be raised over the next few days,
U.S. Ambassador Winston Lord told hundreds of Chinese scholars ``Let
us commit ourselves not only to expanding our exchanges of
delegations and goods, but also to that ever-elusive, more profound
goal _ the exchange of understanding.''
   China's Foreign Ministry plans a strait-laced dinner and evening
of traditional entertainment Friday at the imposing Great Hall of
the People.
   Lord's wife, Bette Bao Lord, said she is planning a more
light-hearted party Saturday that will involve ushers in panda suits.
   ``It's not going to be a reception, it will be a happening,'' she
said. ``We want to have fun.''
   Both sides said the state of Chinese-U.S. relations is cause for
celebration but acknowledged that friction exists over trade, human
rights issues and the status of the rival Nationalist government on
Taiwan.
   ``Ten years ago, nobody could imagine that the two countries
would develop the kinds of extensive and permeating contacts that
exist today,'' Zi Zhongyun, director of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences' Institute of American Studies, told a seminar
marking the anniversary.
   For decades after the Communists came to power in 1949, the
United States recognized their defeated rivals, the Nationalists on
Taiwan, as China's government. Ideological suspicion was reinforced
when the Chinese Communists and United States found themselves on
opposite sides in the 1950-53 Korean War.
   In 1972, President Richard Nixon made a dramatic trip to Beijing
and began a process of drawing closer to China that culminated on
Dec. 15, 1978, when President Jimmy Carter signed an accord
recognizing the Communist government.
   The agreement took effect Jan. 1, 1979.
   Since then, the United States has become China's second-largest
trading partner, after Japan, with 1988 trade projected at more than
$13.5 billion. More than 50,000 Chinese will travel to the United
States in 1988, Lord told the seminar Thursday, and about 300,000
Americans will visit China.
   Hundreds of cultural and scientific exchanges have taken place in
addition to regular visits by senior government officials.
   However, Ms. Zi said China remains unhappy over U.S. failure to
press Taiwan to enter into reunification talks with the mainland.
   She also repeated China's frequent charges of U.S. trade
protectionism and criticized U.S. use of technology transfer ``to
impose pressure on China.''
   Last year, the United States froze for months its liberalization
of technology transfers to China to protest China's use of force in
suppressing pro-independence demonstrations in Tibet in the last 14
months.
   In his speech, Lord said U.S. concern for human rights ``is
natural and universal. We do not single out China.'' He reiterated
that the United States recognizes China's sovereignty over Tibet but
pressed for greater access to the region by foreign journalists.
   Washington has not commented on the latest clash between Chinese
police and Tibetan activists, in which police on Saturday fatally
shot at least two people and injured 13.
   China says its rule over Tibet dates to the 13th century. Tibetan
activists claim their remote region was effectively independent from
China for centuries before Chinese Communist troops entered in 1950.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
