<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sweden-Palme 1stLd-Writethru a0662 12-15 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Palme, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Remanded In Custody, Signal Major Break in Palme Killing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to identify detained man. Pickup 6th graf
``The suspicions...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor ordered a 41-year-old Swede
held in custody Thursday in the slaying of Prime Minister Olof
Palme, signaling what could be a major break in Sweden's crime of
the century.
   The man detained Wednesday is suspected of ``having murdered Olof
Palme,'' Jorgen Almblad, spokesman for the prosecutor's office, told
Swedish Radio.
   Sweden's strict press and libel law forbids publication of a
suspect's name, but he was identified in public records as Christer
Pettersson.
   Palme, a four-term Social Democratic prime minister who
championed international peace and disarmament issues, was killed
the night of Feb. 28, 1986, while walking home unguarded with his
wife from a downtown movie theater.
   The killing jolted a nation which prides itself on orderliness
and had seen little of the political violence and terrorism that
plague other countries.
   Pettersson has a history of violent crime and a previous
conviction of manslaughter. He has been interrogated since he was
detained Wednesday.
   ``The suspicions from yesterday remain,'' said Almblad.
   A witness identified the man as someone who waited outside the
Grand Theater, where Palme had been just before he was fatally shot,
the radio reported without identifying its source. It said there
were discrepancies between witness accounts and the suspect's alibi.
   The killer followed Palme down the street after the prime
minister left the theater and shot him with a .357 magnum revolver
which has not been found.
   Before Wednesday, police were unable to produce a solid lead or a
motive in the killing, despite the largest manhunt in Swedish
history and a reward of $8 million. The investigation was marred by
squabbling between police and prosecutors, and the chief detective
in the case was replaced twice. Government commissions accused
police of incompetence in the investigation.
   Thursday's move means that prosecutors feel they have enough
evidence to build a case against the man and may hold him
indefinitely, although his attorney may dispute the remand order in
Stockholm District Court on Friday.
   ``There is reason to believe it will be a difficult case,'' said
Arne Liljeros, the public defender assigned to the case. ``My client
denies it, says it's a mistake,'' he said in a television interview.
   A friend of the suspect said the man was a member of the Sweden
Party, an ultra-rightist group that advocates white supremacy, the
national news agency TT reported. But police have not linked him
with the party, the report said.
   ``He didn't like Palme, he was angry at him,'' the unidentified
friend was quoted as saying.
   Authorities have refused to give details of their case, but
Swedish police reporters were given access to the suspect's file.
Reports said he had 63 convictions for various offenses and had
spent the last 22 years in and out of prisons and phychiatric wards.
   He was convicted of fatally stabbing an alleged drug addict with
a bayonet in 1970, just a few yards from the site of the Palme
killing.
   Almblad said the suspect had been under investigation ``for a
long time,'' but declined to give further details. The man had been
questioned in 1986, but was not arrested because his alibi appeared
sound at the time, according to TT.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0190 </DOCNO>
