<1ST_LINE>r w AM-O'Hare-Flights     12-15 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare-Flights,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American, United Airlines Agree to Change Schedules at O'Hare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two airlines that dominate Chicago's O'Hare
airport agreed Thursday on flight schedule changes aimed at reducing
the number of delays in and out of the airport next spring, the
Federal Aviation Administration said.
   After two days of meetings, American Airlines and United Airlines
agreed to stagger and more evenly distribute flights at O'Hare _ the
busiest airport in the nation _ especially during heavy travel
periods in the evening, officials said.
   ``We're pleased with the adjustments which should provide a
substantial reduction in delays we've been experiencing (at
Chicago),'' said FAA spokesman Dick Stafford.
   Most of the adjustments will go into effect March 1 when the
airlines put their spring schedules into place.
   The discussions under the direction of the FAA were being
conducted at a hotel near Washington.
   Flight delays have increased at O'Hare in recent months after the
FAA reduced the maximum number of flights allowed each hour at the
airport. The flight restrictions were imposed because of concern
that air traffic controllers were being asked to handle too many
planes.
   There has been a sharp increase in controller errors involving
air traffic in the Chicago area this year.
   American and United together have about 60 percent of the flights
at O'Hare.
   Stafford said the adjustments agreed upon by the two airlines
will be closely watched by the FAA when they go into effect. ``If we
find out the agreement isn't working, we'll call the carriers back
in again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
