<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Strike     12-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Strike,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Say Government Must Give More To Workers, Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of the one-day general strike
that jolted Spain to a standstill demanded on Thursday that Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez give workers and the poor a bigger share of
the country's growing prosperity.
   Nicolas Redondo, head of the General Workers' Union, told
reporters that Wednesday's 24-hour strike was ``a victory for all of
Spanish society.''
   ``The government has to be sensitive to the demands of the union
movement,. It should not underestimate what has happened or try to
fool itself,'' he said.
   His union is a century-old ally of Gonzalez's governing Socialist
Party.
   In a statement Thursday, the prime minister acknowledged ``the
political success'' of the strike and admitted it represented ``a
tough political blow for the government.''
   The unions estimate that 7.8 million of Spain's 11.8 million
employed stayed off the job to protest austere economic policies.
   Gonzalez said the government would give its view of the strike in
Parliament next Wednesday and seek a first meeting with union
leaders the following day.
   But government spokeswoman Rosa Conde said the government's
position ``will not vary substantially.''
   The General Workers' Union joined the communist-dominated Workers
Commissions to organize the strike after talks with the government
broke down a month ago over demands for more pay, unemployment
benefits and pensions.
   Redondo warned that the two unions will organize more strikes and
demonstrations if the government fails to satisfy their demands.
   Redondo and Secretary-General Antonio Gutierrez of the Workers
Commissions told reporters the government must accept the unions'
basic demands prior to their entering wide-ranging negotiations on
economic policies repeatedly offered by Gonzalez.
   These include wage and pension demands, expanded unemployment
benefits, granting civil servants collective bargaining rights and
withdrawing a youth employment plan the unions reject as
exploitative.
   The unions have denounced Gonzalez' anti-inflation, high-growth
economic policies which caused a boom in the last three years. They
complain that the policies failed to reduce unemployment, which at
18.7 percent remains the highest in Europe.
   Redondo said it was time to compensate workers and the poor for
sacrifices the unions contend made the boom possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
