<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ColliderReports     12-15 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collider Reports,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Spends $1.3 Million Sending Collider Reports to the
Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department came under criticism
Thursday from an Illinois congressman who said the department wasted
$1.5 million by mailing a 26-pound, 23-volume report on the
superconducting super collider to 16,000 people, sometimes sending
four to a family.
   A department spokesman, Jeff Sherwood, disputed the figures cited
by Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., saying the report actually went to
about 17,000 people and cost $1.3 million.
   ``This is crazy,'' said Hastert, whose district includes one of
the rejected sites for the collider. ``It's just a lack of common
sense.''
   The document at issue is an 8,000-page environmental impact
statement on possible sites for the $4.4 billion atom smasher in
Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, Michigan, North Carolina, Tennessee and
Texas.
   Energy Secretary John Herrington announced Nov. 10 that Texas
would house the project, a 53-mile, underground ring of magnets
which would whip proton beams together with 20 times the force of
the most powerful existing atom smasher.
   Scientists hope to learn more about the nature of matter from
studying subatomic particles created by the proton collisions.
   The department sent copies of the environmental statement to
everyone who testified at hearings on the project or submitted
written comments on any of the seven finalist sites, Sherwood said.
   ``It is government practice that both draft and final documents
be made available to interested parties as part of the environmental
review process,'' he explained. ``In order to comply with that
process, the department mailed that document out.''
   However, Hastert said an expensive mailing went far beyond the
requirement that agencies keep people involved in the site-selection
process.
   ``The law says people have to be contacted; they don't have to
send all this stuff,'' he said. ``If the department sent a letter
with a reply card, maybe they'd get 1 percent that would want the
report. Then, just making them available in libraries would be
enough.
   ``Why not do that? We're scrimping to cut spending by pennies,
dimes and nickles in Congress. They're spending almost $1{ million,
here, when we could be using that money to build highways or feed
the homeless. What a waste!''
   Sherwood acknowledged that the mailing might alienate members of
Congress who will decide whether to appropriate money for the
collider.
   ``I understand where the argument is coming from. I don't know
who made the ultimate decision,'' he said. ``But if we hadn't
distributed (the report), we would have been criticized for that as
well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
