<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CriticsAwards     12-15 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Critics Awards,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Accidental Tourist' Named Best Picture by New York Critics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Accidental Tourist,'' a movie about the
emotional journey of a travel writer, was named best picture of 1988
on Thursday by the New York Film Critics Circle.
   The award couldn't have come at a better time for ``Accidental
Tourist,'' which opens next Friday in New York, Los Angeles and
Toronto. The movie, which was screened in advance for critics, is
based on the best-selling novel by Anne Tyler.
   The Critics Circle gave Meryl Streep its best actress award for
``A Cry in the Dark,'' in which she played an Australian mother
charged with killing her infant child. Jeremy Irons was named best
actor for his double portrayal of twin gynecologists in ``Dead
Ringers.''
   The best supporting actor award went to Dean Stockwell for two
movies _ ``Married to the Mob'' and ``Tucker.'' Diane Venora won the
best supporting actress award for her work in ``Bird.''
   The best foreign language film was ``Women on the Verge of a
Nervous Breakdown,'' the Spanish movie about a woman whose lover
leaves her. ``Thin Blue Line,'' a film about the murder of a Dallas
police officer, won the award for best documentary.
   The best director award went to Chris Menges for ``A World
Apart.'' Henri Alekan was named best cinematographer for ``Wings of
Desire.'' The best screenplay award went to Ron Shelton for ``Bull
Durham.''
   The New York Film Critics Circle is an organization of more than
two dozen New York-based critics for both print and broadcast media.
</TEXT>
