<DOCNO> AP881215-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NuclearWaste     12-15 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Waste,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE, Three Governors To Meet On Nuke Waste Impasse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Garrey in 13th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Energy Department officials will meet
here with the governors of three western states Friday in an attempt
to resolve an impasse over storage of radioactive wastes from
nuclear weapons plants.
   The governors of Idaho, Colorado and New Mexico said they want to
hear proposals to solve the problem when they meet with Joseph
Salgado, chief deputy to Energy Secretary John Herrington, and other
regional DOE officials.
   The immediate problem is to find a storage site for seven boxcars
of radioactive material _ and enough additional waste to fill 17
more _ sitting outside the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant near
Denver.
   The other question is when the federal government will open its
Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a prototype for permanent waste storage
facilities under construction in southwestern New Mexico.
   Doug Elmet, a spokesman for the DOE in Washington, said Thursday
the purpose of the meeting was to provide ``a chance for some
straight talk between the governors and the federal government.''
   But the governors said they hope federal officials will have an
answer to the problem.
   ``I've got all the information I need. What I need now is for
them to come and say, `We have got our act together,''' Idaho Gov.
Cecil Andrus said at a Thursday news conference. ``They should come
with a proposal that the three governors can deal with.''
   Waste has been stacking up at Rocky Flats, which manufactures
plutonium components for nuclear weapons, since October when Andrus
turned away a boxcar headed for the Idaho National Engineering
Laboratory and said the state would accept no more shipments.
   Andrus said he would not open the laboaratory to additional
shipments until the pilot plant is opened and DOE has outlined a
plan to remove existing waste from Idaho. Since the ban was imposed,
he said, ``There has been no progress for two months, which tells me
I was right to put my foot down.''
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer said he would require Rocky Flats to
suspend production once its temporary storage capacity is filled.
Romer said during a news conference Thursday that he would not
consider a 90-day extension that would permit DOE to keep waste
beyond the plant's capacity.
   ``If they don't have a solution, they are going to have to close
it by failing to act,'' Romer said. ``I do not want a de facto dump
here. That's why I've kept that storage in those boxcars.''
   Romer said he did not expect an immediate solution to the Rocky
Flats problem, but said he hoped the DOE would ``put some alternate
solutions on the table.''
   Don Caviness, spokesman for New Mexico Gov. Garrey Carruthers,
said his boss wanted the Department of Energy to provide a firm
deadline for opening the pilot plant and an update on the progress
of some $240 million in mitigation funds the state has been
promised. Under an agreement signed between the state and DOE eight
years ago, New Mexico is to receive $190 million to build bypasses
around major cities through which waste would be shipped, and $50
million to compensate for lost mining royalties.
   Caviness said Carruthers would not permit the pilot plant to open
until those pledges are fulfilled.
   ``The DOE is in the awkward position. The governor is not going
to have the WIPP site open until the terms are met. New Mexico has
no intention of rolling over because the governors of other states
have problems,'' said Caviness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2053EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChurchofLove     12-15 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church of Love,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church of Love Case Goes To Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a man and a woman accused of
bilking 31,000 men out of $4.5 million with phony stories of a
retreat inhabited by nude ``love angels'' went to a jury Thursday.
   In closing arguments, defense attorneys told the jurors that
defendants Donald Lowry, 59, and Pamala St. Charles, 25, are ``two
of the nicest people ... you'll ever meet.''
   Prosecutors contend Lowry, founder of the Church of Love, and Ms.
St. Charles, his assistant, defrauded lonely men with a mail-order,
sex-fantasy scam that exchanged pictures of nude women and phony
letters for contributions to a non-existent rural church paradise.
The letters asked for donations of money for the angels' supposed
needs, including garden seeds, winter coats and sewing machines.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Darilynn Knauss charged in her closing
argument that the defendants were con artists. But defense Attorney
William G. Schick argued the church was a legitimate business and
described Lowry and Ms. St. Clair as ``two of the nicest people who
care more about others than anyone you'll ever meet.''
   Prosecutors said Wednesday that Ms. St. Charles wrote to church
members telling them not to cooperate with a federal investigation.
   ``Why should you cooperate with them when it is to their
advantage only?'' Ms. St. Charles wrote in the letter introduced in
court. ``They are the enemy.''
   The letter was sent to Church of Love members who attended a
November 1986 convention called ``The Gathering,'' which was held in
a Chicago hotel, prosecutors said.
   Under questioning from her attorney, William G. Schick of Moline,
Ms. St. Charles said she wasn't trying to block the investigation,
but was concerned that investigators may have given false
information about the church to members.
   Ms. St. Charles and Lowry are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud
and unlawful use of funds fraudulently obtained through the COL Corp.
   She and Lowry now operate the International Order of Knights, a
mail order operation that clearly states that its letters from
``fantasy girls'' are fictional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
