<DOCNO> AP881215-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2054EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InvestmentFundLoss     12-15 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Investment Fund Loss,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mystery Behind W.Va.'s $200 Million Loss Slowly Clearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $200 million drop in West Virginia
investment funds are actual dollar losses, not interest, and
resulted from poor sales, state treasury officials said Thursday.
   As jittery local governments continued to pull their money from
the state investment pool, treasury officials said they sold off $30
million worth of securities early to satisfy a run on the investment
account.
   In addition, Treasurer A. James Manchin said the man in charge of
investments at the time of the 1987 loss _ former Associate
Treasurer Arnold T. Margolin _ was warned by his staff about the bad
investments but did nothing to halt them.
   The loss was not revealed until this week, and the news has
spurred a four-day run by local and county governments on the
state's consolidated investment fund, in which state agencies and
local governments place money for investment by the state.
   The local governments pulled out another $37 million Thursday,
bringing to $146 million the investment fund withdrawals since
Monday _ about half of what the agencies had invested.
   Assistant Treasurer Charles Capet said $30 million worth of
securities was sold at a loss to raise the funds needed to pay the
local governments. The state also sold other matured securities and
all its interest earnings were used to meet the demand. ``It's a day
to day thing,'' Capet said.
   ``From the newspaper reports that I've seen and the lack of an
explanation from those in charge, our money would be at risk in the
account if we were to wait for an explanation,'' said Jefferson
County Administrator David Ash, whose county commission Thursday
withdrew the $1.6 million it had in the investment fund.
   Manchin, who is in charge of the investment fund, said he
suspects no wrongdoing in the loss.
   ``It was just bad investments,'' he said Thursday.
   The treasurer has asked the U.S. attorney's office and state
officials to investigate the loss, however. U.S. Attorney Michael
Carey directed Manchin's request to the FBI, which has not decided
whether to investigate.
   At Manchin's request, the private accounting firm of Touche Ross
& Co. is investigating the loss.
   Margolin, who submitted his resignation last month to join the
staff of Gov.-elect Gaston Caperton as chief financial adviser, has
said he is awaiting the results of the Touche Ross investigation
before commenting.
   Manchin has refused to accept Margolin's resignation until the
matter is cleared up. He has challenged Margolin to reveal publicly
what happened, since Margolin said he has explained the situation to
Caperton.
   ``He was the man directly responsible,'' Manchin said of
Margolin. ``If Arnie explained it to Caperton, why doesn't he
explain it to the people? This is strange silence. He's hiding
behind the governor-elect.''
   But Caperton spokesman Steve Cohen quoted Margolin as saying that
he notified Manchin as soon as he discovered the losses. The
governor-elect said he retains the ``fullest confidence'' in
Margolin.
   Assistant Treasurer Charles Capet said the bad investments were
made over a 6- to 8-month period. He said the assets were purchased
at a high price and sold at a lower price.
   Former Assistant Treasurer Kathy Lester, who actually made the
investments under Margolin, was quoted in The Charleston Gazette on
Thursday as saying that she was retaining a lawyer and would have no
comment.
   Assistant Treasurer Mary Hudson, who now is in charge of
investments, said the consolidated investment fund this week totaled
$1.572 billion, or $208 million less than last December. The fund
was $2.4 billion at the end of 1986.
</TEXT>
