<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PostOfficeSiege 1stLd-Writethru a0653 12-15 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Post Office Siege, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Wounds Three, Holds Girlfriend Hostage For 13 Hours</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, `Murphy was ..., to UPDATE with hearing;
^LaserPhoto NU3</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A postal worker who shot and wounded three
people and held his girlfriend hostage for almost 13 hours was
coaxed into surrendering Thursday by an old acquaintance _ the
police chief.
   ``I just tried to appeal to him as a father,'' Warren Woodfork
said. ``I'm glad it worked. I'm not a trained hostage negotiator.''
   Warren Murphy, 39, gave himself up in the main New Orleans post
office shortly after 9 a.m. and released his hostage, 29-year-old
Carol Smith, unharmed, said police spokeswoman Carmine Menchel.
   Murphy was booked with assault with intent to commit murder, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Lance Africk. U.S. Magistrate Michaelle
Wynne sent Murphy to undergo psychiatric evaluation at a federal
lockup in Springfield, Mo.
   Three post office workers hit by birdshot from Murphy's gun
during the siege, which began about 8:30 p.m. Wednesday, were not
seriously wounded, officials said.
   Woodfork, who negotiated with Murphy for about two hours, said he
knew the gunman because their sons had played football together.
   He said Murphy was concerned about a marital breakup and the
welfare of his children who reportedly were in his estranged wife's
custody in Washington.
   FBI spokeswoman Nancy Fisher identified Smith, also a postal
employee, as Murphy's girlfriend.
   ``He wasn't angry at her,'' Fisher said. ``He was upset over a
family matter. After the shooting started, he just grabbed her.''
   Volney Hayes, an FBI spokesman, said Murphy, after arriving for
work Wednesday evening, pulled a birdshot-loaded shotgun out of a
bag and started shooting.
   He hit one person in the eye, another in the thigh and another in
the arm.
   Postal employee Leonard King, hit in the eye, was reported in
good condition at Tulane Medical Center. Another victim who was
unidentified was in fair condition at Tulane, a spokesman said. At
Charity Hospital, a spokeswoman said a third victim, also
unidentified, was discharged Thursday.
   About 400 postal workers and customers fled when the shooting
broke out, authorities said. About 100 others took cover and hid for
four hours before being escorted out by officers making a
room-by-room search for the gunman.
   When the shooting began, Pat Wingerter of New Orleans was
standing in line with his Christmas cards.
   ``I heard one shot and then the people started coming out,''
Wingerter said. ``Even after the shot, there were people driving up
mailing letters for about five minutes. It was crazy.''
   After eluding police for five hours, the gunman was cornered with
his hostage in a windowless coffee break room with a single door.
Hayes said Murphy chased off agents with gunfire.
   More gunfire erupted sporadically through the night when Murphy
apparently became frustrated, Hayes said. No one was hurt, he said.
   ``They were just random shots,'' he said. ``They haven't been at
anyone. ... just stick the barrel under the door and fire.''
   Once it was apparent there was no danger to people outside the
building, police lifted roadblocks around the building, allowing
rush hour traffic to proceed on the busy streets surrounding the
post office.
   Hayes said Murphy made his only demand about 9 a.m., telling
negotiators he wanted to see no news reporters.
   A few minutes later, Murphy surrendered.
   ``I told him I'd meet him halfway, and when he walked out I was
there,'' Woodfork said. ``He had thrown the shotgun out.''
   Postal inspector Don Durken said he didn't know how Murphy got
the gun into the post office.
   ``Most of our entrances are secured,'' said Durken. ``But it's a
big building. The loading docks are open at times. Unless you had
someone every 20 feet, it would be hard to make sure nothing ever
got through.''
</TEXT>
