<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0726,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Taps Kemp for HUD, Nearing Decision on Tower for Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Tower; PICKS UP 11th graf
pvs bgng, `Sullivan is'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush will name onetime rival
Rep. Jack Kemp of New York as secretary of housing and urban
development and was poised to make a decision on former Sen. John
Tower as defense secretary, sources said Thursday.
   Sources close to both Kemp and the vice president said Kemp had
accepted the job after meeting with Bush on Wednesday and that the
HUD announcement could come either Friday or Monday.
   Meanwhile, Tower was tentatively set to talk with Bush on Friday.
A final FBI background check on the former chairman of the Senate
Armed Services Committee was presented to the vice president on
Thursday.
   Transition officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said the lengthy background check did not uncover any problems that
would hurt Tower's chances for Senate confirmation.
   Kemp, 53, a former professional football quarterback who has
championed conservative causes, was a distant also-ran in the
Republican primaries last winter. He was an original sponsor of the
1981 tax cut legislation later endorsed by President Reagan and is
an ardent advocate of free enterprise and government deregulation.
   Kemp has called for housing vouchers for the poor and allowing
tenants of public housing to purchase their units at low cost as
part of his urban redevelopment proposals.
   Meanwhile, Bush moved closer to filling two other Cabinet
appointments, transition sources said.
   Bush met privately with Dr. Louis Sullivan, a black medical
school chief and contender for secretary of health and human
services, and was on the verge of naming Samuel Skinner as secretary
of transportation, according to the sources.
   Gary MacDougal, a Chicago business executive and Bush transition
adviser, also has emerged as a top candidate for secretary of labor,
sources said.
   The sources, who commented only on condition they not be
identified, said Bush may fill some of the eight remaining vacancies
in his Cabinet on Friday.
   He has filled six Cabinet departments so far and has said he
wants to finish before Christmas.
   Transition legal counsel C. Boyden Gray delivered his final
background report on Tower to Bush on Thursday.
   Bush has delayed a decision on whether to name Tower, 63, defense
secretary pending completion of an extensive FBI investigation of
the former Texas senator's background, including an acrimonious
divorce.
   Sullivan is not the only black reportedly under consideration for
the Bush Cabinet, which already includes a Hispanic, Lauro F.
Cavazos, the holdover secretary of education. Retired Army Gen.
Julius W. Becton Jr., who now runs the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, is in the running to head the new Department of Veterans
Affairs.
   Bush told reporters only that he had a ``very good'' meeting with
Sullivan.
   Transition sources said Sullivan, 55, president of Morehouse
School of Medicine in Atlanta, assured Bush at the meeting that he
shared the vice president's anti-abortion views.
   Bush and Sullivan are friends. He accompanied Bush on a trip to
South Africa in 1982, and Barbara Bush serves on the Morehouse board
of trustees. Sullivan introduced the future first lady at the
Republican convention in New Orleans last August.
   Although transition officials formally said there was no final
decision on the HHS post, Bush has made a practice of meeting with
his prospective Cabinet choice shortly before an announcement.
   Skinner, 50, is chairman of the Regional Transportation Authority
of Northeastern Illinois.
   Bush said Wednesday that he expects to name a black to his
Cabinet.
   At a photo opportunity before meeting with transition advisers
and talent scouts, the vice president brushed aside a question about
whether he may appoint two blacks to the Cabinet.
   ``Don't believe all the rumors that are around. Just wait to have
an announcement,'' said Bush, who also told reporters that after the
transition, he won't allow questions at picture-taking sessions.
   ``Talking at photo ops will continue until Jan. 20 and after that
there will be absolutely none,'' Bush said. ``And then I'll have
other ways of communicating that will be much more pleasant for you
and much more pleasant for me and much more respectful of our guests
like foreign visitors.''
   He said the current practice of trying to sandwich in questions
during picture-taking sessions was ``demeaning to your profession.''
   MacDougal, 52, former chairman of Mark Controls Corp., is
reportedly among four candidates on a short list for the labor job,
along with Washington labor lawyer William Kilberg; Patricia Diaz
Dennis, a member of the Federal Communications Commission, and Frank
Doyle, a senior vice president for General Electric. Constance
Horner, the head of the Office of Personnel Management, has faded as
a top contender, administration sources said.
   Gray, the transition lawyer, said background checks now are under
way on candidates for subcabinet jobs.
   As for Tower, Gray said he did not know whether Bush would ask
him to pursue further any aspect of the extensive checking already
completed.
   One of the leading proponents of the Strategic Defense
Initiative, retired Lt. Gen. Daniel O. Graham, said Thursday he
opposes a Tower nomination because the former Senate Armed Services
Committee chairman ``is not for SDI.''
   Graham, founder of High Frontier, a lobbying group for the
space-based missile shield, said Tower would be ``in the pocket of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff'' and would sacrifice SDI to preserve
weapons in the Pentagon arsenal. He predicted Tower would not get
the job ``mainly because he's carrying so much baggage around on his
back.''
</TEXT>
