<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-WorldReax 2ndLd-Writethru   12-15 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-World Reax, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0716,0936</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Decision Hailed As Step Toward Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 20-23, `Khaled Musamer...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with later Hussein, British reaction. Pick up 24th pvs, `Japan
welcomed...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Israel-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians, the Arab world generally and many other countries
said Thursday the U.S. decision to talk with the PLO may bring new
life to stagnant Middle East peace negotiations.
   ``I could scream and cry and say, `Happy new peaceful era, Arabs
and Israelis!''' said Nawal Saadi, 44, a pharmacist whose family
fled Israeli-held Jerusalem for Amman, Jordan.
   Mrs. Saadi, one of 1.5 million Palestinians in Jordan, wept as
she said: ``Israel has to know that Arabs, and especially
Palestinians, are for peace and the wise U.S. decision does not mean
Israel will be thrown into the sea. ... We want to live in peace and
share the same land.''
   Mohammed Milhem, a former Palestinian mayor who was expelled from
the Israeli-occupied West Bank, said Wednesday's announcement was
``a great step by a great nation.''
   ``One of the major roadblocks has now been removed to convening
an international conference and the peaceful co-existence between
all peoples and all religions and all states,'' Milhem, former mayor
of Halhoul and a member of the PLO's ruling executive committee,
said in Amman.
   Some radical factions of the Palestine Liberation Organization
also hailed the U.S. decision.
   Kays al-Samarai, spokesman for the Marxist Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, called it ``a new victory for the PLO''
and for the intefadeh _ the year-old Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   George Habash, leader of the radical Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, called it a victory for the uprising even
though ``the U.S. administration says that initiating the dialogue
does not entail recognition of Palestinian rights to ... an
independent state.''
   Palestinians declared an independent state last month.
   Habash's statement referred to ``Israel'' instead of ``the
Zionist entity,'' the phrase his group and other factions
traditionally have used to describe the Jewish state.
   In Israel, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said it was ``sad day
for all of us.''
   President Reagan said in Washington that the move was ``just
another step'' in the Middle East peace process and Israel should
not worry about the U.S. commitment to its security.
   In the West Bank and Gaza, delighted Palestinans marched in the
streets to celebrate.
   Some Palestinians opposed the concessions made by PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat, such as renouncing terrorism and recognizing Israel's
right to exist, which effectively denies many Palestinians the dream
of returning someday to their homes.
   ``Armed struggle is our only option. Palestine is for the
Palestinian people and not for Israel,'' said Hassan Daher, a
22-year-old student at the Arab University of Beirut.
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and King Hussein of Jordan
praised the U.S. decision and predicted it will lead to an
international conference on Middle East peace.
   Mubarak said the decision was a beginning, but Israel must
withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza and allow establishment of a
Palestinian state. He accused Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who
opposes an international conference, of delaying peace efforts.
   Egypt's leading newspaper, the state-owned Al Ahram, said the
U.S. announcement came hours after Mubarak telephoned Secretary of
State George P. Shultz ``to urge him to take a positive attitude
toward the constructive decisions of the PLO.''
   Hussein, after meeting with Mubarak in Cairo, and said: ``I
believe the ice has been broken. ... I believe the peace process has
begun, and we hope to see it accelerate in the near future.''
   Later, in a satellite TV interview with ``CBS Evening News,''
Hussein said Americans ``should understand that the Palestinians and
their representatives have opted for peace ... I know Arafat to be a
man who is determined to stand by his word (in renouncing terrorism)
... That's good enough for me.''
   Khaled Musamer, a PLO spokesman in Amman, noted that the
Americans said the talks would start at a low level, but added: ``We
hope it will be more than that after the first meeting and
especially under the new American president.''
   In Britain, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Arafat's recent
statements qualified the PLO to take part in a peace conference.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said later in a British
Broadcasting Corp. interview, ``There has been courage and clarity
from the Palestinian side. We must now look for the same kind of
response from Israel.''
   President Francois Mitterrand of France said the decision ``has
brought peace in the region a step closer.''
   Japan welcomed the U.S. declaration as ``an important step toward
progress.''
   Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita of Italy, who was visiting
Washington, concurred, and Vatican radio called the American
decision a sign that ``the force of reason begins to prevail.''
   The governments of Belgium, Greece, Australia and East Germany
were among those praising the action.
   Holland said it would send a delegation of senior diplomats to
Tunis, Tunisia, for talks with the PLO and the European Parliament
urged member nations to recognize the PLO as a Palestinian
government-in-exile.
   An-Nidaa, a Beirut daily, carried the headline: ``American
Retreat Under Blows of Stone-Throwing Heroes.''
   Saudi Arabia's official news agency used the headline ``Finally,
American-Palestinian dialogue.''
   In an Amman refugee camp, accountant Said Khalidy said: ``I never
expected the United States would look at us or care to find a
solution to the Palestinian issue.''
</TEXT>
