<DOCNO> AP881215-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YellowstoneFires     12-15 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Fires,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Panel Recommends Temporary Halt to `Let It Burn' Policy for
Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal panel on Thursday recommended a
temporary halt to the ``let it burn'' policy in national parks and
wilderness areas to make sure everybody understands what the policy
means.
   In a report to the secretaries of agriculture and interior, the
advisory panel said current policies permitting fires to burn under
predetermined conditions ``are sound, but the policies themselves
need to be refined, strengthened and reaffirmed.''
   Until the moratorium is lifted, fires will be put out, officials
said.
   ``No ... natural fires are to be allowed until fire management
plans meet these standards,'' the report said.
   Charles Philpot, co-chairman of the review panel, told reporters
he expected ``the moratorium would be finished by the beginning of
the Western fire season, which is the middle of May.''
   Philpot is a former Forest Service official who is now special
assistant to the deputy secretary of agriculture.
   The secretaries of Interior and Agriculture appointed the
committee in September after the worst fire season in history in
Wyoming's Yellowstone National Park. Some 249 fires in and near the
park prompted complaints from residents and their representatives in
Congress that their communities were being ruined by smoke and the
collapse of tourism.
   The panel reviewed fire management policy on all federal lands,
not just Yellowstone. The panel said it found that some plans did
not spell out the conditions under which natural fires would be
allowed to burn.
   Some plans also did not consider ``values at risk outside of
parks and wilderness and the number of fires that can be managed at
one time,'' and ``cumulative effects of drought.''
   The panel's other co-chairman, Brad Leonard, deputy director of
the Interior Department's Office of Program Analysis, estimated that
``Twenty-five to 30 percent of the plans have some shortcomings.
Some of them are minor.''
   The Interior Department contains the National Park Service and
the Agriculture Department contains the Forest Service, which
supervises many wilderness areas and manages much national forest
land adjacent to Yellowstone.
   Interior's Bureau of Land Management, Fish and Wildlife Service
and Bureau of Indian Affairs also manage affected lands.
   The agencies insist they don't have ``let it burn'' policies but
rather ``let it burn if it meets our criteria'' policies.
   The report said the agencies reject as ``impractical and
unprofessional'' the practice that fires can be allowed to burn free
of conditions laid down in advance or appropriate suppression
action. It said some employees essentially had advocated that policy
as long as fire didn't escape the agency's land.
   The report said Interior and Agriculture agencies should make
sure that fire management plans conform to departmental policies,
that employees understand the policies, that everybody is using a
common vocabulary and that agencies have agreed beforehand what to
do if fires threaten to move across administrative boundaries.
   Denis Galvin, deputy director of the Park Service, said his
agency had had the report for 24 hours, and would be submitting
comments to the two secretaries.
   ``I don't see it as a major shift,'' Galvin said. ``It's clear
we'll do more around developed areas'' in deliberately set fires to
clear firebreaks or other techniques.
   The report, which will remain open for public comment for 60
days, recommended more research on when deliberately set fires can
be used and how to use them in lodgepole pine forests, the dominant
kind in Yellowstone.
   Many people interviewed said this technique should be available
for all federal land, though it has been little used in Yellowstone
and practically never in lodgepole because of the difficulty of
controlling it.
   The fires in Yellowstone were particularly intense because of
more than a century's buildup of dead trees and other matter on the
forest floor.
   ``There is little agreement on whether management objectives can
be achieved through planned ignitions when they result in high
intensity crown fire,'' the report said.
   Bill Linenesch of the National Parks and Conservation Association
said he saw no reason why all parks should be barred from letting
fires burn until every management plan had been approved.
   ``The lesson of the summer is that you cannot choreograph
nature,'' said Dave Simon of the association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
