<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Attack     12-15 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Attack,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Official's House Attacked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The house of the second-ranking
official in the U.S. Embassy was attacked with grenades last month,
the embassy reported Thursday.
   Neither David Dlouhy, the deputy chief of mission, nor any of his
family members or domestic employees was injured in the Nov. 25
nighttime attack.
   Embassy spokesman Joseph McManus told The Associated Press that
men traveling in two cars through the affluent neighborhood of
Maquilishuat threw several grenades and that two landed at the wall
surrounding Dlouhy's house.
   McManus said the two grenades caused some material damage, but no
injuries.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said one
of the explosives bounced off the top of the wall into the yard.
   A woman was wounded by shrapnel from another grenade thrown
farther down the road, according to newspaper reports published in
the days after the attack. Those reports did not mention the attack
on Dlouhy's home.
   No group claimed responsibility for the Maquilishuat attack.
Because other grenades were thrown at other homes, it was unclear if
the attackers considered Dlouhy's house their specific target.
   Four days after the attack, leftist guerrillas briefly took over
two San Salvador radio stations to broadcast a statement saying U.S.
Embassy officials and U.S. buildings were considered ``legitimate
targets'' in the 9-year-old civil war.
   The centrist government's war effort is funded by the United
States.
   The guerrillas, on their clandestine radio station, previously
made similar statements.
   The wall around the offices of the U.S. Agency for International
Development was struck by a rocket-propelled grenade in October.
</TEXT>
