<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-PLO 1stLd-Writethru   12-15 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0650,0903</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Reacts With Shock and Dismay</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 20 grafs UPDATING with Shamir aide saying dialogue
doomed to collapse, report that Shamir considering steps to make
U.S. move fade, more Pickering quotes. PICK up 17th pvs, `Shamir,
the...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leaders responded with anger and dismay
Thursday to the U.S. declaration that it will talk with the PLO, a
stunning reversal of policy to which they were given no time to
object.
   Some Israelis were left with a sense of betrayal by the way the
announcement was handled. Others said the dialogue with the
Palestine Liberation Organization is doomed to collapse.
   ``We believe that the United States will discover very soon the
true face of the PLO, and will realize that it cannot be a partner
for negotiations and peace,'' said Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   According to the daily Haaretz, Shamir was considering a
unilateral Israeli step ``that will make the U.S. decision fade.''
   The initiative amounted to granting a limited self-rule to 1.5
million Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied lands, Haaretz said in
a front-page report in its Friday editions.
   The daily Hadashot described Washington's decision as ``the most
painful diplomatic slap in the face that Israel has received since
its establishment. We have been left alone to face the entire
world.''
   Israeli officials said they were notified only 30 minutes before
Secretary of State George P. Shultz made the announcement, which
allowed no time for an attempt to dissuade the Americans.
   Analysts said Israel will face mounting pressure for a favorable
response to the PLO and delay could endanger relations with
Washington, which is its main ally and provides $3 billion a year in
aid.
   If U.S. talks with the PLO succeed, pressure would grow for
Israel to accept a U.N.-sponsored peace conference, which many
Israelis see as a forum for demanding unreasonable concessions from
the Jewish state.
   A conference probably would consider such issues as the Israeli
settlements that dot the occupied territories, return of the
territories, the status of Jerusalem and the central question of an
independent Palestinian state.
   An example of what Israel considers unreasonable was a provision
in a U.N. General Assembly resolution passed Thursday for U.N.
supervision of the occupied territories and Jerusalem, which Israel
has declared its capital.
   Such right-wing leaders as Yitzhak Modai of the Likud bloc said
Israel was prepared to take the heat.
   ``The United States wants to speak to the PLO, but this doesn't
require us to speak with the PLO,'' Modai said. ``The United States
can advise us and even pressure us here and there, but we have to
know how to withstand the pressures.''
   Palestinians called the U.S. decision a victory of their year-old
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, in which more
than 320 Palestinians and 13 Israelis have been killed.
   Yossi Ben-Aharon, a senior aide to Shamir, told foreign reporters
there could be no solutions to Palestinian problems without Israel.
   ``They are still where they were in the camps,'' he said. ``We
are still running the show. Their lot ... has not changed by this
American move. The agent to bring about change is Israel, and
nothing can be done by bypassing Israel.''
   Shultz sent an explanatory message to Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres, the leaders of Israel's caretaker government.
   A text released by Israeli officials said: ``I know how sensitive
an issue this is for you and the people of Israel. The dialogue that
is about to be launched is not an end in itself. It must focus on
the core issue of negotiations to end the Arafat-Israeli conflict.''
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering passed on oral assurances that
the United States was not recognizing PLO claims to an independent
state. Israel army radio called Shamir's talk with Pickering ``a
hard and unpleasant one.''
   Pickering said ties with Israel are ``stronger than ever,'' but
he said Israelis and Palestinians must make difficult concessions
for peace.
   Shamir, the head of Likud, made no comment Thursday, but Pazner
said: ``We regret this American decision, very much.'' He said
Israel would not reconsider its refusal to deal with the PLO, which
it calls a terrorist organization.
   Dozens of Jewish settlers from the territories began a hunger
strike, pitching tents in front of Shamir's office.
   ``The U.S. policy of recognizing the PLO is the seed of the next
war,'' said Ron Nachman, a settler leader. ``Israel cannot reach
agreement with the PLO. There is no common ground and the result
will be an explosion.''
   Peres, leader of the center-left Labor Party and Shamir's
political rival, said of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's renunciation
of terrorism:
   ``I surely see a change in their rhetoric; I hardly see a change
in their actions. This is the discrepancy that worries me.''
   He said Israel was ``facing a new situation'' and proposed an
alternative: that elections be held in the West Bank and Gaza to
choose Palestinian leaders for peace negotiations.
   Ezer Weizman, a Labor member of the Cabinet without portfolio,
said Arafat's recognition of Israel and renunciation of terrorism
made the PLO a satisfactory partner for talks.
   ``I think a new era has opened,'' he said.
</TEXT>
