<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fierce Winds, Snow Hit California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The high pressure ..., to delete erroneous
reference to 50,000 Mohawk Plant utility customers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce winds ripped across Northern California and ice pellets
and snow fell in the central coastal area of the state Thursday,
while up to 18 inches of snow fell in Colorado and Michigan's Upper
Peninsula.
   Northward winds in California were clocked at 102 mph early
Thursday atop Mt. Diablo about 40 miles east of San Francisco.
Hurricane force winds are 74 mph or greater. The winds caused at
least one death, overturned trucks and cut power to more than
440,000 electric customers.
   Winds gusted to 67 mph at Travis Air Force Base and to 54 mph on
the Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco.
   One to 2 inches of wet snow fell in the higher elevations near
Paso Robles, Calif. Ice pellets and snowshowers were reported over
the Inland Hills of Santa Barbara County.
   A snow advisory was in effect for the higher elevations of the
southern California deserts through Friday.
   Early Thursday, winds in northern Utah blew trailers off their
foundations at Utah State University in Logan. Winds gusted to 105
mph at Centerville, 84 mph at Logan and 74 mph at Hill Air Force
Base. The winds knocked out power to 50,000 electric customers.
   The high pressure system that produced strong winds over
California and Utah also brought wind gusts of up to 65 mph at the
Niagara Mohawk Power Plant in western New York and to 48 mph at
Syracuse N.Y.
   In Michigan's Upper Peninsula, up to 18 inches of snow fell.
   ``Walloped? Who's been walloped?'' said Kerry Noble, manager of
ABC True Value Hardware in Marquette. ``This is just a little
(storm).''
   In Colorado, six to 12 inches of snow was reported in the
Colorado Springs area with 2 feet snow drifts. Up to 18 inches were
reported in the eastern foothills, 13 inches in west Denver, 11 in
Boulder, 9 in Fountain, 6 in Pueblo, 3 in Trinidad and 2 in Lamar.
   Cold arctic air kept Thursday afternoon temperatures below zero
over portions of northern Minnesota. Wind chill temperatures of 20
to 40 below zero were common over the northern Plains and Upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at Thief River Falls, Minn., to 81 degrees at
Brownsville, Texas.
   The low in the nation Thursday morning was 23 degrees below zero
at Park Rapids, Minn.
   For Friday, the National Weather Service forecast light snow from
eastern North Dakota to portions of the Great Lakes region. Widely
scattered rainshowers will occur over northern and central Florida,
southern California and southwest Arizona. Snowshowers will develop
over northern Arizona, southern Utah and in the mountains of Nevada
and California.
   High temperatures will be in the teens from Minnesota to New
York, with single digits and teens over northern New England. Highs
will be in the 40s and 50s from South Carolina across the Gulf
Coastal states to much of Texas and New Mexico and in portions of
Arizona, California, Oregon and Washington.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s are expected in the Florida Peninsula,
southern Arizona and coastal California. For much of the rest of the
nation, highs will be in the 20s and 30s.
</TEXT>
