<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NIreland-Bias     12-15 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Bias,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Laws Would Ban Religious Discrimination In Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government proposed new laws Thursday to
prevent employers in Northern Ireland from discriminating on the
basis of religion, but said threats of disinvestment could only
produce greater misery.
   ``I have made absolutely clear ... that there is to be no
discrimination of any sort in Northern Ireland,'' said Northern
Ireland Secretary Tom King, Britain's top official in the province.
   The bill, whose passage is assured because of the governing
Conservatives' huge majority in Parliament, would force companies to
report regularly on how many Catholics and Protestants they employ.
It would order them if necessary to change their employment
practices and levy fines of up to $55,000 on employers who don't.
   The measures, due to take effect next summer, stopped short of
imposing hiring quotas for the 40 percent Catholic minority, but
they mark the toughest attempt to end job discrimination in the
British province.
   Despite longtime bans on overt religious discrimination in jobs,
Catholic unemployment runs at 17 percent, 2{ times the Protestant
rate.
   The new moves appear to have been spurred partly by threats of
disinvestment from the United States.
   Eight American states have endorsed fair employment principles
put forward in 1984 by the late Irish statesman Sean MacBride. He
called for ending investment in companies in Northern Ireland
accused of religious bias.
   The disinvestment lobby is headed by Irish-American legislators
and pressure groups. American investment accounts for nearly 14
percent of the jobs in Northern Ireland.
   ``There is absolutely no way in which this legislation is
designed to see Protestants being dismissed for Catholics to take
their place,'' King told reporters. ``This is about recruitment ...
seeing that there is equality of opportunity.''
   He said the only way to improve employment opportunities for
Catholics was to create more jobs, and he called the disinvestment
program in the United States ``a very negative campaign.''
   ``We're getting more jobs into Northern Ireland and that combined
with effective legislation is the real hope for Catholics of a
fairer situation,'' King said. ``There is no hope for Catholics in
any policy that leads to disinvestment in Northern Ireland, which
leads to greater misery for all.''
   More than 2,700 people have been killed since political and
sectarian violence broke out in Northern Ireland in 1969 after
several years of civil rights campaigning by Catholics.
   Under the new laws, all companies with more than 25 employees _
and later with 10 or more _ will have to submit reports at least
once every three years on the religious composition of the work
force to a new body, the Fair Employment Commission.
   Failure to submit a report or comply with the commission will be
a criminal offense, carrying a fine of up to $55,000.
   The laws would also ban ``indirect discrimination'' in hiring
practices, such as getting workers to find new workers or taking
recruits from a single school. Nearly all Catholic and Protestant
children are educated separately.
   Public and private companies with more than 250 employees also
will have to monitor their job applications as well as the
composition of their work force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
