<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilyPoisoning     12-15 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Poisoning,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Trial Asked in 1968 Arcadia Family Poisonings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man imprisoned 20 years ago in the
poisoning deaths of his seven children asked for a new trial
Thursday, telling the Florida Supreme Court he was framed.
   Attorneys for James Richardson said the prosecutors and the
sheriff involved in his conviction time should be charged with
perjury and perhaps attempted murder, because he once faced
execution in the electric chair.
   Richardson's case also is being reviewed by Gov. Bob Martinez,
who was considering a request to recommend clemency to free the
former orange picker from prison. Three Cabinet members would have
to concur.
   ``This petition is going to crumble the house of cards the
state's case was built on,'' Miami lawyer Ellis Rubin said shortly
before filing the petition.
   Rubin, and lawyer Mark Lane of New York, who wrote a book on the
Arcadia murders, said Richardson was framed partly to protect a
friend of then-Sheriff Frank Cline. The friend was related to Betsy
Reese, the Richardsons' baby sitter who Rubin and Lane say has
confessed to the killings.
   Reese fed the children on the day of Oct. 25, 1968, when James
and Annie Mae Richardson were working in the fields. The children,
ranging in age from 2 to 8, died within a day after eating food
laced with the deadly pesticide parathion.
   The lawyers said Richardson, convicted on one count of
first-degree murder, was an easy target because he was illiterate,
poor and black.
   ``We know what racism was in Florida in 1968 because of this
case. Let's find out what it is in 19 and 88. This case is going to
do it,'' said Rubin.
   They based their petition on three claims:
   _The knowing use of perjury from the sheriff regarding an
insurance policy Richardson supposedly purchased for the seven
children, and from two former cellmates of Richardson's who said he
had confessed to the crime. One has since recanted that statement.
   _Prosecutors suppressed evidence that would have shown Richardson
had not yet purchased the insurance on the children.
   _Newly discovered evidence; former Arcadia Police Chief Richard
Barnard says he believes Richardson was framed by the sheriff, and
affidavits from nursing assistants that Betsy Reese has told them
she fed the poison to the children.
   Cline did not return a telephone message left at his home.
   There was no answer Thursday night at the office of State
Attorney Frank Schaub, who won Richardson's conviction in 1968.
Schaub leaves office next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
