<DOCNO> AP881215-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GuerrillaAbducted     12-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guerrilla Abducted,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Abduct Militia Leader; Villagers Grab U.N. Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers and allied militiamen
infiltrated a U.N.-policed village in south Lebanon on Thursday and
abducted a Shiite Moslem guerrilla leader, police said.
   Armed residents in the village of Tibnin retaliated by kidnapping
three Irish soldiers with the U.N. peacekeepers for about an hour, a
police spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The Irish soldiers were released after the mainstream Shiite Amal
militia promised the villagers that the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon will do its best to locate the guerrilla leader, Jawad
Kasfi, and bring him back, the spokesman said.
   A source at the 5,800-strong UNIFIL said villagers from Tibnin
held three Irish soldiers aboard an armored personnel carrier for
more than an hour.
   ``The Amal movement interfered and the villagers released the
three Irish soldiers unharmed,'' the source said on condition of
anonymity.
   Tibnin, 13 miles north of the Israeli border, is within UNIFIL's
area of operations.
   The police source said two Israeli soldiers and three men from
the South Lebanon Army militia ``infiltrated into Tibnin in two
civilian cars early in the day and kidnapped Kasfi.''
   He said Kasfi was reputed to have ``engineered and lead guerrilla
attacks against the Israelis and the SLA in south Lebanon.''
   Israeli troops and South Lebanon Army militiamen control a
six-to-10-mile strip of south Lebanon which they refer to as their
``security zone.''
   The zone, which extends from the Mediterranean in the west to the
foothills of Mount Hermon in the east, serves as a buffer against
cross-border guerrilla raids into northern Israel.
   The nine-nation UNIFIL patrols a narrow region north of the
security zone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
