<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0628 12-15 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors Hear Sounds Blasted At Polygamist Clan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 3 grafs on women given misdemeanor citation for
unwittingly bringing weapon to trial; no pick up.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The piercing sounds blasted at a family's
farm during a 13-day police siege were demonstrated Thursday at the
trial of three polygamist clan members charged with a law officer's
death.
   Jurors showed little reaction as noises used in the psychological
assault ranging from an air-raid type siren to a sound resembling a
stuck car horn were played from two 100-watt speakers about 60 yards
away from the Summit County Courthouse.
   The demonstration came in the ninth day of the trial of clan
patriarch Addam Swapp, his brother Jonathan Swapp and brother-in-law
John Timothy Singer.
   All are charged with second-degree murder in the Jan. 28 death of
Corrections Lt. Fred House.
   House was shot and killed as he directed attack dogs toward the
Swapp brothers during an arrest attempt. Addam Swapp, who
precipitated the standoff when he bombed a Mormon chapel in nearby
Marion on Jan. 16, was seriously wounded during the same shootout.
   Judge Michael Murphy cautioned jurors that the demonstration was
only to illustrate methods used to rob clan members of sleep in
hopes of speeding their surrender, and that they were not exact
duplications.
   Defense attorneys have contended that loud, piercing electronic
noises, low-flying aircraft, flares and banks of brilliant lights
used by authorities in an effort to exhaust the 15 barricaded clan
members, including nine children, actually escalated tensions during
the siege.
   On Wednesday, Elliott Landau, a psychologist called by the
defense, testified that the FBI's use of the loudspeaker may have
caused anxiety, stress, irritability and reduced reasoning ability
among clan members during the standoff.
   Earlier testimony indicated the loudspeakers were used
irregularly during the final days of the standoff, and that they
were repeatedly shot out or torn down by clan members.
   Addam Swapp said the noises were a torture and they put pillows
on the children's heads in an attempt to block the sound. He said he
was compelled to shoot out or tear down the speakers to stop ``the
crazy noise from hell.''
   Also on Wednesday, Addam Swapp testified that neither he nor any
other member of his family deliberately fired at officers during the
firefight that ended the siege by 100 law officers.
   He said once the siege began, none of the family felt they could
trust anything the authorities said.
   Swapp said he never fired at anyone during the siege and felt of
killing, ``it's murder, it's wrong.''
   Asked who should atone for the slaying, he said, ``that was an
accident.''
   Prosecutors contend and defense attorneys concede the
wheelchair-bound Singer fired the fatal bullet, but Singer says he
was aiming at the dogs, not House.
   In a related development, Carla Foster, a friend of the Swapps,
was issued a misdemeanor citation charging her with illegally
carrying a concealed weapon after she unwittingly brought a gun to
the proceedings, officers said.
   Foster, 36, had handed her purse to a deputy stationed at a metal
detector and told him the gun was inside. She later explained to
officers that she had left her purse in her car during the morning
session and had retrieved it after lunch, forgetting that the weapon
was inside, said Detective Sgt. Robert Berry.
   Murphy barred Foster from the courtroom for the remainder of the
trial, and she was ordered to appear Tuesday in 3rd Circuit Court,
Berry said. The incident went virtually unnoticed in the courtroom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0214 </DOCNO>
