<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DiabetesBoy     12-15 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diabetes Boy,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Sentenced to 41 Months in Death of Diabetic Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fonmer deacon of a faith-healing sect was
sentenced to 41 months in prison Thursday for failing to seek
medical help for his dying, diabetic son.
   Bobby Norman, 43, who was convicted in October of first-degree
manslaughter in the death of his son, Aaron, was a deacon in a
nameless Christian fellowship that followed a literal translation of
the Bible, distrusted conventional medicine, and practiced strict
discipline of members.
   Aaron Norman, 10, died of complications related to juvenile
diabetes at his parent's Mead home Dec. 20, 1987, the day after he
was spanked by his father and church founder Doug Kleber during a
faith-healing session.
   ``In 15 years as a judge, nothing has bothered me more than this
trial, this sentencing,'' Spokane County Superior Court Judge John
Schultheis said before handing down the sentence to a grim-faced
Norman.
   In brief remarks prior to sentencing, Norman told Schultheis he
loved his son and asked for mercy so that he could remain with his
shattered family, especially an 8-year-old son who is in counseling.
   During an hour-long plea for leniency, defense attorney Roger
Peven argued that Norman was under the influence of Kleber and
former Spokane pastor Jeffrey Siegel.
   Drawing parallels to the followers of the Rev. Jim Jones who
committed mass suicide in Guyana, Peven argued that normally
intelligent people can be seduced by evil people who subvert God's
word to carry out their will.
   Schultheis told Norman that as a parent, ``I have to be the
person that intervenes between the child ... and outside
impediments. You had the absolute obligation to intervene, and you
didn't do it.''
   Deputy Spokane County prosecutor Clark Colwell had asked
Schultheis to find exceptional circumstances that would allow him to
sentence Norman to more than the 31-41 months called for by state
sentencing guidelines.
   Kleber, 34, of Champaign-Urbana, Ill., was sentenced Dec. 7 to
three years in prison after pleading guilty to second-degree
criminal mistreatment. He founded the sect, dubbed the ``No Name
Fellowship'' as a prayer group of Christian athletes at the
University of Illinois in the 1970s, where he played football.
   Siegel, 33, of Chapel Hill, N.C., also pleaded guilty to
second-degree criminal mistreatment and was sentenced to a two-year
term.
   Testimony during Norman's three-week trial indicated the gravely
ill boy was beaten the day before his death by his father and
Kleber, while Siegel and other church members watched. The spankings
were believed necessary to get the boy to confess to what they
called the sin of masturbation, which church elders believed was the
cause of his illness.
   Norman, a 24-year Burlington Northern Railroad employee,
testified that he believed Kleber's assurances that his son was
recovering, despite physical signs to the contrary.
   Norman and his wife, Judith, originally were charged with
homicide by abuse. The charge against the Norman was later reduced
to first-degree manslaughter and charges against Mrs. Norman were
dismissed.
   Charges of second-degree criminal mistreatment also are pending
against three other former sect leaders, whose trials are scheduled
for next year.
   The fellowship, which at its peak claimed about 300 adult members
in four states, disbanded in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
