<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Earth is ``under siege by the invasion
of human products that destroy its atmosphere, its water, its flora
and fauna,'' says a conference of 40 scientists and Christian
theologians.
   Citing damage to the ozone layer, degrading of land, pollution of
water below and above ground, toxic materials injected into the air,
deforestation intensifying droughts and floods, the conference says:
   ``God's earth faces a crisis... As the recognition of God's land
onwership gave way to the notion of human ownership, land became a
commodity ... Humans began treating the land as a resource rather
than a created partner.''
   The conference was jointly sponsored last month by the North
American Conference on Christianity and Ecology and the World
Alliance of Reformed Churches, embracing 161 Reformed and
Presbyterian denominations totaling about 70 million members.
</TEXT>
