<1ST_LINE>a a AM-PuebloCrew Adv23   12-15 1125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pueblo Crew, Adv23,1166</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Crewmen of Seized Ship Have Lost No Bitterness</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days before Christmas 20 years ago, the
captive crewmen of the spy ship USS Pueblo crossed the ``Bridge of
No Return'' to freedom, but they still haven't put their bitterness
behind them.
   ``I thought they would shoot me in the back,'' recalled crew
member Harry Iredale. ``I didn't believe it until I was on the other
side.''
   ``I felt like I had just come back from the dead,'' said Lloyd
Bucher, captain of the ship that had been seized on the high seas by
North Korea, the first such taking of a U.S. warship in a century
and a half.
   The crewmembers remain angry at the American military's failure
to protect the lightly armed vessel or to come to its aid.
   ``There were so many people at the Joint Chiefs of Staff level on
down who weren't paying attention to their damn job,'' said Bucher.
``They would have greatly preferred for the North Koreans to have
done us in completely.''
   Instead, one crewman was killed in the attack and the 82 others
were subjected to 11 months of brutal captivity.
   ``The U.S. at that time had enormous military forces in the
western Pacific within 5 minutes flying time of us,'' Bucher, now
61, said in a telephone interview from his home in Poway, Calif. ``I
would have thought something could be mustered to come to our aid.
But everybody just forgot we were there.''
   Iredale, 44, of Fairfax, was a civilian oceanographer employed by
the Navy and assigned to the Pueblo to provide a cover for the
ship's real mission of collecting electronic intelligence. He
believes the capture demonstrated an American naivete about the
world.
   Conducting espionage off the North Korean coast was not the same
as running similar missions off the Soviet Union, he said. ``The
North Koreans didn't play by the rules.''
   Throughout the attack, seizure and early days of captivity,
Iredale said, ``We expected someone to come over the horizon to
rescue us.''
   Robert J. Chicca, a Marine sergeant who worked as a Korean
linguist on the Pueblo, said he still finds it difficult to believe
there was no retaliation.
   ``I would lay the blame on every military commander who was in
helping range and didn't come,'' said Chicca, 44, in a telephone
interview from his home in Bonita, Calif.
   Retired Adm. John J. Hyland, commander in chief of the Pacific
Fleet at the time, said it is difficult to provide protection for a
spy ship.
   Writing in this fall's issue of Naval History magazine, Hyland
said, ``There isn't any way you can do anything for an
intellgience-gathering ship unless you want to accompany it with a
destroyer, which would defeat the purpose.''
   Bucher, who retired from the Navy in 1973 after 27{ years of
service, said the lack of preparedness that permitted the Pueblo
humiliation persists in the military today.
   Pointing to the failed mission to rescue American hostages in
Iran in 1980 and the terrorist bombing that killed more than 200
Marines in Beirut in 1983, he said, ``As the years have passed I
have learned of the incredible disarray our defenses are in.''
   The weather was clear and cold on Jan. 23, 1968, as the Pueblo
lolled about 15 miles off the North Korean coast _ three miles
outside the communist nation's territorial waters.
   Iredale was taking water-temperature measurements as four North
Korean torpedo boats and two subchasers, all heavily armed,
approached the 176-foot Pueblo around noon.
   ``They circled around and had their guns trained on us,'' Iredale
said.
   A subchaser raised a signal flag asking the Pueblo's nationality,
and Bucher ordered the hoisting of the American flag. When the
subchaser ordered the Pueblo to follow it, the American ship began
to move away.
   One of the boats suddenly opened fire on the Pueblo with its 57mm
cannon, slightly wounding Bucher and another crewman. A later salvo
killed Fireman Duane Hodges and wounded Chicca and several others.
   Bucher ordered the Pueblo stopped and stalled for time as crewmen
radioed for help and frantically destroyed classified documents.
   Shortly after 2 p.m. the Pueblo, which never fired a shot from
its .50-caliber machine guns, was boarded by about 10 North Korean
soldiers clad in olive green quilted jackets and carrying submachine
guns.
   The Pueblo became the first American warship captured since 1807
when a British ship forced the USS Chesapeake to surrender off the
Virginia capes.
   After the North Koreans failed to extract ``confessions'' from
the men during initial interrogations, the torture and beatings
began.
   ``They wanted us to say we were inside their territorial waters
and spying on them,'' Iredale said.
   ``You were helpless, and after a while, hopeless.''
   The worst part of the imprisonment was ``hell week,'' which came
late in the crew's captivity, Iredale said.
   ``They had me kneel down and took a hammer handle and started
pounding my head. They put a board on the back of my knees and
jumped up and down on it.
   ``After it stopped they came in and gave me a pail of water and a
brush to wash my blood off the floor and stucco walls,'' Iredale
said.
   Bucher said he was ``kicked into unconsciousness. That I endured
a few times.''
   Chicca's nose was broken several times. ``They didn't like
Marines,'' he said.
   Freedom finally came on Dec. 23 at the bridge separating North
Korea and South Korea _ but only after American officials signed an
apology that they immediately repudiated.
   A Navy court of inquiry recommended a court-martial for Bucher,
who violated the hallowed Navy code of ``don't give up the ship.''
That finding was reduced to a letter of reprimand by the commander
of the Pacific Fleet.
   The court of inquiry also recommended a reprimand for the admiral
responsible for ensuring the Pueblo's safety.
   Secretary of the Navy John B. Chafee overturned the panel's
recommendations on the day they were made public, saying the Pueblo
crew had suffered enough.
   ``If he (Bucher) hadn't surrendered they would have blown the
ship out of the water,'' Iredale said. ``It would be suicide.''
   Bucher said he was under orders to observe the North Koreans but
``not to incite them.''
   Still, he said in some ways he feels personally responsible.
``Whatever I was unable to do are the things I feel worst about,''
he said.
   ``If I had a way to destroy the ship, we would have abandoned it
and blown it up. I tried to get cans of TNT before we sailed, but
the Navy said they didn't have any.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Dec. 23</NOTE>
