<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:King Adv21   12-15 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: King, Adv21,0697</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Dec 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>B.B. Takes Lucille From the Blues to U2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, playing the blues was a sure way to
get them, says guitar great B.B. King.
   ``That has hit me pretty hard, that the blues were not popular
for a long time,'' said King, recalling the days in the 1960s and
'70s when he was more popular in Europe than at home. ``It was like
being black twice. But I kept working hard, kept practicing, kept
playing.''
   He and ``Lucille,'' his guitar, are still playing. After
overcoming prejudice both racial and musical, King is now revered as
a blues giant; he's just released his 52nd blues album, and he
almost steals the show from U2 in their concert movie, ``U2 Rattle
and Hum.''
   ``I was in Ireland, and (U2 lead singer) Bono came by,'' King
said recently about their collaboration. ``I'd always admired him
and the group, and we talked about songwriting. I told him to think
of me when he was writing, and he said, `OK, I'll do it.'''
   The result, ``When Love Comes to Town,'' features King swapping
vocals with Bono and playing his distinctive lead guitar over U2's
backbeat _ a merging of the Mississippi delta and the Emerald Isle
recorded at the renowned Sun Studios in Memphis, Tenn.
   King, 63, was born in Indianola, Miss., and took up the guitar at
an early age. He started out playing and singing gospel, but soon
began taking requests from churchgoers for more secular music.
Making the guitar a career, he recalled, was a financial decision
easily reached.
   ``I made $22.50 on a plantation driving a tractor all week.
Playing guitar on a Saturday night I made $25 _ understand, that's
for one evening,'' King said. ``That's when I decided.''
   King moved to Memphis after World War II, dubbing himself the
``Beale Street Blues Boy'' _ later shortened to B.B. In 1951, he
scored his first hit with ``3 O'Clock Blues'' and his career was off
and running.
   But during the British Invasion of the '60s and the disco craze
of the '70s, King and his music slipped into the background. Despite
the lack of acclaim, King never considered playing any other music.
   ``No, I didn't even think about it; I never felt that way,'' he
said. ``I felt bad, I felt ridiculed, looked down upon for doing
this kind of music. I wished it was different, but everything I play
is bluesy.''
   King said his instantly-recognizable guitar style was developed
more because of his ears than his hands: ``I can't hear lows, so I
would turn the treble up. That's how it started.''
   But it's evolving to this day, he said before a Manhattan
appearance at the Benson and Hedges Blues Festival to benefit the
homeless.
   ``It's always changing. I'm influenced by everything. There are
young people today who come up and say they idolize me _ I learn
from them. It's a round-robin.''
   Another thing that has the veteran musician smiling is the number
of current artists who are acknowledging the blues ``are the mother
of all music.'' King cited Robert Cray as a particular favorite.
Then he named another musician who loved the blues: the late John
Lennon.
   ``I remember once an interviewer asked John Lennon what he'd like
to being doing. And he said, `Playing guitar, playing the blues like
B.B. King,''' King said. ``He never knew what that meant to me. It
feels good to hear people talk like that.''
   Despite his advancing years, King keeps an active schedule; he
estimates spending 300 days a year on the road. And he has no
intention of hanging up ``Lucille'' any time in the near future.
   ``When the great creator says it's enough, that's when I'll
stop,'' said King. ``What else would I do? It's like Count Basie
told me one time: My friends are around the world. If I stopped
playing, how could I see them all?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Dec. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
