<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-TreatmentforSale Adv19-2Takes   12-15 1075</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treatment for Sale, Adv19-2 Takes,1110</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Maverick Researcher's Approach to Developing Cancer Drugs Is
Faltering</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maverick researcher's efforts to speed
tests on unproven cancer therapies by selling them to any patients
willing to pay is faltering.
   Dr. Robert K. Oldham, founder of Biotherapeutics Inc., has so far
been unable to show that the treatments, which cost as much as
$24,000, can prolong lives or reduce the severity of symptoms.
   Although patients stoutly defend their right to seek his
experimental help, Oldham is failing to attract enough patients to
make a profit. What is more, he has been attacked by doctors and
scientists who say it's unethical, and possibly dangerous, to sell
treatments not yet shown to work.
   Dr. Arnold Relman, editor of the New England Journal of Medicine,
says patients who go to Oldham ``are people desperate with fear.
They're dying of cancer. And they're encouraged to believe there
might be some hope. It's cruel deception. It's commercial
exploitation of a tragedy. I think it's totally immoral.''
   Biotherapeutics was the first profit-making enterprise to take
advantage of government reluctance to allow sales of most
experimental drugs until they've been throroughly tested for safety
and effectiveness.
   Oldham's daring decision to sell such unproven treatments to the
public, and risk federal closure, has put Biotherapeutics in the
midst of a debate over what the government might do to speed
delivery of new drugs to dying patients.
   The outcome is vitally important to anyone who will be touched by
cancer, AIDS, heart disease or any other incurable ailment.
   Oldham is selling what are called immune therapies. They have
been widely touted as an important fourth weapon against cancer,
augmenting the triple arsenal of chemotherapy, radiation and surgery
that cure only about half of the almost 1 million Americans
diagnosed with cancer each year.
   Immune therapies, sometimes called biological therapies, are
intended to provoke the body's immune system to destroy invading
cancer cells.
   The hope _ and so far it remains little more than a hope _ is
that the therapies may attack tumors impervious to conventional
therapies.
   Another potential advantage is that the immune system may target
cancer cells more accurately than conventional treatments, thus
producing fewer of the harmful side effects often associated with
chemotherapy and radiation.
   Dr. Steven A. Rosenberg of the National Cancer Institute, who has
done much of the pioneering work in biological therapy, calls this
``the dawn of a new approach to treating cancer.''
   ``I've now had almost 20 patients with widespread, metastatic
cancer that's disappeared,'' Rosenberg said in an interview.
   Rosenberg is, however, a sharp critic of Oldham. He asserts that
biological therapy is not ready for widespread use. ``The worst
thing we can do is raise false expectations,'' he said.
   Biotherapeutics Inc. is located in a squat, modern, red-brick
building just outside Franklin, an antebellum town 18 miles south of
Nashville with a picturesque square frequently sought out by
moviemakers.
   The building's Y-shaped entrance resembles an antibody molecule,
a reminder of the company's use of cancer antibodies in some
treatments.
   Oldham, the company's dominant presence, is a well-known
researcher with more than 300 papers to his credit. Among his
accomplishments, he lists the discovery of certain white blood cells
called natural killer cells, which help defend the body against
disease.
   He began his research career at the National Cancer Institute. He
left in 1975 to establish the cancer program at Vanderbilt
University but returned to the cancer institute in 1980 to initiate
research on biological therapy for cancer.
   He left the institute again in 1984, this time to set up
Biotherapeutics, which focuses almost exclusively on the use of
biological anti-cancer agents.
   Oldham is a tough, combative man. He bristles at criticism of
Biotherapeutics and seeks opportunities to defend himself and his
enterprise.
   If cancer patients want the treatments he offers _ whether those
treatments work or not _ then the patients ought to get them, Oldham
says. ``Where does society come off saying you can't have it?'' he
argued.
   For more than three years, Oldham has sidestepped federal
regulations on the sale of experimental treatments by claiming to be
in the business of patient-funded research.
   Oldham says he is not selling treatment. He says he's recruiting
patients to serve as subjects in cancer research _ and to pay for
the privilege.
   He says what he is doing is no different from what the National
Cancer Institute is doing, except for the source of the funding. The
cancer institute gets its money from Congress; Biotherapeutics gets
its money from patients.
   But is Oldham selling research? Interviews with patients, Oldham
and other company officials suggest that people are coming to
Biotherapeutics not to contribute to a research effort, but to try
to save their lives.
   Here is the wording on a poster outside his office: ``If you had
cancer, and traditional treatments weren't effective, what would you
do? Give up? Or fight, pursuing every option? ... When standard
therapies fail, we offer patients a scientifically valid option.''
   Ask Oldham's patients why they have come to him, and it's clear
they're seeking treatment _ not a chance to be guinea pigs.
   James E. Murphy was recently treated by Oldham for colon cancer.
His doctor in Washington, D.C., had told him he could do nothing
more for him. Why had Murphy come to Oldham?
   ``You don't have any alternative if you want to fight it,'' he
said in an interview in his hospital room. ``Eventually I will die,
but at least I'll give it a shot. ... I think Biotherapeutics
charging (for experimental treatments) is better than not giving
people a shot at it.''
   Murphy, 60, said he hoped his case would help Oldham learn
something that might help others, but that wasn't why he was there.
   A salesman for a computer systems development company, Murphy
said he and his wife paid for his treatment with money from their
retirement account.
   Murphy knows the Biotherapeutics treatment is a long shot. Oldham
explained that well. And he believes that, ideally, experimental
treatments shouldn't be commercialized, as Oldham's are.
   ``But the government isn't doing anything,'' Murphy said. ``You
call the National Institutes of Health and ask about colon cancer
and you get a tape.'' You call Oldham, and if you are have the
strength left and the money, you get treated.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1406EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-TreatmentforSale Adv19-1stAdd   12-15 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treatment for Sale, Adv19-1st Add,0803</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>FRANKLIN: get treated.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The two principal therapies Oldham is using are monoclonal
antibodies and adoptive immunotherapy.
   Monoclonal antibodies are protective proteins produced in mice
that have been injected with human cancer cells. Such antibodies
could, theoretically, attack and destroy tumors or could be used to
carry cancer-killing drugs directly to tumors.
   Oldham is selling a monoclonal antibody treatment for $24,000.
Does it work? ``It's too soon to tell,'' he said.
   Adoptive immunotherapy involves taking immune cells from cancer
patients, stimulating the cells with a drug called interleukin-2,
and re-injecting them in the hope the cells will attack the
patients' tumors. The cells are called lymphokine-activated killer
cells, or LAKs.
   This treatment has been shown to be of some help in fighting
melanoma and kidney cancer. Ten percent of such patients show a
dramatic reduction in tumor size, but whether the treatments will
improve or extend their lives is not yet known.
   ``It's probably helping some people,'' said Dr. Bruce Chabner,
director of the cancer treatment program at the National Cancer
Institute. Kidney and other urinary cancers will strike 22,500
Americans this year and melanoma will strike 27,300, says the
American Cancer Society.
   Oldham is selling adoptive immunotherapy for 50 percent off the
regular price of $19,400. Does it work? ``It's too early to tell,''
he said.
   Many of Oldham's critics have questioned why the FDA hasn't acted
to stop Biotherapeutics. Charging for experimental treatments is
usually prohibited by the FDA, according to Dr. Robert Temple, a
director in the FDA's drug evaluation office.
   ``We in general don't think people should be charged for
investigational drugs,'' he said. ``They haven't been shown to work
yet; it's not fair.''
   The FDA says it hasn't made a decision yet on Biotherapeutics.
Many doctors outside the FDA say the agency is knotted in sharp
internal debate.
   Peter Barton Hutt, formerly the FDA's chief counsel and now a
Washington lawyer, put the FDA's fundamental dilemma this way: ``If
someone is desperately ill and has no other hope, should the
government tell them what they can take? Balanced against that, if
the patient is desperately ill and has no hope, should there be
protection against them being defrauded?''
   An additional complication is that Biotherapeutics' company
structure makes it difficult for the FDA to act.
   Biotherapeutics does not send its drugs across state lines. It
has hospital affiliates scattered across the country, but each
hospital has a nearby laboratory that produces drugs according to
the Biotherapeutics recipe.
   Dr. Bruce Burlington, director of the FDA's division of
biological investigational new drugs, said that limits the agency's
ability to act. ``With intrastate activities, there is debate over
the extent of our jurisdiction,'' he said.
   While the FDA ponders its moves, the ethical debate over Oldham's
activities continues.
   Dr. Michael Grodin, a pediatrician and director of the medical
ethics program at Boston University, says Oldham clearly has
conflicting interests.
   As a doctor, he should be helping patients. As a researcher, he
should be trying to advance general knowledge, not to save dying
patients. And as a businessman, he should be trying to keep his
company afloat.
   ``It seems to me that the patient can't sort that out, even if
the researcher can,'' said Grodin.
   The immediate concern of Biotherapeutics is not, however, in
resolving these ethical tangles but in curing the company's
financial ills.
   In the most recent fiscal year, Biotherapeutics lost almost $10
million of the $40 million stake it raised to go into business. It
treated 400 patients, and, said Louis P. Berneman, the company's
president, ``the expectations were that that would have been
higher.'' He wouldn't say exactly what the company had hoped for.
   If management can't turn its troubled finances around, the
company won't survive beyond 1990, said Joseph Clark, its chief
financial officer. Clark added, however, that he had little doubt
that the company would make it.
   It has already taken some drastic steps. The price of its most
expensive product _ the monoclonal antibody treatment _ has been cut
from $35,000 to $24,000. Adoptive immunotherapy is on sale for
$9,700.
   The company hopes to persuade patients' insurance companies to
come up with the rest, although insurance companies as a rule do not
reimburse patients for experimental treatments.
   Biotherapeutics hopes the FDA will approve interleukin-2 next
year for use against kidney cancer and melanoma. Berneman thinks
insurance companies will then reimburse the costs of adoptive
immunotherapy.
   Oldham is determined to press on against whatever odds. ``Some of
our critics would legislate and regulate against us being
available,'' he said. ``And that is wrong.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Dec. 19</NOTE>
