<1ST_LINE>s w BC-CastroAfter30Years Adv25-1stAdd   12-15 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Castro After 30 Years, Adv25-1st Add,0396</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>HAVANA: 50 percent.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   For millions of Cubans, Castro remains an inspirational figure.
His oratorical skills are undiminished. He impresses visitors with
the breadth of his interests, ranging from medicine to nuclear
power. Little occurs in Cuba which escapes his restless gaze. Seldom
has a leader of so small a country had an international impact as
great as his.
   He can claim partial credit for the agreement under which South
Africa will grant Namibia, Africa's last colony, independence and
black majority rule. That was Castro's price for agreeing to
withdraw Cuba's forces from Angola.
   Above all, he sees himself as the broker for the dispossessed. He
constantly expresses outrage about the injustice of a world in which
some countries enjoy boundless abundance while others starve _
120,000 children every three days, a Hiroshima and a Nagasaki every
72 hours, he claims.
   Castro is proud that the infant mortality rate in Cuba is
comparable to that in some of the most developed countries. One
reason Cuba has had difficulty developing economically is that so
much of the country's resources go toward meeting basic human needs
_ housing, schools and hospitals.
   The vast majority of Cuba's children have the opportunity to
develop their minds and bodies through Cuba's far-reaching
educational and sports programs.
   On a per capita basis, Cuba quite possibly produces more good
boxers, runners, swimmers and baseball players than any other
country.
   While more than a million Cubans have fled the island since 1959,
the revolution has rescued countless others, mostly peasants and
workers, from the social and economic oblivion they endured under
the previous system.
   Block-by-block ``defense committees'' are used to monitor the
politically suspect but they also have helped make Cuba's streets as
safe as any in the hemisphere. Castro also boasts that Cuba is drug
free.
   Castro has been at the helm in Cuba for well over half his adult
life and, at 62, he shows no sign of slowing down. If he does
falter, brother Raul, 57, has been tapped as the successor.
   But Fidel, as he is known to his countrymen, may well be around
for years to come. He has outlasted six American presidents. Next
month, Ronald Reagan will become the seventh.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
