<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv24-25-1stLd-Writethru   12-15 1075</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv24-25-1st Ld-Writethru, b0503,1099</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mazda Builds U.S. Designed Mini-van</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 15th paragraph to CORRECT spelling to two-passenger.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   About the time Chrysler was getting ready to introduce its
minivans for the 1984 model year, Mazda employees in California had
their own concept for a minivan on the drawing boards.
   The result, the 1989 Mazda MPV, debuted in November and marks a
milestone in the Japanese automaker's history. The MPV _ an
aerodynamic-shaped and smartly dressed package _ is the first Mazda
vehicle born of an initial design that originated in the United
States. In fact, the MPV (for multipurpose vehicle) is not sold
today in Japan, Mazda's home country.
   The vehicle, designed with American buyers in mind, is built in
Japan but sold only in the United States and Canada. Sales of about
40,000 are forecast through October 1989, including about 4,000
four-wheel-drive models due out beginning in March, said spokesman
Fred Aikins. For the following 12 months, steady sales of another
40,000 are expected, he added.
   Early results were heartening, with Mazda reporting more than 900
sold in the first three weeks the vehicles were out.
   ``We feel the (minivan) market is continuing to expand,'' Aikins
said. ``Our sales need to come from the additional buyers into the
market and from the domestics.''
   Besides Chrysler, Ford and General Motors also sell small vans,
though Chrysler outpaces all the competition in sales. The No. 3
U.S. automaker has sold more than 1 million of its Dodge Caravan and
Plymouth Voyager vans since the 1984 model year.
   Major Japanese automakers such as Toyota and Nissan also sell
minivans here, but Aikins said the Mazda MPV is different because it
is not as box-like as the competitors. In price, however, the MPV is
in the midst of all the others.
   Aikins said the base price for a two-passenger cargo van is
$10,989, with the lowest-priced five-passenger MPV wagon at $12,909.
The base price for a seven-passenger MPV with the standard
four-cylinder engine is $13,759.
   The test vehicle had a V6 engine and topped out at just over
$19,000. Those price ranges are comparable to the competition.
   The MPV has a side door that opens outward, like a regular car
door, rather than a sliding side door that is standard on other
vans. The MPV's side door, however, opens to a maximum 90 degrees _
greater than that on a car door.
   The design allows a slightly wider door opening on the vehicle
than on other small vans, Aikins noted. The swing-out door is
lighter and easier for children to manage than some sliding doors.
The MPV side door also features a bar that's easy to grab and use
when manuevering around in the back.
   In addition, swing-out doors have greater durability and are less
prone to rattles during driving, Aikins said.
   Another feature on the test MPV _ a seven-passenger model _ was a
three-passenger rear bench seat with a seatback that folded down so
the folded seat could be pushed upward and locked in place behind
the middle bench seat. It's an unusual-looking arrangement but
provides cargo space in back.
   On other vans, the rear seat can be unlocked from the floor and
removed, but the MPV rear seat can't be removed unless hand tools
are used first to unfasten it from the floor. That's a bit awkward
and time-consuming for someone who wants to get large, long items in
the van.
   But Aikins countered that buyers may not have to remove the MPV
rear seat seat at all. Mazda designed the rear seat bench and the
two-passenger middle seat with seatbacks that fold down backwards
for a somewhat uneven, but mostly flat, bed. Aikins suggested buyers
just load their long items on that bed.
   But I don't know that owners want long, dirty items _ such as
wood _ on their upholstery. Wouldn't owners rather put the items on
the floor as permitted in other vans? (The MPV's middle seat is
removable, however, with a flip of a couple latches, if you have
cargo that is not very long.)
   The MPV, like all vans, offered good visibility, because of its
higher riding profile. Still, it handled like a car, except for some
body sway around corners.
   The van is rear-drive, as opposed to the front-drive Chrysler
products, permitting towing capabilities of up to 4,300 pounds with
the optional MPV towing package. Despite the rear-drive
configuration, however, the MPV has a flat floor, save for the
slightly raised area under the rear bench seat where suspension coil
springs are located.
   Probably the most enjoyable part of the MPV was the optional
3-liter V6 engine which performed flawlessly. Teamed with a
four-speed automatic overdrive transmission, the engine was smooth
and peppy. It's the same powerplant that's in the Mazda 929.
   The standard engine for the MPV is a 2.6-liter four-cylinder
that's newly developed for the van, Aikins said.
   Another highlight of the MPV was the nicely appointed interior.
Upholstery is placed on the sides of the doors, providing soft
armrests, and carpeting is below on the sides of the doors, giving
the impression of a nicely integrated interior. There was even a
nifty pull-down two-cup holder on the side of the front passenger
seat.
   About the only complaint was that the dashboard featured a tiny
mapbox and a too-small glovebox. The van's interior was spacious,
and legroom was admirable in all three seating areas _ front, middle
and rear.
   It was relatively easy to move around inside, though obviously,
you must hunch over a bit.
   The sloping front dashboard design gave an airy feel. Fit and
finish was superb. The test vehicle had the optional, separate air
conditioner for rear-seat passengers _ another nice touch.
   Mazda says its target buyers are men, but company officials
expect women to be the primary drivers. That's explained by the fact
that 73 percent of the potential buyers are male, with 88 percent
married. The median age is 39, 60 percent are college graduates.
   The MPV is new, there are no trouble index reports from Consumer
Reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 24-25</NOTE>
