<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Dawber, Adv23-25,0742</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 23-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pam Dawber Plays Wife of Stricken Football Coach</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: RETRANSMISSION to correct cycle designator to BC.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of a football coach stricken in the
prime of life by Lou Gehrig's disease isn't exactly light-hearted
viewing, but Pam Dawber, who plays the coach's wife, found the movie
``happy.''
   ``It's really about the human spirit at its very best,'' she
said. ``I think he inspires so many people by overcoming his own
incredible trauma. It's a hopeful, happy movie.''
   It was soon after Dawber's CBS sitcom ``My Sister Sam'' was
finally dropped for good after bouncing around the schedule for two
seasons that she was offered the role as Lucy Wedemeyer in the
real-life movie ``Quiet Victory,'' which CBS will air Monday, the
day after Christmas.
   Mrs. Wedemeyer helps her husband, Charlie Wedemeyer (Michael
Nouri), continue his coaching career despite the disease that leaves
him unable to speak or move.
   Dawber had held off new projects until she got final word on ``My
Sister Sam,'' so the movie offer came as she was ready for something
new. The series was on-again, off-again on CBS until April.
   ``We all thought we were going back to work on the USA Network,''
she said. ``Tribune Entertainment was nearly ready to make 44 new
shows. Then it fell through. Too bad. It was a good show. But it was
the victim of network politics.
   ``They wanted our Monday night time slot for a new show, `Frank's
Place.' So they ended up killing two shows. `Frank's Place' never
should have been on at 8 o'clock. It was a more sophisticated show.''
   ``My Sister Sam'' was moved to Saturday night its second year,
but was soon taken off the air. It returned briefly in April as part
of CBS' ill-fated attempt to program sitcoms on Tuesday.
   April wasn't all bad for Dawber. She and husband Mark Harmon had
their son, Sean.
   For ``Quiet Victory,'' she packed up her new baby and spent
several weeks filming on Folly Beach, on one of the sea islands off
South Carolina. The Wedemeyers live in Los Gatos, which is south of
San Francisco, but it was too expensive to film there.
   ``So, we went to South Carolina, which has palm trees, old houses
and beaches,'' she said.
   Wedemeyer was 30 when he learned he had amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, called Lou Gehrig's disease after the famous New York
Yankee first baseman who was also stricken. A former star
quarterback at Michigan State, Wedemeyer was coaching the Los Gatos
Wildcats and teaching mathematics. He was married to his high school
sweetheart, Lucy, a former cheerleader.
   He's a native of Hawaii, where he was known as ``Kalekauwila,''
God of Lightning. His brother is Herman Wedemeyer, another football
star, who played Detective Duke Lukela for eight years on ``Hawaii
Five-0.''
   ``Charlie is completely immobile,'' said Dawber. ``He can move
his lips. He has a portable breathing apparatus and a feeding tube
and sometimes gets around in a golf cart. Lucy reads his lips and
relays his coaching commands to the team. ...
   ``He's a regal, charismatic man. Lucy's kept him alive through
her attitude. They both have a wonderful sense of humor. She's a
terribly selfless woman. Lucy in a way is the cheerleader for Los
Gatos. The community has done so much for them and with them.''
   The movie was directed by Roy Campanella II, whose father played
for the Brooklyn Dodgers until an automobile accident left him an
invalid.
   Now that the movie is completed, Dawber, who gained fame as Robin
Williams' foil on ``Mork and Mindy,'' is ``shopping around'' for a
new comedy series.
   A sitcom offers ``the most reasonble schedule,'' she said. ``I
don't want my son dragged around while I do more movies. I want the
industry to know that I'm available.''
   Dawber, who has sung in many musicals, including ``Pirates of
Penzance'' on Broadway, planned to audition for the role of
Christine in the Los Angeles production of ``Phantom of the Opera.''
She said she would have to audition without benefit of having seen
the play, since she was unable to get tickets to the show in New
York.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 23-25</NOTE>
