<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Years, in Its Own Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a year of election triumph and defeat in America, and of
glimmerings of peace around the world. The news stories of 1988 here
are told in the words of those who made the news:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We totally and absolutely renounce all forms of terrorism.''
   _ PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, Dec. 14, in Geneva, Switzerland.
   ``I have authorized the State Department to enter into a
substantive dialogue with PLO representatives.''
   _ President Reagan, in a statement issued just hours after Arafat
spoke.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I never thought I would see the day the Soviets were involved
with us here.''
   _ Joe Behne, test director from Lawrence Livermore Laboratories,
as U.S. and Soviet scientists prepared joint verification Aug. 15 of
a nuclear test blast in Nevada.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``It is now quite clear that building up military power makes no
country omnipotent. What's more, one-sided reliance on military
power ultimately weakens other components of national security.''
   _ Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announcing Soviet troop
reductions during his speech to the United Nations on Dec. 7.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The suspect aircraft was outside the prescribed commercial air
corridor. More importantly, the aircraft headed directly for
Vincennes on a constant bearing at high speed. ... We do have
indications that the people on the ship were led to believe ... that
the aircraft was ... decreasing in altitude as it neared the ship.
... Given the threatening flight profile and the decreasing range,
the aircraft was declared hostile.''
   _ Adm. William Crowe, chairman of Joint Chiefs of Staff, on July
3, after the USS Vincennes shot down Iranian airliner, killing 290
people.
   ``IR 655 ... was in the assigned airway.... At no time did IR 655
actually descend in altitude prior to engagement.''
   _ Final investigative Pentagon report on the shootdown, released
Aug. 19.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I tell him every morning that worrying won't make any
difference anyway.''
   _ Carla Kodat, on the advice she gives her husband, Pete, a
farmer in Morris, Ill., whose crops withered in the worst U.S.
drought in a half-century.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``It was a case of fry and die or jump and try.''
   _ Roy Carey, 45, who leaped to safety from an explosion July 8
that ripped apart an oil rig 120 miles off Scotland, killing 167.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Drugs are everywhere _ in the workplace, movie industry, sports
fields and college campuses.''
   _ Nancy Reagan's spokeswoman Elaine Crispen, after disclosure
July 1 that two White House secretaries had resigned and three
Secret Service officers were suspended during a drug probe.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Bobby Knight told me this: `There is nothing that a good
defense cannot beat a better offense.' In other words, a good
offense wins.''
   ``We all lived in this century - I didn't live in this century
-in this century's history. We did not have - as a matter of fact,
we fought - Hitlerism.''
   ``First, I'd say a prayer for myself and for the country that I'm
about to lead.''
   _ Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, on the campaign trail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine. Senator, you're no Jack
Kennedy.''
   _ Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen in Oct. 5
debate, after Quayle likened his own experience to the late
president's.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``(George) Bush has real vulnerabilities. We Democrats, if we
don't shoot ourselves in the foot, can win.''
   _ Susan Estrich, campaign manager for Michael Dukakis, on May 27.
   ``The people have spoken.''
   George Bush, celebrating his presidential election victory Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``What I think it does is spell the end of the user-friendly
era.''
   _ Richard tenEyck, telecommunications director of the Boston
Computer Society, following the sabotage of 6,000 computers
nationwide in November by a computer virus.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I was trying to help end the killing. But there were times I
was thoughtless and careless about it and I'm ... very sorry that I
hurt them.''
   _ Actress Jane Fonda, apologizing June 17 for her visit to Hanoi
during the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I am a serious, scientific astrologer and I am really not one
of these clowns, and I really don't like this circus atmosphere.''
   _ Astrologer Joan Quigley May 8, who advised first lady Nancy
Reagan, as reported by former White House chief of staff Donald T.
Regan in his newly released book.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Life is just a game. But I think somebody already said that.''
   _ Marcel Souza, Brazilian Olympic basketball team.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
