<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-15 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Shrinks, Factory Use Up, But Markets Not Pleased</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit dipped slightly in October and the
nation's factories ran at their highest rate in nine years in
November, the government says.
   Stocks and bonds fell Wednesday in reaction to the reports.
Investors feared they hinted at higher inflation in the months ahead
and possible moves by the nation's central bank to nudge up interest
rates.
   The merchandise trade deficit for October fell 3.1 percent to
$10.3 billion, the Commerce Department said. But investors decided
the improvement would not continue unless the dollar fell further to
make U.S. goods more competitive in world markets. That could
depress stocks and bonds.
   In the day's other big economic report, the Federal Reserve said
U.S. industry in November was using more of its capacity than at any
time in nine years.
   The operating rate at factories, mines and utilities was 84.2
percent last month, up from 84.0 percent in October and the highest
rate since November 1979. That raised speculation that factories
were running too close to full tilt, possibly leading to shortages
that would boost inflation.
   ``We're starting to approach levels of capacity utilization in
some industries that will mean higher prices. If growth continues at
this rate, we'll soon find most industries passing on higher prices
and we'll see monthly increases in the inflation numbers,'' said
David Berson, an economist with the Federal National Mortgage
Association.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped
9.24 points to 2,134.25 on Wednesday as declining issues outnumbered
advances by about 6 to 5 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks.
   In the bond market, the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond
lost } point, or about $7.50 for every $1,000 in face value. Its
yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator
of interest rate trends, climbed to 9.04 percent from 8.97 percent
late Tuesday.
   The dollar retreated against major currencies Wednesday, hurt by
what money dealers called rumors of a hike in West German interest
rates and a negative market reaction to the monthly U.S. trade
report.
   ``The figures came out in line with expectations, and since
there's overriding bearish sentiment to the dollar, people just
resumed selling it,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, a trader at the New York
commodities futures firm Refco Inc.
   In other economic news Wednesday:
   _The Commerce Department said business inventories in October
climbed at the slowest rate in five months, while sales surged a
strong 1.2 percent. The report suggested robust economic growth.
   _The Federal Reserve said its industrial production index in
November increased by 0.5 percent for the second month in a row.
   _Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks fell 11 percent in
early December compared with a burst of incentive-driven sales in
the same period a year earlier, domestic automakers reported.
   David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a
government securities trader in New York, said improvement in the
trade deficit will slow in the months ahead. He said capacity
strains will make it difficult to manufacture more exports, and
strong domestic demand will suck in more imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
