<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-15 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anticipation of colder weather in the Northeast
has pushed wholesale home heating oil prices sharply higher.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
heating oil rose 1.86 cents Wednesday to settle at 51.13 cents a
gallon, after falling 0.93 cent on profit-taking Tuesday. Other
contract months were up more than a penny.
   Prices were higher Monday and Friday on the arrival of
sub-freezing temperatures in the Northeast. The weather remained
cold on Wednesday, and parts of the region were hit with snow.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior energy analyst with E.D.&F. Man
International Futures Inc, said Wednesday's ``heating oil market ...
was supported by anticipation of colder weather in the Northeast.''
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Wednesday, January unleaded gasoline, which fell 0.90 cent on
Tuesday, rose 0.42 cent to settle at 43.72 cents a gallon.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $16.37 a barrel, up 37 cents
from Tuesday, when it fell 6 cents.
   Lebow said the markets also got a boost from reports that
non-OPEC oil producers Colombia and Norway would be willing to cut
production if the cartel sticks to an output-slashing pact ratified
last month.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
agreed to keep daily crude production at 18.5 million barrels to
help prop up sagging worldwide oil prices.
   ``Overall, the traders' sentiment seems to be changing. They're
more optimistic OPEC is going to cut production, and there's no sign
to lead to the contrary,'' said Lebow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
