<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   12-15 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fall in Early December Sales Not Seen as Worry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11 percent drop in sales of U.S.-made cars and
light trucks in early December isn't seen as worrisome in an
industry flirting with the second-best calendar year in history.
   Companies making cars and light trucks in the United States on
Wednesday reported they sold an average of 29,610 vehicles during
the nine selling days in the Dec. 1-10 period this year. That
compared with an average of 33,251 vehicles sold during the same
time last year, when there also were nine selling days.
   The automakers reported that car sales dropped 10.5 percent and
light truck sales were down 11.7 percent in early December of this
year compared with last year.
   But no one was predicting that the numbers pointed to an industry
in a slump. Incentives began to work their way back into car deals
during early December last year after a brief hiatus as the 1988
model year started.
   ``They (automakers) started putting on some heavy-duty
incentives'' in early December last year, said analyst Kathleen
Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. ``You've got a
tough time to compare it with.''
   Mary Ann Sudol of Fitch Investors agreed.
   ``That's hard to read,'' she said. ``It's not surprising that
they're down a little bit, given that December is bad for auto sales
anyway.
   ``In any (recent) 10-day period, you've had so much noise in the
period that it's hard to make a comparison. That noise is
incentives.''
   As the year draws to a close, the companies are looking forward
to what could be the second-best sales year in history, behind the
16.3 million vehicles sold in 1986.
   For the year, car and light truck sales in the United States have
risen 6.9 percent in 1988 over 1987, going to a daily rate of 37,949
this year compared with 35,499 last year.
   Among the Big Three U.S. automakers, General Motors Corp. showed
the largest early-December decline in car sales, falling 12.9
percent to a daily rate of 8,906 cars in 1988 from 10,226 last year.
GM's car sales were up 0.9 percent in 1988 over 1987 to a daily rate
of 11,776 this year, compared with 11,668 last year.
   Ford Motor Co.'s sales in early December fell 11.6 percent to a
daily rate of 5,582 this year, compared with 6,316 in the same
period last year. But for the year, Ford's car sales have climbed
7.7 percent to an average daily rate of 7,121 in 1988 compared with
6,612 in 1987.
   Chrysler Corp. said it sold cars at a daily rate of 2,673 in
early December this year compared with 2,979 during the same period
last year, a 10.3 percent decline. So far this year, Chrysler has
sold 10.3 percent more cars, with a daily sales rate of 3,451 in
1988 compared with 3,130 last year.
</TEXT>
