<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HCAAssets     12-15 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-HCA Assets,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HCA Will Sell Some Assets To Fund Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A management-led group buying out
Hospital Corp. of America plans to sell some assets of the nation's
largest hospital management company to help finance the $3.6 billion
acquisition.
   ``In order to meet its debt obligations, which include the
repayment of a $1.3 billion asset sale bridge loan within two years
of the merger, HCA will be required to sell certain of its assets
and businesses,'' company officials said Wednesday in a statement.
   ``HCA is currently reviewing each of its affiliated businesses
for possible disposition. However, no decision has been made with
respect to which assets or businesses will be sold and no such
decisions are currently anticipated to be made prior to the
merger,'' the statement said.
   A management group led by HCA Chairman Thomas F. Frist Jr. has
obtained commitments for more than $4 billion in debt and $300
million in equity to finance the buyout.
   The management group, TF Investments Inc., submitted the only
buyout proposal by a Nov. 18 deadline set by HCA's board of
directors. The company's board approved the buyout Nov. 22.
   ``They're still reviewing assets and businesses, and they're not
going to make any decision until the merger is completed,'' HCA
spokesman David McFadden said.
   ``We're looking to get the proxy cleared by the (Securities and
Exchange Commission) in mid-January. We're still planning to hold
the shareholder meeting in February, what time we really don't
know.''
   McFadden said HCA officials expect shareholders to approve the
buyout.
   HCA has filed preliminary proxy materials relating to the sale
with the SEC.
   Co-arrangers for the bank financing are Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.
of New York and Chase Manhattan Bank.
   Additional loan commitments have been obtained from Continental
Illinois National Bank and Trust Co. of Chicago, General Electric
Capital Corp., Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Toronto-Dominion Bank
and Deutsche Bank of West Germany.
   HCA officials said $2.362 billion of the $4.012 billion in bank
financing will be in an 8-year loan. About $1.3 billion will come
from the bridge facility that will mature two years after the sale
is completed.
   About $280 million is expected to come from an anticipated $350
million revolving credit facility, officials said.
   Equity commitments have been obtained from Frist, HCA management
and Texas-based investor Richard Rainwater for $125 million, the HCA
stock bonus retirement plan for $75 million and $100 million from
``affiliates of certain of the lenders,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
