<DOCNO> AP881215-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 0747EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-15 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved slightly higher in thin European
trading late this morning as the market waited for a widely expected
increase in a key West German interest rate in the wake of a round
of interest rate increases elsewhere in Europe.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Traders said an increase in the West German Lombard rate is
likely to be matched by a rise in the U.S. Federal Reserve's
discount rate.
   The Lombard rate is what the West German central bank charges
commercial banks for supplemental borrowings in which securities are
used as collateral.
   The discount rate is what the U.S. central bank charges on loans
to commercial banks.
   There were interest rate hikes in the Netherlands, Belgium and
France on Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8312, compared with
$1.8335 Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7362 West German marks, down from 1.7365; 1.4638
Swiss francs, up from 1.4630; 5.9365 French francs, up from 5.9350;
1.9593 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9590; 1,286.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,279.50; 1.2005 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1986.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.38 yen to a closing 122.97 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 122.85 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421.40 a troy ounce, up
from $420.75 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price also of $421.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $421.25, up from $420 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.67 to close at a bid $423.05.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.16.
