<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Obit-Adler     12-15 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Adler,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Larry Adler, Rags-To-Riches Immigrant, Dead At 57</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Adler, a Hungarian refugee from
World War II who arrived in Australia penniless and became one of
its leading business tycoons, has died at age 57 of complications
following a heart attack.
   Adler, who died Tuesday, was chairman and chief executive of FAI
Insurances Ltd., one of Australia's largest companies. The cause of
death was not given other than that it was related to a Dec. 2 heart
attack.
   Known as a shrewd and sometimes ruthless workaholic, Adler once
described work as something to ``play at.''
   ``I work golf, I work tennis, but I play work,'' he told a
newspaper interviewer three years ago. ``I absolutely love it and if
another heart attack is the price I have to pay to keep going at
this pace, then I'll pay it gladly.''
   Adler claimed that money itself was not the prime motive for his
constant striving.
   ``Sure, it's important when you haven't got it. But once you have
it, it is merely a barometer of how well you are doing,'' he said.
``Money is the only applause a businessman gets for his
performance.''
   Arriving in the country in 1949, Adler worked as a gas station
attendant, record-shop owner and taxi driver before forming Fire &
All Risks Insurance in 1960 with $56,000 cash.
   FAI is a $2 billion-a-year business, and is listed on exchanges
in New York, Toronto, Switzerland, New Zealand, London, Hong Kong
and Singapore.
   Laszlo J. Adler was born Nov. 2, 1931, in Budapest, Hungary, of
Jewish parents. His father, who had run a large profitable insurance
company, died in a Nazi death camp when the country was invaded in
1944. He changed his name to Larry upon settling in Australia.
   New South Wales state Premier Nick Greiner called Adler one of
Australia's great entrepreneurs. ``He built up, by his own drive and
hard work and native wit, a huge business in a very competitive
area.''
   Adler is survived by his wife Ethel and three children.
   His son Rodney, 29, a director of FAI, today was named chief
executive of the company. The family has a 41 percent controlling
interest in FAI.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
