<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-15 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines Against Yen, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined today against the Japanese
yen on investors' fears of possible interest rate hikes abroad,
while stock prices also fell.
   Trading in both markets was relatively quiet following
Wednesday's report by the U.S. Commerce Department that showed the
U.S. trade deficit had dropped only 3.1 percent in October from the
previous month to $10.35 billion.
   ``The trade figures didn't provide any clear direction for the
dollar, and dealers, anticipating possible rate hikes in West
Germany and the United States, aren't taking any large positions,''
said Kaneo Ogino, a dealer at Goldman, Sachs in Tokyo.
   The dollar closed at 122.97 yen, down 0.38 yen from Wednesday's
close.
   A moderate sell-off pushed the dollar down to 122.88 yen at the
opening, but it drifted higher on buying by investment trusts, Ogino
said. It ranged between 122.85 yen and 123.05 yen.
   ``The market held a sense of disappointment over the slowed pace
of improvement in the U.S. trade deficit in recent months, though
the latest figures were within expectations,'' said a dealer at the
Bank of Tokyo who spoke anonymously.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 156.92-point gainer Wednesday, fell 48.98 points,
or 0.16 percent, closing at 29,705.75.
   Investors, finding no incentives for either buying or selling,
remained mostly on the sidelines because of worry over rising
interest rates, traders said.
   Many investors in both markets are also reluctant to take any new
positions as the end of the year approaches, analysts said.
   ``It's a case of the end-of-the-year blues,'' said Casey
Flaherty, a trader at Yamaichi Securities Co.
   Flaherty said the market lacked new speculative themes.
   ``Until we get something new, there isn't likely to be much going
on this year,'' he said.
</TEXT>
