<HEAD>Share Prices Higher on Slower Growth in British Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher on the London stock
exchange at midday Thursday, helped by news that the growth in
British average earnings slowed in October.
   The news helped ease fears of overheating in the British economy,
dealers said. The British government has pushed up interest rates
sharply in recent months to help quell inflationary pressures.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 6.5
points, or 0.37 percent, at 1762.6 at about 12:30 p.m.
   The index opened 6.6 points down on nervousness ahead of the
release of the earnings figures and amid worries about upward
pressures on interest rates worldwide. The figures showed the
underlying annual rate of increase in average earnings fell to 9
percent in October from 9.25 percent in September and August.
   Volume was light as 228.7 million shares changed hands by midday,
compared with 263.6 million shares at the same time on Wednesday.
   Oil shares continued to dominate trading, as the market remained
convinced that London and Scottish Marine Oil had completed the
long-awaited sale of its 25.2 percent stake in Enterprise Oil. This
rumor swept the market late Wednesday and continued to make the
rounds Thursday.
   Dealers said both companies' share prices rose on relief the deal
might have finally been completed. Lasmo shares were up 11 pence at
474 pence, after peaking at 481, while Enterprise shares gained 18
to 534, having been as high as 537.
   Also in the oil sector, news late Wednesday that British
Petroleum Co. was talking exclusively with RTZ Corp. about selling
most of its minerals business gave a sharp boost to turnover,
especially in BP shares.
   BP shares, which had risen strongly on rumors ahead of official
confirmation of the possible sale, were down 1 at 258. RTZ also
reversed its recent course and rose 7 to 400. One dealer said price
changes were a correction to the previous moves. But another dealer
said the transaction, which would include the sale of BP's gold
operations, could prove a better deal for RTZ than for BP.
</TEXT>
