<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Budget     12-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Budget,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC 1989 Budget Adopted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the European
Parliament, Lord Plumb, Thursday signed the EEC's $52.8 billion 1989
budget into law.
   It was the first time since 1983, and only the second since 1979,
that the budget was signed before the fiscal year begins on Jan.1.
   The 1988 budget was only signed in June this year.
   The European Economic Community's 1989 budget amounts to 44.83
billion European currency units, or the equivalent of $52.8 billion,
with farm spending set at 26.7 billion Ecus _ $31.5 billion _ or 56
percent of the total budget.
   It was the first time agriculture payments were kept to under 60
percent of the budget since the European Economic Community was
founded 31 years ago.
   This was the result of a deal hammered out by the 12 EEC leaders
in Brussels in February to strictly control farm payments.
   The 1989 budget cut agriculture spending by 1.3 billion Ecus, or
$1.5 billion, because of higher-than-forecast world cereal prices
and a cheaper U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
