<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Economy,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Research Institute Projects 4.4 Percent Growth In 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Japanese research institute Thursday
predicted Japan's economy will grow 4.4 percent in the fiscal year
beginning April 1.
   The Nikko Research Center, affiliated with Nikko Securities Co.,
echoed projections issued by other leading economic think tanks over
the last two weeks.
   Like other researchers, Nikko said the bullish 4.4 percent growth
after accounting for inflation would be led by strong capital
investments and personal spending. Producer prices, on the other
hand, are expected to rise by a modest 0.5 percent, while consumer
prices are expected to rise by 1.0 percent.
   The forecast is based on assumptions that the official discount
rate will remain unchanged at a postwar low of 2.5 percent, an
exchange rate of 120 yen to the dollar and crude oil prices at
$14.50 per barrel.
</TEXT>
