<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Airline Dispute,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Air Lines Protests Possible U.S. Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan Air Lines said Thursday it would consider
retaliation against United Airlines if the U.S. government bans
sales of JAL tickets through computerized reservation and ticketing
systems in the United States.
   ``We deeply regret the sudden decision by the United States
neglecting our previous agreements and unilaterally applying
political pressure to settle this matter,'' the company said in a
statement.
   The U.S. Department of Transportation has accused JAL of
violating the fair competition rules of the International Air
Transport Association and called for discussions on whether
sanctions should be imposed, Kyodo News Service reported from New
York.
   The U.S. Embassy in Tokyo said Thursday it had no details of the
decision.
   The dispute surfaced last summer when JAL refused to allow United
Airlines' ticketing system to sell JAL tickets in Japan. JAL said it
is not allowed to sell United's tickets in the United States and
thus has the right to refuse sales of JAL tickets by United in Japan.
   If U.S. sanctions are adopted against JAL, the Japanese airline's
statement said, it would appeal to U.S. courts. If the sanctions are
allowed to stand, it added, ``We will consider the possibility of
retaliation against United Airlines.''
   The statement said: ``We believe we reserve the right to choose
which ticketing system to use based on our commercial judgment and
thus such a matter should not be settled on a political and
administrative basis.''
   United's Tokyo office declined to comment on the matter while
legal proceedings are under way.
</TEXT>
