<DOCNO> AP881215-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Retail-Hours     12-15 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail-Hours,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stores Sue State Over Dec. 26 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five retail stores have sued the State of
Massachusetts for the right of all stores to open during normal
business hours on Dec. 26 without having to get local permits.
   The stores are challenging state Commissioner of Labor and
Industries James Snow's interpretation of a new state law on store
openings the days after Christmas and New Year's. The holidays fall
on Sundays this year.
   Snow ruled that Sunday hours will apply on Monday, Dec. 26. That
means the stores cannot open before noon unless they get permission
from their local police chiefs, and the permits must be confirmed by
the state.
   Snow already has said the state will confirm all local permits,
but many local police chiefs have refused to grant them.
   The suit was filed Wednesday in Suffolk Superior Court by
Filene's, Filene's Basement, Lord & Taylor, Caldor and Lechmere.
   Permits to open before noon have been granted by police chiefs in
Auburn, Boston, Danvers, Hanover, Newton, Peabody, Westborough,
Westfield and Worcester.
   Permits have been denied by chiefs in Belmont, Braintree,
Brockton, Burlington, Cambridge, Dedham, Framingham, Hyannis,
Natick, Springfield and Wellesley.
   ``The retailers reluctantly decided to take this action primarily
for customer-service reasons,'' said Boston lawyer Dawn-Marie
Driscoll.
   ``On the day after Christmas, customers appear early to make
exchanges, to use gift certificates and to take advantage of
after-Christmas sales.
   ``Retailers would lose a lot of customer goodwill by being open
in some locations and being closed in others.''
   Under state law, when some holidays, including Christmas, occur
on Sundays, they are observed on the following Mondays.
   A change in the law passed last month, and agreed to by a
coalition of retailers and unions, allows retailers to open Jan. 1
and Jan. 2, and Dec. 26, but not Dec. 25.
   But the wording of the change is open to interpretation.
Retailers and some legislators said they thought it meant stores
could be open during usual weekday hours. Other said they thought it
meant Sunday hours would apply.
</TEXT>
