<2ND_LINE>PM-HCA-Financing,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HCA Officials Undecided On What Assets To Sell To Fund Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital Corp. of America officials say
they have not decided what assets they will sell to help finance the
$3.6 billion management-led buyout of the nation's largest health
care company.
   ``They're still reviewing assets and businesses, and they're not
going to make any decision until the merger is completed,'' HCA
spokesman David McFadden said Wednesday.
   HCA officials released a statement Wednesday outlining how TF
Investments Inc., a group of top managers led by HCA Chairman Thomas
F. Frist Jr. and third-party investors, plans to buy out the health
care giant.
   ``In order to meet its debt obligations, which include the
repayment of a $1.3 billion asset sale bridge loan within two years
of the merger, HCA will be required to sell certain of its assets
and businesses,'' company officials said in the statement.
   The statement said HCA currently is reviewing each of its
affiliated businesses for possible disposition.
   TF Investments has obtained commitments for more than $4 billion
in debt and $300 million in equity to finance the buyout, the
company said. TF Investments submitted the only buyout proposal by a
Nov. 18 deadline set by HCA's board of directors. The company's
board approved the buyout Nov. 22 and shareholders are expected to
ratify the decision at a February shareholders meeting.
   HCA has filed preliminary proxy materials relating to the sale
with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the statement said.
   Officials said $2.362 billion of the $4.012 billion in bank
financing will be in an eight-year loan. About $1.3 billion will
come from the bridge facility that will mature two years after the
sale is completed.
   About $280 million is expected to come from an anticipated $350
million revolving credit facility, officials said.
</TEXT>
