<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalAttendants     12-15 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Attendants,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Don't Plan To Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the flight attendants union at
Continental Airlines say they don't anticipate a strike against the
airline over wages even though the membership has authorized a
walkout if necessary.
   Negotiations with the Houston-based Continental will resume in
January, Carla Winkler, president of Local 1 of the Union of Flight
Attendants, said at a news conference Wednesday.
   ``We have made a decision that we are not calling a work stoppage
and are going to do everything we can to talk to Continental and to
try to develop a good rapport with them,'' she said.
   The union represents about 5,600 attendants, with 60 to 70
percent of them dues-paying union members, Ms. Winkler said. They
have been working without a contract for five years, she added.
   Union leaders said of the some 4,400 attendants who voted, 80
percent of them gave the union's board the authority to call a
strike if necessary.
   Continental spokesman Art Kent said the company had not expected
the attendants to agree to a strike.
   ``We're obviously pleased that nothing is going to happen to
impact public travel, especially during the traveling season,'' Kent
said.
   Ms. Winkler said Continental flight attendants are paid $11,000
to $15,000 annually, levels 30 to 35 percent below their
counterparts at other airlines.
   The union is seeking a three-year deal that would boost the lower
end of a salary scale by 5 percent and the upper end of the scale by
up to 35 percent, she said.
   Continental, she said, is offering an increase of about $1 an
hour. But Kent said the airline had made a wage and benefits package
proposal it is prepared to implement Jan. 1 that includes raises of
up to $4.25 per hour. He added, however, that the company will
continue talks with the flight attendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
