<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WestPoint-Farley     12-15 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-West Point-Farley,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Extends Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. today extended for the fourth time its
$1.4 billion unsolicited takeover bid for Georgia-based textiles
giant West Point-Pepperell Inc.
   The $48-per-share cash tender offer, which was to have expired at
12:01 a.m. EST today, will run for another week, expiring at 12:01
a.m. next Thursday, Farley said in a statement.
   Farley, the Chicago-based maker of Fruit of the Loom underwear,
Acme boots and several other apparel brands, said about 13.6 million
shares of West Point-Pepperell had been tendered by shareholders.
Those shares, along with the Pepperell shares held by Farley,
represent more than 50 percent of Pepperell's outstanding common
stock, Farley has said.
   Farley's offer is contingent on getting Pepperell's ``poison
pill'' takeover defense overturned, either in court or by a vote of
Pepperell shareholders. Farley has asked Pepperell to call a special
shareholder meeting to consider its takeover bid.
   Pepperell, based in West Point, Ga., is the country's largest
publicly held textile manufacturer. It's brands include Gold Toe
socks, Arrow shirts and Martex towels.
   In an unrelated matter, the Federal Trade Commission granted
final approval for the acquisition by West Point Pepperell of J.P.
Stevens & Co. Inc., but the FTC also ruled that the Hannah Pickett
Sheet Mill in Rockingham, N.C., would have to be sold in the next
nine months.
   The commission's order does not require the divestiture of any
brand names or licensing arrangements, West Point said.
   Hannah Pickett represents less than 8 percent of the sheet-making
capacity of the total company.
</TEXT>
