<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CaliforniaAir     12-15 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California Air,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiations to Settle California Air Pollution Lawsuit Break Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations to settle a lawsuit brought by the
state of California over air pollution from offshore oil drilling
rigs have broken down after more than two years, the Interior
Department said today.
   The department will propose new air pollution regulations in four
to six weeks which will tighten current standards, said Tom DeRocco,
spokesman for the department's Minerals Management Service.
   However, DeRocco said he could give no details of the forthcoming
proposed regulations.
   The state's 1981 lawsuit charged that pollution from drilling
rigs in federal waters off southern California made it impossible
for onshore communities to meet federal clean air regulations.
   Negotiators held their last meeting in California on Wednesday.
DeRocco said the department had been optimistic that an agreement
would result: ``We thought we were going to have something to share
with you,'' he said, but no agreement resulted.
   He said he did not know what the principal points of disagreement
were. Interior officials involved in the negotiations were to meet
in Denver with Secretary Donald P. Hodel to discuss the breakdown.
   Hodel and Gov. George Deukmejian agreed in November 1985 to try
to settle the lawsuit under the auspices of the Mediation Institute.
Other major parties were the Coalition for Clean Air and the
Citizens for a Better Environment, supporting the state's position
in the lawsuit, and the Western Oil and Gas Association, supporting
the department.
   By agreement with the state, Interior has required winning
bidders in Southern California lease offerings to install
pollution-control equipment generally similar to that required for
land-based production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
