<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-15 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with corn and oat
futures slightly higher while wheat and soybean prices were modestly
lower.
   Persistent rumors that the Soviet Union was in the market for
U.S. corn supported corn futures prices. But analysts said
expectations of large Soviet purchases of U.S. wheat appeared to be
fading _ and so was buying interest in wheat futures.
   Soybean traders continued to watch the planting weather in Brazil
and Argentina, the world's second- and fourth-largest soybean
producers, where conditions have been generally dry.
   ``They did have some fairly good rain in the early part of this
week,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in New York. ``Now the market will be looking ahead to see if
the front moving in this weekend will bring any significiant
precipitation or not.''
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.26 a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.67{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.11} a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 3 cents lower with January at $7.76{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .20 cent higher with December
at 72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .10
cent higher with January at 84.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .05
cent lower to .35 cent higher with December at 43.55 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .33 cent to .53 cent higher with February
at 45.25 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
