<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Germany-InterestRates 1stLd-Writethru   12-15 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Interest Rates, 1st Ld - Writethru,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bundesbank Hikes Lombard Rate By A Half Percentage Point</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede, ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with Poehl saying German hike
not part of concerted rate move.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank
boosted a key interest rate 0.5 percentage points to help prevent
inflation from flaring up, but a top official said the move
shouldn't be considered part of a coordinated international rate
hike.
   The Bundesbank raised the Lombard lending rate to 5.5 percent
from 5 percent effective Friday, but it kept the discount rate
unchanged at 3.5 percent.
   The Lombard rate is what the central bank charges on loans to
commercial banks when securities are used as collateral. The
discount rate is the main commercial bank loan.
   Bundesbank officials said the change in the Lombard rate came in
response to concerns about rising inflation.
   ``We are in an environment of slightly rising interest rates,''
said Bundesbank President Karl Otto Poehl.
   He said the economy is in a process ``which one can call a
boom,'' and that a tighter monetary policy is appropriate.
   Poehl also referred to interest rate developments in the United
States, Great Britain and other European countries. But he stressed
that the Lombard rate hike should not be seen as a concerted
interest rate increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
