<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1210EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TennecoLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru f0066 12-15 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco Lawsuit, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0066,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco To Challenge $600 Million Judgment In Contract Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of plaintiff to Kimble sted Kimball throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WHARTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ohio natural gas producer has won a $600
million damage judgment against a Tenneco Inc. subsidiary, but
Tenneco quickly said it would appeal the jury award.
   The 12-member jury on Wednesday ruled that Tenneco's Tennessee
Gas Pipeline subsidiary broke a contract to buy natural gas from
Floyd Kimble, co-owner of Red Hill Oil Co. of Dover, Ohio.
   The jury awarded actual damages of about $250 million, plus
interest, and punitive damages of $350 million, according to Tenneco
officials.
   The verdict followed three days of deliberations and capped a
4{-month trial in Wharton before State District Judge Daniel R.
Sklar, who still must approve the verdict.
   Houston-based Tenneco issued a statement saying it was
disappointed with the verdict and would appeal it.
   ``I'm amazed _ shocked _ astonished,'' said Walter Sapp,
Tenneco's general counsel. ``I find it totally incredible.''
   The verdict stemmed from a suit the tiny company filed against
Tenneco in December 1985 that alleged Tenneco broke a contract it
had to buy certain volumes of gas, Tenneco spokeswoman M.A. Shute
said.
   Kimble was represented by Houston attorneys John O'Quinn and Al
Deaton, who were not available for comment Wednesday.
   The Wall Street Journal on Thursday quoted Kimble's wife Doris,
who is co-owner of Red Hill, as saying of the court challenge: ``We
felt we had valid reasons as individuals to seek fulfillment of the
contract.''
   According to a statement issued by a Dallas public relations firm
representing O'Quinn, the litigation stemmed from a practice by
pipeline companies _ when oil and gas prices were higher _ of making
contracts guaranteeing producers that the companies would buy their
gas at fair market prices.
   Sapp said the two sides ``had a wide dispute'' regarding the
amount of gas Tennessee Gas was obliged to buy from Kimble. He did
not have the specific amounts of gas each side claimed it had agreed
to buy.
   Kimble claimed Tennessee Gas broke its contract in 1983, but Sapp
said the company was acting on a provision in the contract that
allowed it to buy less gas under certain circumstances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
