<DOCNO> AP881215-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-O'HareFlights     12-15 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Hare Flights,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Working Toward Staggered Flights Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two airlines that have nearly two-thirds of
the flights in and out of Chicago's O'Hare airport moved toward an
agreement today on staggering flights in an attempt to reduce delays.
   American Airlines and United Airlines worked out some tentative
scheduling arrangements for evening flights on Wednesday and were
tackling the morning flight schedule at O'Hare today, officials said.
   The discussions under the direction of the Federal Aviation
Administration were being conducted at a hotel near Washington. Any
agreement must be approved by the FAA.
   The scheduling changes, which often involve shifting flight
schedules only slightly, would not go into effect until March.
   The FAA recently directed a reduction in the maximum number of
flights per hour at O'Hare, the country's busiest airport, because
of concerns that air traffic controllers were being asked to handle
too many planes during some peak periods.
   This year there has been a sharp increase in controller errors
involving air traffic in the Chicago area.
   FAA spokesman Dick Stafford said the two-day meeting was expected
to produce a scheduling arrangement between American and United,
which together account for about 60 percent of the flights at O'Hare.
   ``Nothing at this point has been decided,'' said Stafford, adding
that the airlines had ``begun to make a little progress'' in working
out an arrangement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
