<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Ford-Converter 1stLd-Writethru f0031 12-15 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Converter, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0031,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Announces Development of New Catalytic Converter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 new grafs to UPDATE with further comments, Ford
declining to detail cost savings to consumer.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has developed an
inexpensive catalytic converter the automaker says is as effective
as platinum in meeting exhaust emissions standards.
   Ford Chairman Donald E. Petersen told the Pittsburgh High
Technology Council on Wednesday that the automaker is installing the
new converter on some 1989 cars.
   ``To appreciate the full implications of this patented
development, you must understand that at least some platinum _ a
very expensive and scarce metal _ has always been required in the
past to reduce tailpipe emissions to meet government standards,''
Petersen said.
   The idea for the converter evolved from Ford's use of ``theme
groups'' to develop new automotive technologies and adapt them to
the assembly line, Petersen said.
   Ford spokesman Bill Peacock declined today to reveal any details
about the new device or the material in it. He said it would cost
significantly less to produce, but was not specific, and did not say
how much of the savings would be passed on to the consumer.
   Peacock said if successful, the new device would not be put into
the general manufacturing process until after the 1989 model year.
</TEXT>
