<DOCNO> AP881215-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBM-EEC Bjt   12-15 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM-EEC, Bjt,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Decides To Extend Antitrust Settlement With EEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.
said Thursday it decided to extend a 1984 antitrust settlement that
requires the computer giant to give certain technical information to
competitors in Europe.
   The U.S. company and the European Economic Community said in a
statement that the accord ``has come to serve as an effective
vehicle'' for resolving questions on how competing machines can be
hooked up to IBM equipment.
   The 1984 settlement suspended a 4-year antitrust case brought by
the 12-nation trading bloc against IBM.
   IBM was allowed under the agreement the right to give, starting
Jan. 1, a year's notice that it would end the arrangement. That
meant the arrangement could have expired as early as Jan. 1, 1990.
   The agreement makes it easier for other companies to compete with
IBM by setting out a time schedule for release of certain data,
generally within four months, to enable competing equipment to
interconnect with hardware and software for IBM's large-scale System
370 mainframe computers.
   By extending the agreement, IBM avoided an uproar among Europeans
who dislike the dominance of an American-based company in the
European computer market. The agreement is relatively painless to
IBM and has not cut into its share of the market.
   The statement said the community and the company decided that
``neither foresees any change in circumstances that would cause
IBM'' to use its termination right.
   ``However, should such circumstances arise, IBM has agreed to
review the matter with the (EEC) prior to giving any notice,'' the
statement said.
   Jean-Francois Verstrynge, an official in the community's
competition department, said, ``IBM and the (EEC) have agreed that
they do not foresee that at the present time such special
circumstances will occur.'' The special conditions were not
specified.
   The move to extend the agreement, he said, was prompted by
concern the computer market would suffer from ``fear, uncertainty
and doubt'' if IBM had the power to give notice at any time.
   ``It was to eliminate this uncertainy'' that the extension was
sought, he told reporters.
   IBM is, in terms of revenue, the largest computer vendor in
Europe as well as worldwide.
   Verstrynge said the EEC's competition chief, Peter Sutherland,
met on Dec. 1 with C. Michael Armstrong, president of IBM Europe, to
discuss a continuation of the accord.
   ``It was an easy meeting,'' Verstrynge said. ``But Mr. Sutherland
was totally determined.''
   The trading bloc will continue reviewing the agreement annually,
he said.
   An IBM spokesman in Paris, who demanded anonymity, said the
arrangement ``does achieve the intended objective'' of providing a
means through which the company can provide data to competitors.
   He said that from August 1984 to last June 30, the computer firm
received 66 requests from 20 competitors covering 703 questions.
   Verstrynge said prior to the agreement, IBM could announce a new
piece of equipment without releasing technical details.
   ``The competitors could not react with competing products or
services because they didn't have the technical information,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
