<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankerImplicated     12-15 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banker Implicated,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-NY Fed Reserve Bank Director Pleads Innocent To Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former bank president accused of leaking
confidential interest rate data while he was a director of the New
York Federal Reserve Bank pleaded innocent Thursday to insider
trading charges.
   Robert A. Rough was arraigned before U.S. District Judge
Dickinson R. Debevoise one week after being indicted by a federal
grand jury here.
   Rough was accused of leaking information on the discount rate set
by the Federal Reserve Bank in Washington to principals at Bevill,
Bresler & Schulman Inc., a Livingston, N.J. brokerage firm that
later collapsed.
   The government alleged that Bevill, Bresler made millions of
dollars and avoided millions in losses because of the information,
which Rough allegedly exchanged for $47,000 in interest-free loans.
   Rough's attorney, Michael Himmel, said he would need time to
review thousands of transactions by the firm, which collapsed in
April 1985.
   Debevoise on Thursday set Rough's bail at a $150,000 personal
recognizance bond.
   A hearing on pre-trial motions was set for Feb. 14, and trial was
scheduled for Feb. 21.
   After Thursday's hearing, Himmel and Rough declined to comment.
   Authorities have called Rough's case the first insider trading
involving government securities and the Federal Reserve system.
   The indictment said that while he was president of the National
Bank of Sussex County in Branchville and sat on the New York Fed's
board from 1982 to 1984, Rough regularly leaked word on the New York
Fed's discount rate recommendation to the national Fed, as well as
the Fed's final determination on the rate.
   Changes in the discount rate _ the interest on Fed loans to
commercial banks _ have a powerful impact on the securities markets.
Fed officials have called action involving the rate one of their
most closely guarded secrets.
   Discount rate changes widely are regarded as the strongest
indication the Fed makes of the direction it wants to push interest
rates, which affect the price of debt securities such as bonds.
   After the Fed learned of the allegations against Rough, which
first were mentioned in April 1987 during testimony of a criminal
trial stemming from the Bevill, Bresler collapse, it tightened
procedures regarding the rate.
   Rough formally was charged with conspiracy to commit wire and
securities fraud, two counts of bank fraud, one count each of wire
fraud and securities fraud and two counts of making false statements
to banks.
   Rough resigned from Sussex National earlier this year,
prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
