<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0033,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Finish Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher Thursday on the London
Stock Exchange, boosted by news that British wage growth slowed in
October and by some speculative buying of several major stocks.
   Dealers said overall trading volume remained low, with activity
concentrated in a few of the leading shares affected by takeover
speculation or special situations.
   Other share prices were higher in thin volume as the reported
slowdown in British average earnings reduced fears that British
interest rates would have to be increased again to curb inflation.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 7.1
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,763.2, near the session peak.
   Volume was a modest 396.2 million shares, down from 447.1 million
shares a day earlier.
   Early in the trading session the market remained in negative
territory, preoccupied with evidence of an upward drift in world
interest rates.
   But the market turned around after the government reported that
the underlying annual rate of increase in average earnings fell to 9
percent in October from 9.25 percent in September and August.
   Most market forecasts had been for the rate to show no change on
the month, while some analysts called for faster growth.
</TEXT>
