<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     12-15 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher After German Rate Hike, Gold Falls On Platinum
Selloff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in Europe on Thursday after an
expected increase in a key West German interest rate failed to
bolster the West German mark.
   Gold and silver prices fell in busy trading, pulled down by a
sell-off in platinum sparked by Ford Motor Co.'s announcement that
it had developed a catalytic converter that didn't use the metal.
   Dealers said speculation that the U.S. Federal Reserve would
follow the West German Bundesbank's move by boosting the U.S.
discount rate helped the dollar.
   Dealers widely had discounted the Bundesbank's move to raise its
key Lombard lending rate by 0.5 percentage point to 5.5 percent. But
many market players had held on to marks rather than dollars in
hopes that the move would boost the mark further against the U.S.
currency.
   When such a rise did not materialize, dealers sold their marks
for dollars and other currencies.
   ``The move was predicted, and there wasn't enough reaction to
it,'' one dealer said.
   The Lombard rate is the interest the West German central bank
charges commercial banks for supplemental borrowings in which
securities are used as collateral. The discount rate is what the
Federal Reserve charges on loans to commercial banks.
   The West German rate hike followed rate hikes on Wednesday and
Thursday by the central banks of France, Belgium and the Netherlands
and Austria.
   In London, the British pound dipped to $1.8280 from $1.8335 on
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7485 West German marks, up from 1.7365; 1.4725
Swiss francs, up from 1.4630; 5.9745 French francs, up from 5.9350;
1.9665 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9590; 1,288.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,279.50; and 1.2054 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1986.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.38 yen to a closing 122.97 yen. Later in London,
the dollar was quoted at 123.35 yen.
   A wave of platinum selling was sparked by reports that Ford Motor
Co. Chairman Donald Petersen said his company had developed a
catalyst that was just as effective as platinum in meeting stringent
exhaust emissions standards, but was significantly less expensive.
   Platinum tumbled to $565 an ounce at the close in Zurich, down
from Wednesday's close of $600 an ounce and the session high of $601.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $416.45 a troy ounce,
compared with $420.75 bid late Wednesday In Zurich, gold closed at
$416.00 an ounce, down from $420 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.67 to close at a bid of
$423.05.
   Silver bullion prices fell in London to a late bid of $6.11 a
troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $6.16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
