<HEAD>Grain Futures Advance, Soybeans Decline On Export Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices closed modestly higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors that the Soviet
Union may have purchased up to 2 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   But soybean futures declined on the lack of confirmation of a
rumored sale of soybean meal to the Soviets, analysts said.
   The corn market has been strong all week on persistent rumors
that the Soviet Union was in the market for a large amount of U.S.
corn and sorghum.
   Those rumors intensified Thursday, with some observers saying
they believed the sale already had been completed.
   ``It is very likely that the sale has already gone through and
we're just waiting for official confirmation,'' said Ted Mao, a
grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``It wouldn't surprise me to see some sort of confirmation come
in the next 24 to 48 hours,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.28} a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.68 a bushel; oats
were } cent to 2\ cents higher with December at $2.13 a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents to 3} cents lower with January at $7.75 a
bushel.
