<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1513EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ChristmasTrees Bjt   12-15 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Trees, Bjt,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tree Growers Wage Christmas War Against Plastic Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSLEY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow falls silently on the Michigan
battlefield as Tim Schmuckal inspects the ranks of Christmas tree
soldiers.
   Scotch pine, blue spruce and Douglas fir are destined for all
points of the United States to meet their artificial foe: the
plastic Christmas tree.
   ``I'm worried about that,'' says the 18-year-old Schmuckal,
shaking the snow from his brown hair.
   ``They're saying that 42 percent, 48 percent, of people are
buying artificial trees,'' he said.
   With a year of college under his belt, Schmuckal isn't sure there
is enough future in his father's northwestern Lower Peninsula
Christmas tree farm for him to take the same trade.
   The National Christmas Tree Association expects Americans will
buy 34.1 million natural trees this holiday, while about 30 million
people will put up artificial ones.
   There are other problems. The summer drought killed 2,000 young
trees at the Schmuckal farm, flooding hurt Michigan's 1986 harvest,
and an increase in small-scale growers threatens to undercut the
market.
   But growers say those woes are sideline skirmishes. From the
hand-worked 400 acres at the Schmuckal Tree Farm in northern
Michigan to the helicopter-harvested operations of the nation's
largest Christmas tree growers, it is fake trees that are hurting a
$1 billion-a-year business the most.
   The market share for artificial trees has continued increasing
despite a 21.8 percent jump in natural tree sales the past 11 years.
Only 20 years ago, fewer than 20 percent of the holiday trees were
artificial.
   ``We can't ship artificial trees fast enough,'' said Terrence
Hayes, vice president of the American Tree Co. in Pittsburgh. ``The
trees are looking more like real trees each year. And increased
prices don't make any difference. They still sell.''
   Artificial trees offer durability, safety and variety, their
sponsors say. They come in metallic pink, shimmering silver or
decorated with feathers. They come in symmetrical green perfection.
   But, ``they don't smell Christmas. ... And they're expensive,''
said Barry Brand, executive secretary of the Michigan Christmas Tree
Growers Association.
   Artificial trees also are causing problems for others: a charity
lot in Saginaw that once sold about 2,000 trees to raise money for
St. George's Catholic Church now reports sales of 1,400.
   Individual tree growers are doing what they can to compete,
pushing quality control programs and improving tree strains.
   Most trees are stained green before cutting to give them a good
color. Farms like the Schmuckal operation prune the crop into
classic cones by hand, while some bigger operations airlift the
harvest by helicopter so the trees won't lose needles from being
dragged on the ground or hauled in a truck.
   But the biggest push came just this year, when the
Milwaukee-based National Christmas Tree Association declared war
against fake trees with a $1 million promotional campaign.
   About three-fourths of the money is committed to television
commercials featuring NBC weatherman Willard Scott extolling pine
needles over plastic.
   Michigan, which supplied this year's Capitol Hill Christmas tree,
has inaugurated its own promotion with a quality control program.
Select trees that meet specifications are bestowed with a ``Michigan
Snowfresh'' tag before being loaded onto trucks headed for Florida,
New York, Mexico and Canada.
   ``We're trying to build up Michigan. There's something about
Michigan. We have the soils,'' Brand said.
   Oregon growers would disagree, said Don Becker, spokesman for the
National Christmas Tree Association said. Both states ship out about
6 million trees a year and claim to lead the nation.
   ``We don't get into it and just say the two states are the top
producers,'' Becker said.
   Back on his father's farm, Tim Schmuckal isn't certain Michigan
can do for Christmas trees what Idaho did for potatoes. Too few
trees bear the tag and the bulk of what consumers find in hometown
parking lots show no origin at all.
   The national association is not concerned that programs such as
``Snowfresh'' have that impact. Any cut tree is desirable, Becker
said. ``Just get out there and get one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0286 </DOCNO>
