<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BusinessFailures     12-15 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Failures,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Failures Fell 6.3 Percent in First Nine Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of U.S. business failures fell by 6.3
percent during the first three quarters of this year, the best
performance in nearly a decade, according to a private survey
released Thursday.
   The number of business failures fell to 44,793 from 47,794 in the
first nine months of 1987, the report by Dun & Bradstreet Corp.
stated.
   Joseph Duncan, Dun & Bradstreet's corporate economist, said the
decline was ``larely attributable to decreases in the levels of
failures in the oil and agricultural states.''
   Agricultural business failures fell 54.9 percent. Duncan said the
number of agricultural failures soared in 1987 when farmers took
advantage of new protections under the federal bankruptcy law. The
rush to benefit from the new provisions subsided this year, leading
to the drop in failures in that industry.
   The only industry to see an increase in failures was wholesale
trade, where 5.4 percent more companies failed during the first nine
months of this year than in the same period a year earlier.
   In other industries, mining failures fell 25.5 percent;
transportation and utility failures were off 7.8 percent; retail
failures were off 6.6 percent; financial, insurance and real estate
failures fell 3.4 percent; failures of service companies were down
1.8 percent; construction failures were off 1.4 percent; and
manufacturing failures were essentially unchanged.
   Dun & Bradstreet is a financial information publisher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2117EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-EEC-JapanDairy     12-15 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Japan Dairy,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC To Hold Talks With Japan On Dairy Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Thursday it will hold talks next month with Japan in an effort to
open Japan's dairy market to more imports.
   The 12-nation trading bloc would like Japan to ease measures that
it says protect the local dairy industry from foreign competition.
   The Japanese market for table cheese amounts to about 120,000
metric tons a year, with imports from the European trading group
accounting for some 27,000 tons.
   The study found that sales of European dairy products in Japan
were hindered by import quotas on cream, butter, powdered whey, and
condensed and powdered milk.
   It also said Japan maintains a 35 percent tariff on processed and
natural cheeses and limits the opening of large supermarkets that
are the main outlets for sales of imported cheese.
   Moreover, it said, exporters were faced with long delays at
customs offices and discriminatory labeling rules.
   As a result, European Community officials should press Japan to
slash the tariff on imported cheese, ease restrictions on expansion
of supermarkets and shift government subsidies from production to
promotion and consumer education, the study indicated.
   The study found that Japan's per capita consumption of dairy
products is one of the lowest among industrialized nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
