<DOCNO> AP881215-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Semiconductor     12-15 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Semiconductor,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Semi Announces Loss; Micron Has Big Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. on Thursday announced a $25.2
million net loss during its second fiscal quarter and company
officials blamed the loss on a sharp decline in bookings and sales
and a weak semiconductor market.
   The results contrasted sharply with those of another chip maker,
Micron Technology Inc., which said late Wednesday the profits in its
first fiscal quarter nearly quadrupled.
   National Semiconductor of Santa Clara, Calif., said its loss was
in contrast to a net profit of $11.6 million, or 8 cents a share, a
year earlier. Analysts were expecting the losses, noting that the
company faced a squeeze on pricing because of intense competition in
its markets.
   Sales for the second quarter, which ended Nov. 27, were $705.3
million compared to $640 million for the same quarter last year.
   For the first half of fiscal year 1989, sales were $1.35 billion,
with a net loss of $55.7 million. Sales in the same period of 1988
were $1.15 billion with net earnings of $25.1 million or 19 cents
per share.
   Micron Technology, of Boise, Idaho, did better because it makes
computer memory chips, which are priced highly because of short
supplies. It earned $32.2 million on revenue of $110.4 million
during the quarter that ended Dec. 1. Last year, Micron earned $8.4
million on revenue of $43.2 million.
   Per-share earnings were 88 cents for the quarter, compared to 33
cents per share a year ago.
   However, both income and revenue were down from the last quarter
of Micron's 1988 fiscal year, when the company had a record
quarterly profit.
   The declines were due largely to a higher effective tax rate and
costs associated with hiring new employees, said Kipp Bedard,
manager of investor relations. In addition, the company has been
setting money for legal expenses.
   In November, Texas Instruments filed a patent infringement
lawsuit against Micron. Texas Instruments alleges that Micron is
producing memory chips that disregard TI's patents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1557EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     12-15 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.72 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix summary line.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 459 money market mutual
funds rose $1.72 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $281.22 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.22 billion drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high of $281.89 billion in the
week ended Nov. 23, 1988.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 230 general purpose funds rose $170.1 million to $90.06
billion, assets of 93 broker-dealer funds increased $117.7 million
to $117.86 billion, and assets of 136 institutional funds rose $1.43
billion to $73.3 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.95 percent from 7.85 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 7.81 percent from 7.72 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 34
days, down from 35 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.17 percent as of Wednesday from 6.15 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, were unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.12
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.08 percent
the previous week. Yields were 8.39 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
8.35 percent; 8.52 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.49 percent; and
8.68 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.66 percent.
</TEXT>
