<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BrokerageLayoffs     12-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brokerage Layoffs,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smith Barney Announces Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. announced
Thursday it had laid off about 120 employees, largely in its
municipal and equities departments.
   Meanwhile, another large brokerage firm, Kleinwort Benson Group
PLC said in London that it cut 35 jobs from its British equity
trading department. The firm employs around 4,000 people, including
about 600 in that division.
   Smith Barney, a division of Greenwich, Conn.-based Primerica
Corp., made its cuts ``after careful analysis of our staffing
requirements in the context of our current business environment,''
said spokesman Robert Connor.
   ``We decided that in the business environment that we're living
through some steps had to be taken to keep costs down,'' Connor said.
   Smith Barney posted an operating loss of $14.5 million in the
third quarter, compared with an operating profit of $10.5 million in
the year-ago period.
   Business has been off for many Wall Street firms in recent
months, particularly in stock trading.
   The hardest hit area was Smith Barney's municipal department,
where about 25 employees were laid off in the trading, syndicate and
investment banking areas, and in equities trading, where about 20
employees were laid off.
   Smith Barney employs about 6,300. So far this year it has cut its
staff by about 500, Connor said.
   At Kleinwort, a spokesman said the aim of its layoffs was ``to
reduce overheads to stay competitive in a very difficult market.''
   Kleinwort's move follows last week's decision by rival Morgan
Grenfell Group PLC to withdraw from market making in equity and
fixed-interest securities. Morgan Grenfell, which cut 450 jobs,
blamed tough trading conditions and a severe price war among market
makers.
</TEXT>
