<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Comstock     12-15 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Comstock,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McGraw-Hill Buys Commodity Quotations Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc., the publishing and information
services giant, said Thursday it had acquired Commodity Quotations
Inc., which provides up-to-the minute financial information. The
price was not disclosed.
   Commodity Quotations' Comstock product contains commodity,
securities and foreign exchange market information from more than 45
markets and exchanges in the United States, Canada and abroad.
   Comstock is used mainly by retail brokers and investment
advisers, but McGraw-Hill hopes to expand the service and the base
of customers who take it.
   Joseph L. Dionne, chairman and chief executive of McGraw-Hill,
said the acquisition was a step toward his company's long-term goal
``to provide niche markets with authoritative information, directly
and economically to personal computers, and on a real-time basis
which is essential to trading markets.''
   McGraw-Hill already has a service, Platt's Global Alert, that
provides spot news and up-to-the minute quotes for the oil and
petrochemicals industries and has been delivered via Comstock since
April.
   The company plans to expand Comstock into other commodity markets
and provide a full-service financial trading information product to
a wider audience that will include larger financial trading
companies.
   Commodity Quotations, which has offices in Scarsdale, N.Y., and
London, will become part of Standard & Poor's-McGraw-Hill, a unit of
McGraw Hill Financial Services Co., which provides financial,
economic and investment information and analytical service.
</TEXT>
