<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Primerica     12-15 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primerica,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Primerica, Commercial Credit Shareholders Vote On Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial Credit Group Inc.'s $1.65
billion cash and stock buyout of Primerica Corp. was approved
overwhelmingly by shareholders of both companies on Thursday,
despite criticism by some Primerica workers and shareholders of big
severance payments for the company's executives.
   ``I only wish the powers that protected the executive board would
have protected the employees a little more,'' said Lorraine Cheney,
a Primerica employee for three years.
   Cheney and some others said their benefits have been cut, while
top executives of Primerica are receiving severance payments, called
golden parachutes, that reportedly total about $98 million.
   Under the buyout, shareholders will receive one share of
Commercial Credit common stock plus $7 in cash for each share of
Primerica.
   Based on Thursday's closing price, the deal is worth $28.25 a
share in cash and stock. Primerica closed at $28 a share on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The combined companies will operate under the Primerica name.
Primerica, a Greenwich-based financial services and direct-marketing
company, is the parent of Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., the
investment firm it acquired in 1987 for $750 million.
   Separately, Smith Barney on Thursday announced the layoffs of 120
employees due to soft business conditions.
   Baltimore-based Commercial Credit is involved in consumer credit,
including lending, property and casualty insurance and credit cards.
   Shareholders for both companies approved the merger on Thursday.
Primerica shareholders voted in Stamford, while Commercial Credit
shareholders met in New York.
   Primerica's proxy statement does not give a total figure for the
severance payment package for its top executives. But published
reports have put the figure at about $98 million.
   Primerica spokespeople declined to discuss the figure, because
some shareholders have filed lawsuits against the company and its
directors in an attempt to stop the merger.
   The proxy does say that Primerica Chairman Gerald Tsai Jr. will
receive $19.2 million in cash, $8.6 million to cover excise taxes
and $10.4 million, relating to cancellation of stock options.
   The proxy also reports that Tsai, who will be the new company's
largest individual shareholder and director and chairman of the
board's executive committee, will receive an annual fee of $250,000,
office space, staff, plust business expenses.
   ``I can only tell you it is our judgment that this merger is in
the best interest of the shareholders,'' Tsai said.
   Tsai also said he could not discuss the golden parachutes because
the matter is in litigation. But he told one shareholder who
complained that 93 percent of the shareholders voted in favor of the
merger, ``so I guess you're in the minority.''
</TEXT>
