<DOCNO> AP881215-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 1951EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mobil-Ozone     12-15 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mobil-Ozone,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobil Ends Use Of Ozone-Depleting Substance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Chemical Co. said Thursday it has stopped
using ozone-destroying chemicals to make its foam packaging for
food, following through on a commitment made in April.
   Mobil Chemical is a leading producer of foam food containers for
schools, hospitals and fast-food restaurants. A plant in
Bakersfield, Calif., made most of the foam that used the chemicals,
called chlorofluorocarbons.
   The voluntary elimination of the compounds will affect less than
15 percent of Mobil's polystyrene foam products business, the
company said.
   ``We're able to take this step because our research effort gave
us an alternate blowing agent that is environmentally acceptable,''
said John Y. Glass, vice president and general manager of the
Polystyrene Business Group.
   Chlorofluorocarbons are believed responsible for depleting the
earth's ozone layer, a protective shield that screens out harmful
ultraviolet rays from the sun.
   The Food Service and Packaging Institute announced on April 12 a
voluntary program by all its members to phase out use of
chlorofluorocarbons by the end of 1988.
   Mobil Chemical, a Stamford, Conn.-based subsidiary of Mobil
Corp., recently announced it was opening a plastic foam recycling
plant in Massachusetts to recycle polystyrene foam products and
plastic cutlery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
