<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-15 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Market Collapses On Ford News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices collapsed Thursday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange after Ford Motor Co. announced development of a
platinum-free catalytic converter that could slash global demand for
the metal by one-third.
   On other markets, sugar futures plunged; energy futures fell;
grain futures were higher; soybeans were lower; livestock and meat
were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
   All platinum futures except the spot December contract settled
down the daily limit of $25 with the January contract at $579.50 a
troy ounce. The spot contract, which has no limit, finished $34.10
lower at $531.90.
   The use of platinum as a catalyst for chemical reactions in
automobile pollution-control systems accounted for about 38 percent
of world consumption of newly produced platinum last year and was
expected to represent about 35 percent of consumption this year.
   Speculative buying of platinum futures had been rising due to
recent projections that demand would continue outstripping
production through 1992. Ford's announcement jolted the market.
   ``It's a disaster,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, metals analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``All our reasons for
being bullish on platinum have been defused.''
   Fred Demler, New York-based metals economist with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. agreed: ``It's a major development. It could
potentially wipe out one-third of platinum consumption.''
   Ford Chairman Donald E. Peterson announced a pilot program for
the invention Wednesday evening but the news didn't hit the markets
until after the opening of platinum trading on the New York Merc.
   ``It came in dribs and drabs,'' said Ms. Raptopoulos. ``I had
heard it as a rumor as soon as the market opened but I was hesitant
to act.''
   She said the market started falling from its $606 opening, ad at
$601 she recommended selling the contract. That was at about 9:35
a.m., she said. Selling quickly escalated until the market went
limit-down at about 9:50 a.m.
   The first news service report of Peterson's remarks came across
the wires at about 10 a.m. EST.
   The platinum selloff spread to gold and silver futures, which are
traded on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $8.60 to $10.10 lower with February at $416.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 11.6 cents to 13 cents lower with March at
$6.185 a troy ounce.
   Sugar futures prices plummeted on New York's Coffee, Sugar and
Cocoa Exchange on indications that near-term availability of sugar
was on the rise, analysts said.
   Bearish factors included Thailand's announcement that it planned
to move up shipments of 100,000 metric tons of sugar from July to
March, and indications that China had been selling sugar, said
Judith Ganes, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York.
   Sugar settled .44 cents to 2.76 cents lower with the active March
contract at 10.84 cents a pound.
   Oil futures retreated in quiet trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange amid profit-taking following the previous session's rally,
analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 38 cents
lower with January at $16.35 a barrel; heating oil was .19 cent to
.55 cent lower with January at 50.94 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to .32 cent lower with January at 43.65 cents
a gallon.
   Grain futures finished modestly higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid rumors the Soviet Union may have purchased up to 2
million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Soybean futures declined on the lack of confirmation of a rumored
sale of soybean meal to the Soviets, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 1} cents to 3{ cents higher with December at $4.28{
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1{ cents higher with December at
$2.68\ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2{ cents higher with December
at $2.14 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 3 cents lower with
January at $7.75{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
in positioning ahead of Friday's monthly cattle-on-feed report from
the Agriculture Department, while most pork futures declined.
   Live cattle settled .02 cent lower to .37 cent higher with
December at 72.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with January at 84.05 cents a pound; live hogs
were .03 cent to .30 cent lower with December at 43 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 1.17 cents lower to .20 cent higher with
February at 43.87 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated moderately on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 settled .70 point lower at 277.70. Each point
is worth $500.
</TEXT>
