<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-China     12-15 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-China,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maritime Agreement Signed With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and China signed a four-year
maritime agreement Thursday that will ensure access of each nation's
vessels to the ports of the other.
   The two nations also pledged their intention to provide for the
sharing of cargo carriage in two-way trade, the Department of
Transportation announcement said.
   Vessels of each nation would be assured of at least a third of
all such cargoes, it said.
   Under the agreement, U.S.-flag vessels may enter 40 Chinese ports
upon 24 hours advance notice, and Chinese vessels will have the same
access to all but 12 U.S. ports.
   ``This agreement, which caps a five-year effort to improve
U.S.-China maritime relations, will provide new opportunities for
U.S. carriers serving China,'' said Transportation Secretary Jim
Burnley.
   Signing for China was Minister of Communications Qian Yongchang.
   Meanwhile, Sea-Land Corp. announced it will open shipping offices
in Shanghai, Tainjin and Dalian.
</TEXT>
