<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SecuritiesFraud     12-15 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Securities Fraud,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Charged In Stock Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people were charged Thursday with
defrauding investors in a start-up jewelry company of $640,000 in a
case involving a New York brokerage firm already under scrutiny by
federal authorities, the U.S. attorney said.
   Stock of the jewelry company, Renaissance Enterprises, was
underwritten by Monarch Funding Inc. of New York.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission in a 1985 civil lawsuit
charged Monarch, its president, an employee and two others with
manipulating the stock of two Washington, D.C., companies. The
action was put on hold until January while the U.S. attorney in
Newark conducts an overlapping criminal investigation, said SEC
attorney Barry Goldsmith in Washington.
   An indictment unsealed Thursday accused Eric Wynn, 29, his wife
Annabelle Salaverria Wynn, 42, of Edison, N.J., and Francis LaMagra,
40, of Paramus, N.J., of conspiracy, interstate transportation of
fraudulently obtained stockholders' funds and income tax violations.
The indictment was returned May 20.
   Wynn was president of Renaissance, Mrs. Wynn was vice president
and LaMagra was an officer of Intercoastal Affiliates, a company
that dealt with Renaissance, the indictment said.
   It said they used several means to siphon off funds from the
offering, including making checks payable to accounts under
different names controlled by Wynn and under his wife's maiden name.
   They allegedly used $18,500 to buy personal jewelry. Phony loans
were made to companies created by the defendants, the indictment
said.
   The defendants could not be reached for comment. The Wynns have
an unpublished telephone number and LaMagra had no listing in
Paramus.
   ``Mr. LaMagra just unequivocably denies any criminal wrongdoing
in any of these matters,'' said his attorney, Robert De Groot. He
said the government had strung together innocent business activities
to create a fiction of wrongdoing. LaMagra has a ``history of
working in the banking industry'' and is a well-known business
consultant, the lawyer said.
   An attorney for the Wynns, Raymond A. Brown Sr., could not be
reached. He did not return a phone message.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert P. Warren, chief of the frauds
division, said the lag in unsealing the indictment was because of a
continuing investigation.
   LaMagra was convicted in federal court in Brooklyn, N.Y., in
April for conspiring to prepare false income tax returns for a
reputed captain in the Bonanno crime family, Louis Attanasio, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ruth Nordenbrook in Brooklyn.
   That case is on appeal.
   The SEC charged penny-stock underwriter Monarch, which maintains
its innocence, with illegally inflating the stock in 1982 and 1983
of Toxic Waste Containment Inc., a hazardous waste cleanup company,
and Liquidation Control Inc., a business consulting firm for
distressed companies.
   In November 1987, a former Wall Street analyst was sentenced to
eight years in prison by a federal judge in Newark for writing
falsely positive reports on the companies while having a financial
interest in them.
   Thursday's indictment said the Wynns and LaMagra, through false
claims and a false prospectus, caused Monarch to make ``false
representations to induce the public to invest'' in Renaissance.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said the defendants face at
least 50 years in jail each if convicted of all the charges.
   They were not arrested and no court appearance was set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
