<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GE-Fraud     12-15 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GE-Fraud,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE, Two Employees Plead Innocent to Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. and two employees
pleaded innocent Thursday to federal charges of padding the cost of
a battlefield computer system by $10 million.
   GE, the nation's third-largest defense contractor, and the two
employees are charged with hiding savings negotiated with
subcontractors in a $270 million Army contract to make the computer
system.
   The two employees are James Badolato of Springfield, Pa., and
Gerald A. Leo of King of Prussia, Pa.
   ``The government alleges in essence that their materials and
subcontractor costs were inflated and the defendants and General
Electric knew it,'' said Nicholas C. Harbist, the assistant U.S.
attorney prosecuting the case.
   George Jamison, a GE spokesman in Connecticut, said the company
would stand by the statement it released at the time of the
indictments. In that statement, the company labeled the charges
``unfair and unfounded.''
   The company also said that an internal investigation into the
same matter showed pricing discrepancies totaling $3.69 million,
which the company already has refunded.
   In May 1985, GE pleaded guilty to unrelated contract-fraud
charges, paying a $1.04 million fine and reimbursing the government
$800,000.
   J. Clayton Undercofler III, the lawyer representing GE, said the
innocent pleas were entered in a brief hearing before federal
magistrate Edwin E. Naythons.
   A trial date for the current charges was set for Feb. 13.
   Badolato and Leo were released on their own recognizance under a
$250,000 bond. As part of the release agreement, the two men
surrendered their passports and agreed to restrict their travel to
the eastern district of Pennsylvania, Harbist said.
   The 321-count indictment, released Nov. 29, charges that the
scheme was conducted through GE's wholly-owned subsidiary Management
and Technical Services Co., or MATSCO, in the Philadelphia suburb of
King of Prussia.
   GE was awarded a $250 million contract in June 1983 to make the
``decentralized automated service support system,'' called the
DAS-3, for the Army.
   According to the indictment, the company and the two employees
lied to the Defense Department about the prices GE was paying for
parts and raw materials and double-billed for some materials.
   The Army would have been defrauded of $22 million if the scheme
had not been uncovered, the Pentagon said.
   The government charges Badolato, 41, formerly the subsidiary's
subcontracts manager, with trying to cover up the scheme by altering
dates of purchase orders and withholding information from goverment
auditors.
   Leo, 51, formerly the materials manager for MATSCO, is also
charged with lying to a federal auditor.
   Both men have been transferred to other parts of GE.
   Leo faces a maximum of 55 years in prison and $1.3 million in
fines if he is convicted on one count of racketeering, five counts
of mail fraud and two counts of making false statements and
concealing material facts from a federal agency.
   Badolato faces the same penalties plus $5,000 more in fines if
convicted of one count of racketeering, five counts of mail fraud,
one count of obstructing agency proceedings and one count of making
false statements and concealing material facts from a federal agency.
   GE is charged with five counts of mail fraud and 312 counts of
presenting false claims to the government.
   In Washington, Glen Flood, a spokesman for the Defense
Department, said he was unaware of any proceedings to suspend or bar
GE from bidding on defense contracts. An Army spokesman did not
return calls about the matter. Jamison would not comment on the
topic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
