<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TakeoverBill     12-15 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Takeover Bill,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Bill Advances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Legislature voted unanimously
Thursday to temporarily restore to corporations in New York a weapon
to fight hostile takeover attempts by other companies.
   The measure validating the use of so-called ``poison pills'' was
approved 129-0 by the state Assembly and 52-0 by the Senate and sent
to Gov. Mario Cuomo's desk. The legislation, a product of
negotiations involving the governor's office, is expected to quickly
be signed into law by Cuomo.
   The measure is designed to undo until April 1, 1989, the result
of a state Supreme Court ruling earlier this year in which a poison
pill that Irving Bank Corp. tried to use to fend off a hostile
takeover by Bank of New York Co. was ruled illegal.
   That court decided New York state laws prohibit the inequitable
treatment of shareholders. That cleared the way for Bank of New
York's acquisition and raised concerns among the more than 100
companies in New York that have poison pill rules in place as
protection against hostile suitors.
   Under the poison pill scenario, a target company gives
shareholders the right to buy additional stock at reduced prices
when an outside party buys up a certain percentage of the company's
shares. That makes it far more expensive for a suitor to buy enough
stock to get a controlling interest in the target company.
   The poison pill is designed chiefly to give a company time to
fend off an unfriendly takeover, if it chooses, or to negotiate a
better price for its shareholders if it goes along with a buyout
offer.
   The Senate sponsor of the bill, Richard Schermerhorn, R-Orange,
said the Republican-controlled Senate originally favored validating
the poison pills for 18 months, but he said that time period was
reduced due to opposition in the Democratic Assembly.
   A special task force made up of business leaders and others is in
charge of studying the use of poison pills and other aspects of the
merger and acquisition field and will report to the Legislature by
early spring.
   Schermerhorn said he'd been told there were ``billions of dollars
out there'' that could be used in acquisitions and that some effort
must be made to head off the wholesale buying and selling of
companies.
   State. Sen. Franz Leichter, a Manhattan Democrat who voted for
the measure, said poison pills are sometimes used by corporate
management to ``keep itself in control.'' He said that can lead to
what he called abuses.
   ``Poison pills really are a way of changing the rules in the
middle of a game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
