<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Coors-Teamsters     12-15 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coors-Teamsters,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coors Employees Reject Teamsters Representation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brewery workers at Adolph Coors Co. have
voted overwhelmingly against union representation by the Teamsters,
a spokeswoman for the brewery said Thursday night.
   Results of the two days of balloting on union representation were
announced by Pam Crider, a brewery spokeswoman.
   ``Of the 1,562 eligible workers at the brewery, 1,081 voted
against union representation, while 413 voted for the union,'' she
said.
   ``Brewery workers have decided that they don't want union
representation,'' said John Meadows, director of community relations
for Coors. ``Coors will continue to work to maintain high-quality
relationships among its work force without third-party
representation.''
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters switched a live
telephone in Golden to a recording after the vote was announced.
   The vote followed 18 months of union and company politicking at
the brewery, the nation's fourth largest.
   The Teamsters needed a simple majority to win representation for
the 1,600 Coors brewery workers.
   The brewery has been non-union since December 1978, when workers
voted overwhelmingly to withdraw from the AFL-CIO after a bitter
20-month strike.
   The strike had been effectively broken and triggered a nationwide
organized labor boycott of Coors products. That boycott officially
ended in August 1987 with an agreement between Coors and the AFL-CIO
and including the Teamsters.
   An agreement between Coors and the Teamsters stipulated that win
or lose, there will be no return to the boycott against Coors
products.
   Voting began Wednesday, when 126 brewery workers who had Thursday
off voted. It continued at three locations at the brewery on
Thursday, said Meadows.
   Key issues in the election included wages and pensions. The
Teamsters have touted the wages recently implemented and the pension
plan under consideration by Anheuser Busch Co.'s new brewery in Fort
Collins, Colo.
   Coors officials have warned employees not to count on those wage
and pension levels even if the Teamsters win, saying Busch is four
times as large as Coors and can afford salaries and benefits that
Coors cannot.
   Coors Chairman Bill Coors, addressing workers Monday in a series
of meetings at the brewery, rejected the Teamsters' claims that a
union victory would boost sales at Coors, which last year shipped
15.6 million barrels of beer and expects to sell 17 million barrels
this year.
   Teamsters Brewery Division Chief David Laughton has said the
union label would make Coors more palatable to many consumers and
boost sales as much as 10 percent.
   But Robert S. Weinberg, a beer industry analyst in St. Louis,
said the vote won't affect Coors sales one way or another.
   ``A non-union workforce is going to cost the company some
business. Similarly, a union workforce could cost some sales. The
question is: Is it a significant amount of business?'' he asked.
   The election was being conducted independently of the National
Labor Relations Board. University of Denver Prof. Tom Watkins, an
experienced labor arbitrator, was acting as the independent monitor.
   Coors reported third-quarter beer shipments of 5.57 million
barrels, up 8.1 percent from the same period a year earlier, and net
earnings for the period of $21.64 million, up marginally from a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
